{"title_page": "York Museums Trust", "text_new": "{{short description|Charity operating museums and galleries in the City of York, North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name            = York Museums Trust\n| image           = File:Yorkshire Museum.jpg\n| caption         = The Yorkshire Museum, one of the trust's sites.\n| type            = Charity\n| tax_id          =\n| registration_id = 1092466\n| founded_date    = {{Start date|2002|02|26|df=y}}\n| founder         = R I L Guthrie, M J Allen, D E Rayner, R E Rushforth\n| dissolved       = N/A\n| location        = [[York]], England\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{Coord|53.962153|-1.089498|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins         = Created by City of York Council to manage the city's museums and galleries\n| key_people      = Chairman Sir [[John Lawton (biologist)|John Lawton]] <br> Chief Executive [[Reyahn King]]\n| area_served     = [[Yorkshire]]\n| products        =\n| services        = Operating York's city-owned museums and galleries\n| focus           = \n| mission         = \"Our Mission is to cherish the collections, buildings and gardens entrusted to us, presenting and interpreting them as a stimulus for learning, a provocation to curiosity and a source of inspiration and enjoyment for all.\"\n| method          = \n| revenue         =\n| disbursed       =\n| expenses        =\n| endowment       =\n| num_volunteers  =352 (2016)<ref name='2016Rep'>{{cite report |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/YMGT-Report-and-Financial-Statements-YE-31.03.2016.compressed.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2016 |date=2016 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n| num_employees   =\n| num_members     =\n| affiliations    =\n| subsid          =\n| owner           =\n| motto           =\n| formerly        =\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk|yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk}}\n| footnotes       =\n}}\n\n'''York Museums Trust''' (YMT) is the charity responsible for operating some key museums and galleries in [[York]], England. The trust was founded in 2002 to run York's museums on behalf of the [[York#Governance|City of York Council]].<ref name=HistoryPage>{{cite web|title=History |url=http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |work=York Museums Trust website |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=14 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201063851/http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |archivedate=1 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name=YorkPress>{{cite news|title=Brave new world for museums in York |url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/archive/2002/08/01/7922839.Brave_new_world_for_museums_in_York/ |accessdate=15 October 2013 |newspaper=The York Press |date=1 August 2002 }}</ref> It has seen an increase in annual footfall of 254,000 to the venues since its foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=City of York Council |accessdate=24 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918074306/http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |archivedate=18 September 2013 }}</ref> In both 2016 and 2017 it saw its annual visitors numbers reach 500,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/York-Museums-Trust-Annual-Report-31-March-2018.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2018 |date=2018 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sites==\nThe trust runs four cultural venues and a garden.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:The Yorkshire Museum, York - geograph.org.uk - 885952.jpg|The Yorkshire Museum\nFile:York Museum Gardens.jpg|York Museum Gardens\nFile:Castle Museum York.JPG|The Castle Museum\nFile:York City Art Gallery.JPG|York City Art Gallery\nFile:Spire of St Mary, York.JPG|St Mary's (contemporary art space)\n</gallery>\n\n===The Yorkshire Museum===\n\n{{main|Yorkshire Museum}}\n\nThis is the historic county museum displaying collections inherited from the [[Yorkshire Philosophical Society]] and acting as a regional collecting museum.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://artuk.org/visit/venues/yorkshire-museum-3652 |work= [[Art UK]] | title= Galleries: Yorkshire Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Museum Gardens===\n{{main|York Museum Gardens}}\n\nThe Museum Gardens are a botanical garden containing the [[Yorkshire Museum]] and [[St Mary's Abbey, York|St Mary's Abbey]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.plantnetwork.org/directory/yrk.htm |title=York Museum Gardens |work= PlantNetwork: The Plant Collections Network of Britain and Ireland (2005) | publisher= plantnetwork.org | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Castle Museum===\n{{main|York Castle Museum}}\n\nThe Castle Museum is a social history museum housed in two former prison buildings.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/visit/venues/york-castle-museum-3651 |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Castle Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Art Gallery===\n{{main|York Art Gallery}}\n\nYork's Art Gallery has a large collection of paintings and an internationally important collection of studio ceramics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-14976861|title=Anthony Shaw ceramics collection loaned to York Art Gallery|date=19 September 2011|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=24 October 2013}}</ref> In 2012 the trust obtained \u00a37 million of funding for major refurbishment of the gallery.<ref name=\"BBC Redevelopment\">{{cite news|title=York Art Gallery \u00a38m refurbishment to begin in new year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-20851073|accessdate=28 October 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=27 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===York St Mary's===\n{{main|St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York}}\n\nYork St Mary's is a contemporary art space in the deconsecrated church of [[St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York|St Mary's, Castlegate]].<ref name=StMarysArt>{{cite web|title=Welcome to York St Marys |url=http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/yorkstmarys.aspx |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017100232/http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/YorkStMarys.aspx |archivedate=17 October 2013 }}</ref>\nThe first use of the space was a joint exhibition by a number of artists, but since 2005 St Mary's has hosted installations by individuals, which are changed on a regular basis. The first of these commissions, inspired by the medieval building itself, was a textile work by Caroline Broadhead called ''Breathing Spaces''. This was followed by ''Echo'', a work by Susie MacMurray.\nIn 2012, Laura Belem created ''The Temple of a Thousand Bells'', which used individually-made clear glass bells in a composition combining bell chimes with a narrative describing how a temple sinks into the sea, silencing the music of a thousand bells.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.jorvik.co.uk/st-marys-castlegate/ |work= Jorvik an illustrated guide to York |  title=   St Mary\u2019s Church, Castlegate |publisher= jorvik.co.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |work=Events Arts & Culture |title=Installation: The Temple of a Thousand Bells |publisher=yourlocallink.co.uk |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031102707/http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |archivedate=31 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nThe Trust is primarily funded through the City of York Council and the Arts Council. The Trust also derives substantial revenue from admission charges and other income sources. Total funding and income for 2013/14 is expected to be \u00a35.85 Million.<ref name=fplan>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk/assets/aboutus/ymt%20forward%20plan%202012-18.pdf \n |pages=4 \n |work=York Museums Trust \n |title=Forward Plan 2012 - 2018 \n |publisher=yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk \n |accessdate=28 October 2013 \n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |work=National portfolio organisations |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=Arts Council England |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010194919/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |archivedate=10 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Middleham Jewel, obverse - hi-res YORYM 1991 43.jpg|thumb|<center>Middleham Jewel</center>]]\n\nOver 1000 nationally important paintings held by the Trust have been made available online as part of a cooperative project with the [[BBC]] and the [[Public Catalogue Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust  |work= [[Art UK]] |title= More about York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\nA number of objects with a Yorkshire connection and held by the Trust were included in the BBC History of the World project, including the [[Middleham Jewel]], the [[York helmet]], and a tin of [[Rowntree's]] cocoa from [[Ernest Shackleton]]\u2019s unsuccessful [[Nimrod expedition]] to the [[South Pole]].<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA|work= A History of the World | title= Middleham Jewel  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA |work= A History of the World | title= York Helmet  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/FPpsDoamQd24kvF7Hj0Axw |work= A History of the World | title= Shackleton's tin of Rowntree's Cocoa |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n* In 2009 jointly acquired with the [[British Museum]] the [[Vale of York Hoard]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8254865.stm|title=Getting the most out of treasure|date=17 September 2009|work=BBC News|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> a Viking treasure hoard valued at over \u00a31,000,000.<ref>In 2007 the Whelans had been quoted as saying that a conservative estimate for the value of the hoard was about [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]750,000.({{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/6906107.stm |title=Viking treasure hoard uncovered | work=BBC | date=19 July 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2013}})</ref>\n*An exhibition in 2011 of [[David Hockney]]\u2019s largest landscape painting ''[[Bigger Trees Near Warter]]'' was the most well attended since the Trust had taken over the York Art gallery in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/york/hi/people_and_places/arts_and_culture/newsid_9403000/9403395.stm  |work= York - Arts and Culture | title= Hockney's largest painting pulls the crowds in York  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2012 the Trust successfully raised enough money to retain one of a pair of Iron Age gold [[torc]]s that had been found in [[Towton]], [[North Yorkshire]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-16831708|work= BBC News York | title= Iron Age gold bracelet to stay at Yorkshire Museum  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2013 the Trust in conjunction with the BBC organised a ''[[Stargazing Live]]'' event at the York Observatory in the York museum gardens.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.york.ac.uk/news-and-events/features/stargazing-live-2013/ |work= BBC Stargazing Live 2013 |authorlink=University of York | title= University helps local community reach for the stars |publisher= york.ac.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2014 an exhibition at York Castle Museum focussed on the changes brought about by the First World War, in the centenary year of the start of the conflict.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-23231831|work= BBC News York | title= York Castle Museum lottery grant funds WWI exhibition |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2020 the Trust announced that it was closing all of its sites because of government advice regarding the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.minsterfm.com/news/local/3063896/coronavirus---wednesday-18-march-local-updates/ |title=CORONAVIRUS - Wednesday 18 March local updates |publisher=[[Minster FM]] |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk York Museums Trust] - official site\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Organisations based in York]]\n[[Category:Museum organizations]]\n[[Category:York Museums Trust| ]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument museums in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Charity operating museums and galleries in the City of York, North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name            = York Museums Trust\n| image           = File:Yorkshire Museum.jpg\n| caption         = The Yorkshire Museum, one of the trust's sites.\n| type            = Charity\n| tax_id          =\n| registration_id = 1092466\n| founded_date    = {{Start date|2002|02|26|df=y}}\n| founder         = R I L Guthrie, M J Allen, D E Rayner, R E Rushforth\n| dissolved       = N/A\n| location        = [[York]], England\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{Coord|53.962153|-1.089498|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins         = Created by City of York Council to manage the city's museums and galleries\n| key_people      = Chairman Sir [[John Lawton (biologist)|John Lawton]] <br> Chief Executive [[Reyahn King]]\n| area_served     = [[Yorkshire]]\n| products        =\n| services        = Operating York's city-owned museums and galleries\n| focus           = \n| mission         = \"Our Mission is to cherish the collections, buildings and gardens entrusted to us, presenting and interpreting them as a stimulus for learning, a provocation to curiosity and a source of inspiration and enjoyment for all.\"\n| method          = \n| revenue         =\n| disbursed       =\n| expenses        =\n| endowment       =\n| num_volunteers  =352 (2016)<ref name='2016Rep'>{{cite report |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/YMGT-Report-and-Financial-Statements-YE-31.03.2016.compressed.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2016 |date=2016 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n| num_employees   =\n| num_members     =\n| affiliations    =\n| subsid          =\n| owner           =\n| motto           =\n| formerly        =\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk|yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk}}\n| footnotes       =\n}}\n\n'''York Museums Trust''' (YMT) is the charity responsible for operating some key museums and galleries in [[York]], England. The trust was founded in 2002 to run York's museums on behalf of the [[York#Governance|City of York Council]].<ref name=HistoryPage>{{cite web|title=History |url=http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |work=York Museums Trust website |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=14 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201063851/http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |archivedate=1 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name=YorkPress>{{cite news|title=Brave new world for museums in York |url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/archive/2002/08/01/7922839.Brave_new_world_for_museums_in_York/ |accessdate=15 October 2013 |newspaper=The York Press |date=1 August 2002 }}</ref> It has seen an increase in annual footfall of 254,000 to the venues since its foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=City of York Council |accessdate=24 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918074306/http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |archivedate=18 September 2013 }}</ref> In both 2016 and 2017 it saw its annual visitors numbers reach 500,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/York-Museums-Trust-Annual-Report-31-March-2018.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2018 |date=2018 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sites==\nThe trust runs four cultural venues and a garden.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:The Yorkshire Museum, York - geograph.org.uk - 885952.jpg|The Yorkshire Museum\nFile:York Museum Gardens.jpg|York Museum Gardens\nFile:Castle Museum York.JPG|The Castle Museum\nFile:York City Art Gallery.JPG|York City Art Gallery\nFile:Spire of St Mary, York.JPG|St Mary's (contemporary art space)\n</gallery>\n\n===The Yorkshire Museum===\n\n{{main|Yorkshire Museum}}\n\nThis is the historic county museum displaying collections inherited from the [[Yorkshire Philosophical Society]] and acting as a regional collecting museum.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://artuk.org/visit/venues/yorkshire-museum-3652 |work= [[Art UK]] | title= Galleries: Yorkshire Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Museum Gardens===\n{{main|York Museum Gardens}}\n\nThe Museum Gardens are a botanical garden containing the [[Yorkshire Museum]] and [[St Mary's Abbey, York|St Mary's Abbey]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.plantnetwork.org/directory/yrk.htm |title=York Museum Gardens |work= PlantNetwork: The Plant Collections Network of Britain and Ireland (2005) | publisher= plantnetwork.org | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Castle Museum===\n{{main|York Castle Museum}}\n\nThe Castle Museum is a social history museum housed in two former prison buildings.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/visit/venues/york-castle-museum-3651 |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Castle Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Art Gallery===\n{{main|York Art Gallery}}\n\nYork's Art Gallery has a large collection of paintings and an internationally important collection of studio ceramics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-14976861|title=Anthony Shaw ceramics collection loaned to York Art Gallery|date=19 September 2011|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=24 October 2013}}</ref> In 2012 the trust obtained \u00a37 million of funding for major refurbishment of the gallery.<ref name=\"BBC Redevelopment\">{{cite news|title=York Art Gallery \u00a38m refurbishment to begin in new year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-20851073|accessdate=28 October 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=27 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===York St Mary's===\n{{main|St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York}}\n\nYork St Mary's is a contemporary art space in the deconsecrated church of [[St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York|St Mary's, Castlegate]].<ref name=StMarysArt>{{cite web|title=Welcome to York St Marys |url=http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/yorkstmarys.aspx |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017100232/http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/YorkStMarys.aspx |archivedate=17 October 2013 }}</ref>\nThe first use of the space was a joint exhibition by a number of artists, but since 2005 St Mary's has hosted installations by individuals, which are changed on a regular basis. The first of these commissions, inspired by the medieval building itself, was a textile work by Caroline Broadhead called ''Breathing Spaces''. This was followed by ''Echo'', a work by Susie MacMurray.\nIn 2012, Laura Belem created ''The Temple of a Thousand Bells'', which used individually-made clear glass bells in a composition combining bell chimes with a narrative describing how a temple sinks into the sea, silencing the music of a thousand bells.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.jorvik.co.uk/st-marys-castlegate/ |work= Jorvik an illustrated guide to York |  title=   St Mary\u2019s Church, Castlegate |publisher= jorvik.co.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |work=Events Arts & Culture |title=Installation: The Temple of a Thousand Bells |publisher=yourlocallink.co.uk |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031102707/http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |archivedate=31 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nThe Trust is primarily funded through the City of York Council and the Arts Council. The Trust also derives substantial revenue from admission charges and other income sources. Total funding and income for 2013/14 is expected to be \u00a35.85 Million.<ref name=fplan>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk/assets/aboutus/ymt%20forward%20plan%202012-18.pdf \n |pages=4 \n |work=York Museums Trust \n |title=Forward Plan 2012 - 2018 \n |publisher=yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk \n |accessdate=28 October 2013 \n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |work=National portfolio organisations |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=Arts Council England |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010194919/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |archivedate=10 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Middleham Jewel, obverse - hi-res YORYM 1991 43.jpg|thumb|<center>Middleham Jewel</center>]]\n\nOver 1000 nationally important paintings held by the Trust have been made available online as part of a cooperative project with the [[BBC]] and the [[Public Catalogue Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust  |work= [[Art UK]] |title= More about York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\nA number of objects with a Yorkshire connection and held by the Trust were included in the BBC History of the World project, including the [[Middleham Jewel]], the [[York helmet]], and a tin of [[Rowntree's]] cocoa from [[Ernest Shackleton]]\u2019s unsuccessful [[Nimrod expedition]] to the [[South Pole]].<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA|work= A History of the World | title= Middleham Jewel  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA |work= A History of the World | title= York Helmet  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/FPpsDoamQd24kvF7Hj0Axw |work= A History of the World | title= Shackleton's tin of Rowntree's Cocoa |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n* In 2009 jointly acquired with the [[British Museum]] the [[Vale of York Hoard]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8254865.stm|title=Getting the most out of treasure|date=17 September 2009|work=BBC news|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> a Viking treasure hoard valued at over \u00a31,000,000.<ref>In 2007 the Whelans had been quoted as saying that a conservative estimate for the value of the hoard was about [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]750,000.({{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/6906107.stm |title=Viking treasure hoard uncovered | work=BBC | date=19 July 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2013}})</ref>\n*An exhibition in 2011 of [[David Hockney]]\u2019s largest landscape painting ''[[Bigger Trees Near Warter]]'' was the most well attended since the Trust had taken over the York Art gallery in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/york/hi/people_and_places/arts_and_culture/newsid_9403000/9403395.stm  |work= York - Arts and Culture | title= Hockney's largest painting pulls the crowds in York  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2012 the Trust successfully raised enough money to retain one of a pair of Iron Age gold [[torc]]s that had been found in [[Towton]], [[North Yorkshire]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-16831708|work= BBC News York | title= Iron Age gold bracelet to stay at Yorkshire Museum  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2013 the Trust in conjunction with the BBC organised a ''[[Stargazing Live]]'' event at the York Observatory in the York museum gardens.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.york.ac.uk/news-and-events/features/stargazing-live-2013/ |work= BBC Stargazing Live 2013 |authorlink=University of York | title= University helps local community reach for the stars |publisher= york.ac.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2014 an exhibition at York Castle Museum focussed on the changes brought about by the First World War, in the centenary year of the start of the conflict.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-23231831|work= BBC News York | title= York Castle Museum lottery grant funds WWI exhibition |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2020 the Trust announced that it was closing all of its sites because of government advice regarding the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.minsterfm.com/news/local/3063896/coronavirus---wednesday-18-march-local-updates/ |title=CORONAVIRUS - Wednesday 18 March local updates |publisher=[[Minster FM]] |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk York Museums Trust] - official site\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Organisations based in York]]\n[[Category:Museum organizations]]\n[[Category:York Museums Trust| ]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument museums in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/York_Museums_Trust"}
{"title_page": "Sid Waddell", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sid Waddell\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date |df=yes|1940|08|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Alnwick]], [[Northumberland]], England\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2012|08|11|1940|08|10}}\n| death_place        = [[Harrogate]], England\n| nationality        = British\n| other_names        = \n| education          = [[The King Edward VI School, Morpeth]]\n| known_for          = [[Darts]] commentary<br/>One liners\n| occupation         = Sports commentator, television presenter\n| children           = 5\n| years_active       = 1972\u20132012\n}}\n\n'''Sid Waddell''' (10 August 1940 \u2013 11 August 2012) was an [[English people|English]] [[sports commentator]] and television personality. He was nicknamed the ''''Voice of Darts'''' due to his fame as a darts commentator, and worked for [[Granada Television|Granada]], [[Yorkshire Television|Yorkshire]], [[BBC]] and [[Sky Sports]]. Due to his joke telling skills he was also nicknamed the '''Thief of Bad Gags''', firstly by [[Dave Lanning]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Chadband |first=Ian |title=There's Only One Word for Waddell: Just Magic |url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1G1-81254489/there-s-only-one-word-for-waddell-just-magic |accessdate=22 December 2014 |work=London Evening Standard |date=3 January 2002}}</ref> He was nominated for two prestigious awards for his work, and published several books.\n\n==Early life==\nThe son of a Northumberland miner, he attended [[The King Edward VI School, Morpeth|King Edward VI School]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.morpethherald.co.uk/community/remembering-sid-the-voice-of-darts-1-4836949 | title = Remembering Sid, the voice of darts }}</ref> [[Morpeth, Northumberland|Morpeth]], and he went on to obtain a scholarship to [[St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/darts/19232679 | title=Sid Waddell: The life and times of one of sport's greatest voices}}</ref> where he graduated with an upper second degree in Modern History. At Cambridge, Waddell played rugby for St John's, and the Cambridge University LX Club, the rugby second team. Injury brought him to darts and he started the inter-college darts competition. St John's lost in the final of this in 1961 to a team of trainee vicars from [[Selwyn College, Cambridge|Selwyn College]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Granada and Yorkshire===\nWaddell went into academia for a few years in 1962. He joined the Social Studies Department at [[Durham University]] and assisted the Professors of Politics and Economics in writing their books. He toyed with the idea of writing a book on trade unions but settled for folk singing in a duo with Charles E. Hall called the Gravyboatmen. They played on BBC ''Tonight'' and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] locally. In 1966, Waddell joined [[Granada Television]] working with [[Michael Parkinson]] on local news programmes. In 1968, he moved to [[Yorkshire Television]]. Between 1968 and 1974, Waddell was a producer for over 600 editions of local news programme, [[Calendar (News)|''Calendar'']]. He also devised the ITV network children's series ''[[The Flaxton Boys]]'' a historical adventure series that ran for three years from 1969.\n\n1972 was a big year for darts as ITV broadcast the [[News of the World Darts Championship]] for the first time. Waddell was an observer at [[Alexandra Palace]] during the 1972 News of the World Championship and was particularly impressed with the play and character of the eventual finalist, Welshman [[Alan Evans]], who beat reigning champion Dennis Filkins in the semi finals with a fiery display. Also in 1972, Waddell created the show ''[[The Indoor League]]'', which featured various pub games including [[darts]], [[Blackball (pool)|pool]], [[bar billiards]], [[Skittles (sport)|bar skittles]], [[Table football]] (aka foosball), [[arm wrestling]] and [[shove ha'penny]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/w.htm |title=Profile from Waddell's web site |publisher=Sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com |accessdate=11 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20060916170648/http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/w.htm |archivedate=16 September 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''The Indoor League'' was only shown on Yorkshire Television in 1972 but went national on the ITV network from 1973 to 1977, although Waddell had left ITV by the last series of the programme.\n\n===BBC===\nIn 1976, Waddell switched to the BBC and his experience with televised darts helped him to become one of the commentators on the first [[World Professional Darts Championship]] when it began in 1978. Waddell stayed with the BBC until 1994, commentating on all darts events covered by the BBC from 1978 to 1994, with his last darts commentary on the BBC being the first four sets of the [[1994 BDO World Darts Championship|1994 BDO World Championship Final]] between [[John Part]] and [[Bobby George]].\n\nDuring his time with the BBC, Waddell penned ten episodes of a successful children's television series, ''[[Jossy's Giants]]'' in 1986. He was also the writer of two series of another children's show ''Sloggers'' which ran from 1994 to 1996. His credits also include working with the eccentric scientist [[Magnus Pyke]] and he was [[Alan Whicker]]'s producer on ''Whicker's Women'' in 1972. He worked on the ''[[Russell Harty]] Show'', and in 1993 did a series for [[Tyne Tees Television]] called ''Waddell's World'' in which he was a butler to a posh Tweeddale family, a caravanner and on the dole.\n\nHe made one performance as the \"Voice of the Balls\" on the ''National Lottery Red Alert'' on BBC in 1999. He said he was sacked for being \"too [[Geordie]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/pre.htm |title=Waddell's television career |publisher=Sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com |accessdate=11 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070928003333/http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/pre.htm |archivedate=28 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Sky Sports===\nFrom 1994, Waddell became an independently employed commentator, but mainly associated with his work with [[Sky Sports]]. The first darts tournament he commentated on for Sky Sports was the [[1994 World Matchplay (darts)|1994 World Matchplay]] at the [[Winter Gardens, Blackpool]], in August 1994. For the next 17 years, he worked continuously as a commentator on all darts tournaments televised by Sky Sports. In September 2011, Waddell was diagnosed with bowel cancer. Despite this diagnosis and undergoing treatment, he managed to come back to the darts commentary box in the spring of 2012 during some [[2012 Premier League Darts|Premier League]] nights.\n\nAfter commentating on a sporadic basis during the [[2012 Premier League Darts|2012 Premier League]], Waddell did not commentate at either the [[2012 UK Open]] nor the [[2012 World Matchplay (darts)|2012 World Matchplay]] prior to his death on 11 August 2012. Waddell's last darts commentary came in the 2012 [[2012 Premier League Darts|Premier League]] final between [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Phil Taylor]] and [[Simon Whitlock]] on 17 May, where Phil Taylor won the match 10-7 to take the 2012 Premier League title, although Waddell only commentated on the first part of the match; his last commentary contributing to a full match came in the same evening in the semi final match between [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Phil Taylor]] and [[James Wade]], Taylor won the match 8\u20136. The World championship trophy has been renamed eponymously in his honour, in recognition of his contribution to darts.\n\nWaddell's last interview came in June 2012, where he discussed his life, darts commentary, pool commentary and his bowel cancer. This interview was aired on Sky Sports on 16 August 2012, five days after his death, as a tribute entitled: ''Sid Waddell \u2013 A Life in His Own Words''.\n\n===Pool commentary and other works===\nBesides darts, Waddell commentated on numerous other sporting events produced by [[Sky Sports]] and/or [[Matchroom Sport]] over the years. He regularly commentated on the four annual [[nine-ball]] [[Pool (cue sports)|pool]] events on which the two companies collaborated ([[WPA World Nine-ball Championship|World Pool Championship]]; [[World Pool Masters]]; [[World Pool League]]; and [[Mosconi Cup]]), particularly between the years of 1999\u20132003. However, as these events began to be hosted further away from the UK, Waddell gradually withdrew from the sport. He is remembered for coining the term \"Golden Break\", meaning when the 9-ball is pocketed directly from the break, giving the breaking player an immediate win.\n\nIn 2004, he was the commentator for the British game show ''House of Games'' in which two families competed in various household based challenges.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0420411/|IMDb page</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he began to host Sid Waddell's Wrestling Show on [[ESPN Classic (UK)|ESPN Classic]]. This show featured edited versions of matches from the days of [[World of Sport Wrestling|World of Sport]] Wrestling.\n\nIn 2007, Waddell and [[Eric Bristow]] recorded a series of ''Bellies and Bullseyes'' darts programmes about the World Darts Championship from 1978 until 1990 for ESPN Classic, which were later broadcast on the channel in December 2007.\n\n===Awards===\nWaddell was twice nominated for TV awards. He was up for [[BAFTA]] best director in 1992 for a documentary in the ''Ipso Facto'' series, and in 1994 he was nominated for best scriptwriter in the [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] awards for his children's cricket series ''Sloggers''.\n\n==Publications==\nHe wrote eleven published books, including biographies of [[John Lowe]], [[Jocky Wilson]] and [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Phil Taylor]]. His book ''Bellies and Bullseyes'' was short listed for the British Sports Book Award for 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalsportingclub.co.uk/BritishSportsBookAwards08Nominate.htm |title=British Sports Book Awards |publisher=Nationalsportingclub.co.uk |accessdate=11 February 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080702232944/http://www.nationalsportingclub.co.uk/BritishSportsBookAwards08Nominate.htm |archivedate = 2 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nHis racy 1973 novel ''Bedroll Bella'' about a Geordie groupie, was banned by [[WH Smiths]] and [[John Menzies]]. In 2009 he published a memoir of his boyhood in a Geordie pit village ''The Road Back Home''.\n\n==Personal life==\nWaddell was married to Irene. Waddell was a fervent [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] supporter, and lived in [[Pudsey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3048278.ece |title=Man who delivered whole new language to sport remains as sharp as an arrow |work=The Times |location=London |date=14 December 2007 |first=Giles |last=Smith |accessdate=11 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510014005/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3048278.ece |archivedate=10 May 2009 }}</ref> In September 2011, it was announced that Waddell had been diagnosed with [[bowel cancer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/darts/15012394.stm|title=Commentator Sid Waddell diagnosed with bowel cancer|work=BBC News|date=21 September 2011|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe succumbed to bowel cancer on 11 August 2012, the day after his 72nd birthday, In Harrogate, North Yorkshire.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/12/sid-waddell-dies-aged-72 | work = [[The Guardian]] | accessdate = 12 August 2012 | title = Sid Waddell dies aged 72 | location=London | date=12 August 2012}}</ref> Following his death, the decision was made to rename the [[PDC World Darts Championship]] trophy the Sid Waddell trophy from 2013.<ref>[http://news.sky.com/story/972017/world-darts-trophy-named-after-waddell World Darts Trophy Named After Waddell]. Sky News (13 August 2012).</ref> Waddell's funeral was held in Leeds on 22 August 2012. Before Waddell's funeral he was cremated earlier in the day in a private ceremony.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-19332779 | work = [[BBC News]] | accessdate = 22 August 2012 | title = Darts commentator Sid Waddell's funeral held in Leeds | date=22 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n\n{{over-quotation|date=January 2019}}\n<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/12/sid-waddell-quotes | title=Sid Waddell's quotes: 13 of the best | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=23 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/darts/9470619/Sid-Waddell-his-best-darting-one-liners-and-quips-behind-the-microphone.html| title=Sid Waddell: his best darting one-liners and quips behind the microphone| newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/08/13/sid-waddell-darts-dies-greatest-quotes_n_1771845.html | title=Sid Waddell, Darts Commentator Dies: Here Are His Greatest Quotes | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | accessdate=23 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sid Waddell's most legendary lines here|url=http://www.skysports.com/darts/news/12288/8289283/remembers-sid-waddells-most-legendary-lines-here|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n{{wikiquote}}\n*\"It's the greatest comeback since [[Lazarus of Bethany|Lazarus]]\"\n*\"When [[Alexander the Great|Alexander of Macedonia]] was 33, he cried salt tears because there were no more worlds to conquer... [[Eric Bristow|Bristow's]] only 27.\"\n*\"He's burning the midnight oil at both ends!\"\n*\"They'll be rattling their clogs in Cleckheaton!\"\n*\"Even Hypotenuse would have trouble working out these angles!\"\n*\"There's only one word for that \u2013 magic darts!\"\n*\"It's like trying to pin down a kangaroo on a trampoline.\"\n*\"The atmosphere is so tense, if Elvis walked in with a portion of chips, you could hear the vinegar sizzle on them\"\n*\"He's as happy as a penguin in a microwave.\"\n*\"His eyes are bulging like the belly of a hungry chaffinch.\"\n*\"That could have landed on the pupil of a fly's eyeball\"\"\n*\"William Tell could take an apple off your head, [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Taylor]] could take out a processed pea.\"\n*\"He's moving round that pool table like [[Shawn Michaels]] after a couple of body slams.\"\n*\"In the space of three darts, he has gone from being Lee Van Cleef to the Laughing Cavalier.\"\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n | date  = 8 July 2010\n | title = The Road Back Home\n | last = Waddell\n | first = Sid\n | publisher=[[Ebury Press]]\n | isbn = 978-0-09-193223-7\n }}\n* {{cite book\n | date  = 7 August 2008\n | title = Bellies and Bullseyes\n | last = Waddell\n | first = Sid\n | publisher=[[Ebury Press]]\n | isbn = 978-0-09-191756-2\n }}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131204003930/http://www.sidwaddell.com/q.htm Classic Waddell Commentary] from Waddell's Official web site.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0905330}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waddell, Sid}}\n[[Category:Darts people]]\n[[Category:English sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:BBC sports presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Deaths from colorectal cancer]]\n[[Category:People from Alnwick]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sid Waddell\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date |df=yes|1940|08|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Alnwick]], [[Northumberland]], England\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2012|08|11|1940|08|10}}\n| death_place        = [[Harrogate]], England\n| nationality        = British\n| other_names        = \n| education          = [[The King Edward VI School, Morpeth]]\n| known_for          = [[Darts]] commentary<br/>One liners\n| occupation         = Sports commentator, television presenter\n| children           = 5\n| years_active       = 1972\u20132012\n}}\n\n'''Sid Waddell''' (10 August 1940 \u2013 11 August 2012) was an [[English people|English]] [[sports commentator]] and television personality. He was nicknamed the ''''Voice of Darts'''' due to his fame as a darts commentator, and worked for [[Granada Television|Granada]], [[Yorkshire Television|Yorkshire]], [[BBC]] and [[Sky Sports]]. Due to his joke telling skills he was also nicknamed the '''Thief of Bad Gags''', firstly by [[Dave Lanning]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Chadband |first=Ian |title=There's Only One Word for Waddell: Just Magic |url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1G1-81254489/there-s-only-one-word-for-waddell-just-magic |accessdate=22 December 2014 |work=London Evening Standard |date=3 January 2002}}</ref> He was nominated for two prestigious awards for his work, and published several books.\n\n==Early life==\nThe son of a Northumberland miner, he attended [[The King Edward VI School, Morpeth|King Edward VI School]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.morpethherald.co.uk/community/remembering-sid-the-voice-of-darts-1-4836949 | title = Remembering Sid, the voice of darts }}</ref> [[Morpeth, Northumberland|Morpeth]], and he went on to obtain a scholarship to [[St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/darts/19232679 | title=Sid Waddell: The life and times of one of sport's greatest voices}}</ref> where he graduated with an upper second degree in Modern History. At Cambridge, Waddell played rugby for St John's, and the Cambridge University LX Club, the rugby second team. Injury brought him to darts and he started the inter-college darts competition. St John's lost in the final of this in 1961 to a team of trainee vicars from [[Selwyn College, Cambridge|Selwyn College]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Granada and Yorkshire===\nWaddell went into academia for a few years in 1962. He joined the Social Studies Department at [[Durham University]] and assisted the Professors of Politics and Economics in writing their books. He toyed with the idea of writing a book on trade unions but settled for folk singing in a duo with Charles E. Hall called the Gravyboatmen. They played on BBC ''Tonight'' and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] locally. In 1966, Waddell joined [[Granada Television]] working with [[Michael Parkinson]] on local news programmes. In 1968, he moved to [[Yorkshire Television]]. Between 1968 and 1974, Waddell was a producer for over 600 editions of local news programme, [[Calendar (News)|''Calendar'']]. He also devised the ITV network children's series ''[[The Flaxton Boys]]'' a historical adventure series that ran for three years from 1969.\n\n1972 was a big year for darts as ITV broadcast the [[News of the World Darts Championship]] for the first time. Waddell was an observer at [[Alexandra Palace]] during the 1972 News of the World Championship and was particularly impressed with the play and character of the eventual finalist, Welshman [[Alan Evans]], who beat reigning champion Dennis Filkins in the semi finals with a fiery display. Also in 1972, Waddell created the show ''[[The Indoor League]]'', which featured various pub games including [[darts]], [[Blackball (pool)|pool]], [[bar billiards]], [[Skittles (sport)|bar skittles]], [[Table football]] (aka foosball), [[arm wrestling]] and [[shove ha'penny]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/w.htm |title=Profile from Waddell's web site |publisher=Sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com |accessdate=11 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20060916170648/http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/w.htm |archivedate=16 September 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''The Indoor League'' was only shown on Yorkshire Television in 1972 but went national on the ITV network from 1973 to 1977, although Waddell had left ITV by the last series of the programme.\n\n===BBC===\nIn 1976, Waddell switched to the BBC and his experience with televised darts helped him to become one of the commentators on the first [[World Professional Darts Championship]] when it began in 1978. Waddell stayed with the BBC until 1994, commentating on all darts events covered by the BBC from 1978 to 1994, with his last darts commentary on the BBC being the first four sets of the [[1994 BDO World Darts Championship|1994 BDO World Championship Final]] between [[John Part]] and [[Bobby George]].\n\nDuring his time with the BBC, Waddell penned ten episodes of a successful children's television series, ''[[Jossy's Giants]]'' in 1986. He was also the writer of two series of another children's show ''Sloggers'' which ran from 1994 to 1996. His credits also include working with the eccentric scientist [[Magnus Pyke]] and he was [[Alan Whicker]]'s producer on ''Whicker's Women'' in 1972. He worked on the ''[[Russell Harty]] Show'', and in 1993 did a series for [[Tyne Tees Television]] called ''Waddell's World'' in which he was a butler to a posh Tweeddale family, a caravanner and on the dole.\n\nHe made one performance as the \"Voice of the Balls\" on the ''National Lottery Red Alert'' on BBC in 1999. He said he was sacked for being \"too [[Geordie]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/pre.htm |title=Waddell's television career |publisher=Sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com |accessdate=11 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070928003333/http://www.sidwaddell.compsyswebdesign.com/pre.htm |archivedate=28 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Sky Sports===\nFrom 1994, Waddell became an independently employed commentator, but mainly associated with his work with [[Sky Sports]]. The first darts tournament he commentated on for Sky Sports was the [[1994 World Matchplay (darts)|1994 World Matchplay]] at the [[Winter Gardens, Blackpool]], in August 1994. For the next 17 years, he worked continuously as a commentator on all darts tournaments televised by Sky Sports. In September 2011, Waddell was diagnosed with bowel cancer. Despite this diagnosis and undergoing treatment, he managed to come back to the darts commentary box in the spring of 2012 during some [[2012 Premier League Darts|Premier League]] nights.\n\nAfter commentating on a sporadic basis during the [[2012 Premier League Darts|2012 Premier League]], Waddell did not commentate at either the [[2012 UK Open]] nor the [[2012 World Matchplay (darts)|2012 World Matchplay]] prior to his death on 11 August 2012. Waddell's last darts commentary came in the 2012 [[2012 Premier League Darts|Premier League]] final between [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Phil Taylor]] and [[Simon Whitlock]] on 17 May, where Phil Taylor won the match 10-7 to take the 2012 Premier League title, although Waddell only commentated on the first part of the match; his last commentary contributing to a full match came in the same evening in the semi final match between [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Phil Taylor]] and [[James Wade]], Taylor won the match 8\u20136. The World championship trophy has been renamed eponymously in his honour, in recognition of his contribution to darts.\n\nWaddell's last interview came in June 2012, where he discussed his life, darts commentary, pool commentary and his bowel cancer. This interview was aired on Sky Sports on 16 August 2012, five days after his death, as a tribute entitled: ''Sid Waddell \u2013 A Life in His Own Words''.\n\n===Pool commentary and other works===\nBesides darts, Waddell commentated on numerous other sporting events produced by [[Sky Sports]] and/or [[Matchroom Sport]] over the years. He regularly commentated on the four annual [[nine-ball]] [[Pool (cue sports)|pool]] events on which the two companies collaborated ([[WPA World Nine-ball Championship|World Pool Championship]]; [[World Pool Masters]]; [[World Pool League]]; and [[Mosconi Cup]]), particularly between the years of 1999\u20132003. However, as these events began to be hosted further away from the UK, Waddell gradually withdrew from the sport. He is remembered for coining the term \"Golden Break\", meaning when the 9-ball is pocketed directly from the break, giving the breaking player an immediate win.\n\nIn 2004, he was the commentator for the British game show ''House of Games'' in which two families competed in various household based challenges.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0420411/|IMDb page</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he began to host Sid Waddell's Wrestling Show on [[ESPN Classic (UK)|ESPN Classic]]. This show featured edited versions of matches from the days of [[World of Sport Wrestling|World of Sport]] Wrestling.\n\nIn 2007, Waddell and [[Eric Bristow]] recorded a series of ''Bellies and Bullseyes'' darts programmes about the World Darts Championship from 1978 until 1990 for ESPN Classic, which were later broadcast on the channel in December 2007.\n\n===Awards===\nWaddell was twice nominated for TV awards. He was up for [[BAFTA]] best director in 1992 for a documentary in the ''Ipso Facto'' series, and in 1994 he was nominated for best scriptwriter in the [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] awards for his children's cricket series ''Sloggers''.\n\n==Publications==\nHe wrote eleven published books, including biographies of [[John Lowe]], [[Jocky Wilson]] and [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Phil Taylor]]. His book ''Bellies and Bullseyes'' was short listed for the British Sports Book Award for 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalsportingclub.co.uk/BritishSportsBookAwards08Nominate.htm |title=British Sports Book Awards |publisher=Nationalsportingclub.co.uk |accessdate=11 February 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080702232944/http://www.nationalsportingclub.co.uk/BritishSportsBookAwards08Nominate.htm |archivedate = 2 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nHis racy 1973 novel ''Bedroll Bella'' about a Geordie groupie, was banned by [[WH Smiths]] and [[John Menzies]]. In 2009 he published a memoir of his boyhood in a Geordie pit village ''The Road Back Home''.\n\n==Personal life==\nWaddell was married to Irene. Waddell was a fervent [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] supporter, and lived in [[Pudsey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3048278.ece |title=Man who delivered whole new language to sport remains as sharp as an arrow |work=The Times |location=London |date=14 December 2007 |first=Giles |last=Smith |accessdate=11 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510014005/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3048278.ece |archivedate=10 May 2009 }}</ref> In September 2011, it was announced that Waddell had been diagnosed with [[bowel cancer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/darts/15012394.stm|title=Commentator Sid Waddell diagnosed with bowel cancer|work=BBC news|date=21 September 2011|accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe succumbed to bowel cancer on 11 August 2012, the day after his 72nd birthday, In Harrogate, North Yorkshire.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/12/sid-waddell-dies-aged-72 | work = [[The Guardian]] | accessdate = 12 August 2012 | title = Sid Waddell dies aged 72 | location=London | date=12 August 2012}}</ref> Following his death, the decision was made to rename the [[PDC World Darts Championship]] trophy the Sid Waddell trophy from 2013.<ref>[http://news.sky.com/story/972017/world-darts-trophy-named-after-waddell World Darts Trophy Named After Waddell]. Sky News (13 August 2012).</ref> Waddell's funeral was held in Leeds on 22 August 2012. Before Waddell's funeral he was cremated earlier in the day in a private ceremony.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-19332779 | work = [[BBC News]] | accessdate = 22 August 2012 | title = Darts commentator Sid Waddell's funeral held in Leeds | date=22 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n\n{{over-quotation|date=January 2019}}\n<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/12/sid-waddell-quotes | title=Sid Waddell's quotes: 13 of the best | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=23 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/darts/9470619/Sid-Waddell-his-best-darting-one-liners-and-quips-behind-the-microphone.html| title=Sid Waddell: his best darting one-liners and quips behind the microphone| newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/08/13/sid-waddell-darts-dies-greatest-quotes_n_1771845.html | title=Sid Waddell, Darts Commentator Dies: Here Are His Greatest Quotes | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | accessdate=23 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sid Waddell's most legendary lines here|url=http://www.skysports.com/darts/news/12288/8289283/remembers-sid-waddells-most-legendary-lines-here|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n{{wikiquote}}\n*\"It's the greatest comeback since [[Lazarus of Bethany|Lazarus]]\"\n*\"When [[Alexander the Great|Alexander of Macedonia]] was 33, he cried salt tears because there were no more worlds to conquer... [[Eric Bristow|Bristow's]] only 27.\"\n*\"He's burning the midnight oil at both ends!\"\n*\"They'll be rattling their clogs in Cleckheaton!\"\n*\"Even Hypotenuse would have trouble working out these angles!\"\n*\"There's only one word for that \u2013 magic darts!\"\n*\"It's like trying to pin down a kangaroo on a trampoline.\"\n*\"The atmosphere is so tense, if Elvis walked in with a portion of chips, you could hear the vinegar sizzle on them\"\n*\"He's as happy as a penguin in a microwave.\"\n*\"His eyes are bulging like the belly of a hungry chaffinch.\"\n*\"That could have landed on the pupil of a fly's eyeball\"\"\n*\"William Tell could take an apple off your head, [[Phil Taylor (darts player)|Taylor]] could take out a processed pea.\"\n*\"He's moving round that pool table like [[Shawn Michaels]] after a couple of body slams.\"\n*\"In the space of three darts, he has gone from being Lee Van Cleef to the Laughing Cavalier.\"\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n | date  = 8 July 2010\n | title = The Road Back Home\n | last = Waddell\n | first = Sid\n | publisher=[[Ebury Press]]\n | isbn = 978-0-09-193223-7\n }}\n* {{cite book\n | date  = 7 August 2008\n | title = Bellies and Bullseyes\n | last = Waddell\n | first = Sid\n | publisher=[[Ebury Press]]\n | isbn = 978-0-09-191756-2\n }}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131204003930/http://www.sidwaddell.com/q.htm Classic Waddell Commentary] from Waddell's Official web site.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0905330}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waddell, Sid}}\n[[Category:Darts people]]\n[[Category:English sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:BBC sports presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Deaths from colorectal cancer]]\n[[Category:People from Alnwick]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sid_Waddell"}
{"title_page": "Jonas \u00c5kerlund", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{about|the director|the politician|Jonas \u00c5kerlund (politician)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Jonas \u00c5kerlund\n| image                     = Jonas Akerlund.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| caption                   = \u00c5kerlund in 2012\n| birth_name                = Hans Uno Jonas \u00c5kerlund\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1965|11|10}}\n| birth_place               = [[Bromma]], [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]\n| occupation                = {{flatlist|\n* Film director\n* screenwriter\n* music video director\n* drummer\n}}\n| years_active              = 1983\u2013present\n| death_date      =\n| spouse                    = Bea \u00c5kerlund\n| website                   =\n}}\n\n'''Hans Uno Jonas \u00c5kerlund''' ({{IPA-sv|h\u0251\u02d0ns \u02c8\u0289\u030c\u02d0n\u028a \u02c8j\u00fb\u02d0nas \u02c8\u00f4\u02d0k\u025b\u02cc\u026d\u0275nd|lang}}; born 10 November 1965) is a Swedish film director, screenwriter, music video director, and drummer. His video for [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s song \"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\" won a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video, Short Form]], and a record seven awards at [[1998 MTV Video Music Awards]], including the [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]].\n\nIn 2008 he won another Grammy Award, this time around for \"Best Long Form Music Video\" for another work with Madonna \u2013 directing \"The Confessions Tour\" DVD. In 2014 he won this Grammy Award again (that meanwhile changed the name to \"Best Music Film\"), this time for \"Live Kisses\" [[Paul McCartney]] concert film. Jonas \u00c5kerlund, [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]] and Bob Smeaton are the only directors to have won this award twice sharing the record for most wins in this category (check here all winners and nominees of [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film]]).\n\n==Career==\n\u00c5kerlund was a member of the Swedish [[black metal]] band [[Bathory (band)|Bathory]] from 1983 to 1984. He also directed Candlemass' first video \"Bewitched\". He first found fame as the main video director for [[Roxette]]. In 1997, he directed the acclaimed video for [[The Prodigy]]'s \"[[Smack My Bitch Up]]\", which sparked controversy due to its depiction of drug use, violence, and nudity. In 1998, he worked with [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for the song \"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\", and has since worked with acts such as [[Metallica]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[U2]], [[Blink-182]], [[P!nk]], [[Rammstein]], [[Britney Spears]], and [[Lady Gaga]]. He directed the music video for the [[Smashing Pumpkins]]' \"Try, Try, Try\", from which a short film entitled ''Try'' was spawned. He was also the designer and photographer for the [[Roxette]] album ''[[Room Service (Roxette album)|Room Service]]'' in 2001. In 2002, his first full-length film, ''[[Spun]]'', debuted.\n\n\u00c5kerlund directed commercials for Swedish clothing retailer MQ and the re-imagining of the Devo song \"Watch Us Work It\" used in [[Dell Computers]] commercials. He is a long-time collaborator of Madonna, having worked on such music videos as \"Music\", \"American Life\" (which was pulled due to its graphic content and the [[Iraq War]]), and \"Jump\". He also directed her documentary film ''[[I'm Going to Tell You a Secret]]'' and her concert special ''[[The Confessions Tour (album)|The Confessions Tour: Live from London]]''. Among his more recent works were the controversial pornographic music video for [[Rammstein]]'s \"[[Pussy (Rammstein song)|Pussy]]\", the video for the song \"[[Telephone (song)|Telephone]]\" by [[Lady Gaga]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9]], \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\" by [[Maroon 5]] and [[Christina Aguilera]], and [[Duran Duran]]'s single \"Girl Panic!\".<ref name=\"MTV gaga\">{{cite web|last=Wigler|first=Josh|title=The Man Behind Lady Gaga's 'Telephone' Video: Jonas Akerlund|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1633818/man-behind-lady-gagas-telephone-video-jonas-akerlund.jhtml|publisher=MTV|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n\u00c5kerlund's second movie, ''[[Small Apartments]]'', went direct to DVD.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|last=\u00c5kerlund|first=Jonas|title=Small Apartments|date=1 March 2013|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1272886/|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> [[Per Gessle]], of Roxette, was credited for the music and soundtrack.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Videography==\n<!--[[Music video director]] links directly here.-->\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break|width=36%}}\n\n'''1988'''\n:\"Bewitched\" for [[Candlemass (band)|Candlemass]] \n'''1989'''\n:\"What's the Noise?\" for [[Walk on Water (band)|Walk on Water]]\n'''1992'''\n:\"[[Shame, Shame, Shame (Shirley & Company song)|Shame, Shame, Shame]]\" for [[Izabella Scorupco]]\n:\"S\u00e5 l\u00e4nge det lyser mittemot\" for [[Marie Fredriksson]] <small>(Female half of Roxette)</small>\n:\"Mellan sommar och h\u00f6st\" for Marie Fredriksson\n'''1993'''\n:\"[[Fingertips '93]]\" for [[Roxette]]\n'''1994'''\n:\"[[Run to You (Roxette song)|Run to You]]\" for Roxette\n'''1995'''\n:\"A la ronde\" for [[Sinclair (singer)|Sinclair]]\n:\"[[Vulnerable (song)|Vulnerable]]\" for Roxette\n:\"Pay for Me\" for [[Whale (band)|Whale]]\n'''1996'''\n:\"[[June Afternoon]]\" for Roxette\n:\"[[She Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]\" for Roxette\n:\"Un Dia Sin Ti\" for Roxette <small>(Spanish version of \"[[Spending My Time]]\")</small>\n'''1997''' \n:\"[[Do You Wanna Be My Baby?]]\" for [[Per Gessle]] <small>(Male half of Roxette)</small>\n:\"[[James Bond Theme#Moby Re-version|James Bond Theme]]\" for [[Moby]]\n:\"[[Kix (song)|Kix]]\" for Per Gessle\n:\"[[I Want You to Know (Per Gessle song)|I Want You To Know]]\" for Per Gessle\n:\"[[Smack My Bitch Up]]\" for [[The Prodigy]]\n'''1998'''\n:\"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\" for [[Madonna (entertainer)|Mado