ams]] ''\"[[Come Undone (Robbie Williams song)|Come Undone]]\"''\n*[[41st Annual Grammy Awards|1999]] \u2013 [[Grammy]] \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Short Form Music Video]]: [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] ''\"[[Ray of Light]]\"''\n*[[1998 MTV Video Music Awards|1998]] \u2013 [[MTV Video Music Award]] \u2013 [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] ''\"[[Ray of Light (song)|Ray of Light]]\"'' <small>(five awards: Video of the Year, Best Female Video, Best Director, Best Editing and Best Choreography - Jonas \u00c5kerlund was also the editor and he and Madonna were the choreographers for this video)</small>\n*[[1998 MTV Video Music Awards|1998]] \u2013 [[MTV Video Music Award]] \u2013 Best Dance Video: [[The Prodigy]] ''\"[[Smack My Bitch Up]]\"''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0959774}}\n*{{Sfdb name}}\n*[http://www.mvdbase.com/tech.php?last=Akerlund&first=Jonas/ Jonas \u00c5kerlund at the MVDbase.com]\n*[http://edition.cnn.com/2006/TRAVEL/10/11/stockholm.qa/ CNN interview with Jonas \u00c5kerlund]\n*[http://www.jonasakerlund.com/ Jonas \u00c5kerlund official web page]\n*[http://www.raf.se/ R.A.F. official web page]\n*{{cite web|last=Edwards|first=Gavin|title=Video Visionary Jonas \u00c5kerlund Pushes the Limits | url = https://www.wired.com/magazine/2011/05/pl_music_ackerlund/ | work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=24 July 2012}}\n\n{{Jonas \u00c5kerlund}}\n{{Bathory (band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akerlund, Jonas}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Sommar (radio program) hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish film directors]]\n[[Category:Swedish music video directors]]\n[[Category:Swedish heavy metal drummers]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonas_%C3%85kerlund"}
{"title_page": "Ovidiu", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Constan\u021ba\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map              = Ovidiu jud Constanta.jpg\n|map_caption            = Location in Constan\u021ba County\n|subdivisions           = Poiana, Culmea\n|official_name=Ovidiu\n|image_shield=ROU CT Ovidiu CoA.jpg\n|image_skyline=RO CT Ovidiu mosque.jpg\n|image_caption=Ovidiu mosque\n|coordinates            = {{coord|44|16|12|N|28|33|36|E|region:RO_type:city(3220)|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_name=George Scupra<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.ziuaconstanta.ro/stiri/alegeri-locale/lupta-stransa-pentru-consiliul-judetean-constanta-intre-psd-si-pnl-noua-garnitura-de-primari-596101.html| title = Lupt\u0103 str\u00e2ns\u0103 pentru Consiliul Jude\u0163ean Constan\u0163a \u00eentre PSD \u015fi PNL. Noua garnitur\u0103 de primari|date = 7 June 2016|accessdate = 7 June 2016| publisher = Ziua de Constan\u021ba| language = Romanian}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=82.63\n|website={{url|http://www.primariaovidiu.ro/}}\n}}\n:''For the Romanian given name and people named Ovidiu see [[Ovidiu (name)]].''\n'''Ovidiu''' ({{IPA-ro|o\u02c8vidju}}, historical name: ''Canara'', {{lang-tr|Kanara}}) is a town situated a few kilometres north of [[Constan\u021ba]] in [[Constan\u021ba County]], south-eastern [[Romania]]. Ovidiu is quite small, with a population of around 12,000, and many wealthy inhabitants of Constan\u021ba retire there.{{citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\nIn 1930, the town was renamed ''Ovidiu'' after the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] poet [[Ovid]] ({{lang-lat|Ovidius}}). He was supposedly buried on a nearby small island (also called ''Ovidiu'') in the [[Siutghiol Lake]].\n\n==Administration==\nThe town of Ovidiu administers the villages of Poiana (historical names: ''Coco\u0219ul'' - until 1964, {{lang-tr|Horozlar}} - until 1926) and Culmea. The latter was established in 2011 by legally separating from Ovidiu two territorially distinct communities, Social Group Culmea and Social Group Nazarcea.\n\n==Sport==\nThe [[Stadionul Viitorul (Ovidiu)|stadium]] of [[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba]] is located in Ovidiu.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1992 |12591\n|2002 |13458\n|2011 |12342\n}}\n\nAt the 2011 census, Ovidiu had 11,240 Romanians (91.07%), 3  [[Hungarians in Romania|Hungarians]] (0.02%), 229 [[Roma in Romania|Roma]]  (1.86%), 3 Germans (0.02%), 358 [[Turks of Romania|Turks]] (2.90%), 396 [[Tatars of Romania|Tatars]] (3.21%), 8 [[Lipovans]] (0.06%), 36 [[Aromanians]] (0.29%), 69 others (0.56%).\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Insula ovidiu.jpg|The ''Ovidiu'' island in the [[Siutghiol Lake]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Ovidiu}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Constan\u0163a County}}\n\n[[Category:Ovidiu| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Constan\u021ba County]]\n\n{{Constan\u0163a-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Constan\u021ba\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map              = Ovidiu jud Constanta.jpg\n|map_caption            = Location in Constan\u021ba County\n|subdivisions           = Poiana, Culmea\n|official_name=Ovidiu\n|image_shield=ROU CT Ovidiu CoA.jpg\n|image_skyline=RO CT Ovidiu mosque.jpg\n|image_caption=Ovidiu mosque\n|coordinates            = {{coord|44|16|12|N|28|33|36|E|region:RO_type:city(3220)|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_name=George Scupra<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.ziuaconstanta.ro/stiri/alegeri-locale/lupta-stransa-pentru-consiliul-judetean-constanta-intre-psd-si-pnl-noua-garnitura-de-primari-596101.html| title = Lupt\u0103 str\u00e2ns\u0103 pentru Consiliul Jude\u0163ean Constan\u0163a \u00eentre PSD \u015fi PNL. Noua garnitur\u0103 de primari|date = 7 June 2016|accessdate = 7 June 2016| publisher = Ziua de Constan\u021ba| language = Romanian}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=82.63\n|website={{url|http://www.primariaovidiu.ro/}}\n}}\n:''For the Romanian given name and people named Ovidiu see [[Ovidiu (name)]].''\n'''Ovidiu''' ({{IPA-ro|o\u02c8vidju}}, historical name: ''Canara'', {{lang-tr|Kanara}}) is a town situated a few kilometres north of [[Constan\u021ba]] in [[Constan\u021ba County]], south-eastern [[Romania]]. Ovidiu is quite small, with a population of around 12,000, and many wealthy inhabitants of Constan\u021ba retire there.{{citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\nIn 1930, the town was renamed ''Ovidiu'' after the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] poet [[Ovid]] ({{lang-lat|Ovidius}}). He was supposedly buried on a nearby small island (also called ''Ovidiu'') in the [[Siutghiol Lake]].\n\n==Administration==\nThe town of Ovidiu administers the villages of Poiana (historical names: ''Coco\u0219ul'' - until 1964, {{lang-tr|Horozlar}} - until 1926) and Culmea. The latter was established in 2011 by legally separating from Ovidiu two territorially distinct communities, Social Group Culmea and Social Group Nazarcea.\n\n==Sport==\nThe [[Stadionul Viitorul (Ovidiu)|stadium]] of [[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba]] is located in Ovidiu.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1992 |12591\n|2002 |13458\n|2011 |12342\n}}\n\nAt the 2011 census, Ovidiu had 11,240 Romanians (91.07%), 3  [[Hungarians in Romania|Hungarians]] (0.02%), 229 [[Roma in Romania|Roma]]  (1.86%), 3 Germans (0.02%), 358 [[Turks of Romania|Turks]] (2.90%), 396 [[Tatars of Romania|Tatars]] (3.21%), 8 [[Lipovans]] (0.06%), 36 [[Aromanians]] (0.29%), 69 others (0.56%).\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Insula ovidiu.jpg|The ''Ovidiu'' island in the [[Siutghiol Lake]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Ovidiu}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Constan\u0163a County}}\n\n[[Category:Ovidiu| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Constan\u021ba County]]\n\n{{Constan\u0163a-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ovidiu"}
{"title_page": "Lady Jane Grey", "text_new": "{{redirect|Jane Grey}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Lady Jane Grey\n| image = streathamladyjayne.jpg\n| caption = The [[Streatham portrait]], discovered at the beginning of the 21st century and believed to be a copy of a contemporaneous portrait of Lady Jane Grey<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n| succession = [[List of English monarchs|Queen of England]] and [[List of Irish monarchs|Ireland]]\n| moretext = ([[Style of the British sovereign#Styles of English sovereigns|more&nbsp;...]]) <br> '''Disputed'''\n| reign ={{nowrap|10 July 1553 \u2013 19 July 1553}}<ref>Williamson, David (2010). ''Kings & Queens''. National Portrait Gallery Publications. p. 95. {{ISBN|978-1-85514-432-3}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[Edward VI]]\n| successor = [[Mary I]]\n| birth_date = 1536 or 1537<ref name=birth/>\n| birth_place = Possibly London or [[Bradgate Park]], [[Leicestershire]], England\n| death_date = 12 February 1554 (aged 16-17)\n| death_place = [[Tower of London]], London, England\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Lord Guildford Dudley]]|25 May 1553}}\n| house = [[House of Grey|Grey]]\n| father = [[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk]]\n| mother = [[Lady Frances Brandon]]\n| burial_place = [[Church of St Peter ad Vincula]], Tower of London\n| signature = Janegreysig.jpg\n| religion = [[Protestant]]\n}}\n\n'''Lady Jane Grey''' ({{circa|1537}}<ref name=birth>Her exact date of birth is uncertain; many historians agree on the long-held estimate of 1537, while others set it in the latter half of 1536 based on newer research.[http://www.ladyjanegrey.info/?page_id=17][https://www.britannica.com/biography/Lady-Jane-Grey]</ref> \u2013 12 February 1554), also known as '''Lady Jane Dudley''' (after her marriage)<ref name=\"odnbJane\" /> and as \"the '''Nine Days' Queen'''\",<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=2}}</ref> was an English noblewoman and [[de facto]] Queen of England and Ireland from 10 July until 19 July 1553. \n\nJane was the great-granddaughter of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] through his younger daughter [[Mary Tudor, Queen of France|Mary]], and was a first cousin once removed of [[Edward VI]]. She had an excellent [[Renaissance humanism|humanist]] education and a reputation as one of the most learned young women of her day.<ref name=\"ascham213\">{{harvnb|Ascham|1863|p=213}}</ref> In May 1553, she married [[Lord Guildford Dudley]], a younger son of Edward's chief minister [[John Dudley, Duke of Northumberland]]. In June 1553, Edward VI wrote his will, nominating Jane and her male heirs as successors to the Crown, in part because his half-sister [[Mary I of England|Mary]] was Roman Catholic, while Jane was a committed Protestant and would support the reformed [[Church of England]], whose foundation Edward claimed to have laid. The will removed his half-sisters, Mary and [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]], from the line of succession on account of their illegitimacy, subverting their claims under the [[Third Succession Act]].\n\nAfter Edward's death, Jane was proclaimed queen on 10 July 1553 and awaited coronation in the [[Tower of London]]. Support for Mary grew very quickly, and most of Jane's supporters abandoned her. The [[Privy Council of England]] suddenly changed sides and proclaimed Mary as queen on 19 July 1553, deposing Jane. Her primary supporter, her father-in-law the Duke of Northumberland, was accused of treason and executed less than a month later. Jane was held prisoner in the Tower and was convicted in November 1553 of high treason, which carried a sentence of death\u2014though Mary initially spared her life. However, Jane soon became viewed as a threat to the Crown when her father, [[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk]], got involved with [[Wyatt's rebellion]] against Queen Mary's intention to marry [[Philip II of Spain]]. Both Jane and her husband were executed on 12 February 1554.\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nLady Jane Grey was the eldest daughter of [[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk]], and his wife, [[Frances Grey, Duchess of Suffolk|Frances]]. The traditional view is that she was born at [[Bradgate Park]] in [[Leicestershire]] in October 1537, while more recent research indicates that she was born somewhat earlier, possibly in London, in late 1536 or in the spring of 1537.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=36, 299}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|de Lisle|2008|pp=5\u20138}}</ref> Frances was the elder daughter of [[King Henry VIII]]'s younger sister, [[Mary Tudor, Queen of France|Mary]]. Jane had two younger sisters, [[Lady Catherine Grey|Lady Catherine]] and [[Lady Mary Grey|Lady Mary]]; through their mother, the three sisters were great-granddaughters of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]], grandnieces of Henry VIII, and first cousins once removed of [[Edward VI]], [[Mary I]] and [[Elizabeth I]].\n\nJane received a humanist education, studying [[Latin]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] with [[John Aylmer (bishop)|John Aylmer]], and Italian with [[Michelangelo Florio]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=51, 65}}</ref> Through the influence of her father and her tutors, she became a committed Protestant and also corresponded with the [[Z\u00fcrich]] reformer [[Heinrich Bullinger]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=63\u201367}}</ref>\n\nJane preferred book studies to hunting parties<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=51}}</ref> and regarded her strict upbringing, which was typical of the time,<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=53}}</ref> as harsh. To the visiting scholar [[Roger Ascham]], who found her reading [[Plato]], she is said to have complained: <blockquote>\nFor when I am in the presence either of father or mother, whether I speak, keep silence, sit, stand or go, eat, drink, be merry or sad, be sewing, playing, dancing, or doing anything else, I must do it as it were in such weight, measure and number, even so perfectly as God made the world; or else I am so sharply taunted, so cruelly threatened, yea presently sometimes with pinches, nips and bobs and other ways (which I will not name for the honour I bear them) ... that I think myself in hell.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=52}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn early February 1547, Jane was sent to live in the household of Edward VI's uncle, [[Thomas Seymour, 1st Baron Seymour of Sudeley|Thomas Seymour]], who soon married Henry VIII's widow, [[Catherine Parr]]. Jane lived with the couple at [[Sudeley Castle]] in [[Gloucestershire]] until Catherine's [[death in childbirth]] in September 1548.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=42\u201345}}</ref>\n\n== Contracts for marriage ==\nLady Jane acted as chief mourner at Catherine Parr's funeral; Thomas Seymour showed continued interest to keep her in his household, and she returned there for about two months before he was arrested at the end of 1548.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=45\u201347}}</ref> Seymour's brother, the [[Lord Protector]], [[Edward Seymour, 1st Duke of Somerset]], felt threatened by Thomas' popularity with the young King Edward. Among other things, Thomas Seymour was charged with proposing Jane as a bride for the king.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=47\u201349}}</ref>\n\nIn the course of Thomas Seymour's following [[attainder]] and execution, Jane's father was lucky to stay largely out of trouble. After his fourth interrogation by the [[Privy Council of England|King's Council]], he proposed his daughter Jane as a bride for the Protector's eldest son, [[Edward Seymour, 1st Earl of Hertford|Lord Hertford]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=47}}</ref> Nothing came of this, however, and Jane was not engaged until the spring of 1553, her bridegroom being [[Lord Guildford Dudley]], a younger son of [[John Dudley, 1st Duke of Northumberland]].<ref>{{harvnb|Loades|1996|pp=238\u2013239}}</ref> The Duke, [[Lord President of the Council|Lord President]] of the [[privy council|King's Council]] from late 1549, was then the most powerful man in the country.<ref>{{harvnb|Loades|1996|p=179}}</ref> On 25 May 1553, the couple were married at [[Durham House (London)|Durham House]] in a triple wedding, in which Jane's sister [[Lady Catherine Grey|Catherine]] was matched with the heir of the [[William Herbert, 1st Earl of Pembroke (1551 creation)|Earl of Pembroke]], [[Henry Herbert, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|Lord Herbert]], and another [[Katherine Hastings, Countess of Huntingdon|Katherine]], Lord Guildford's sister, with [[Henry Hastings, 3rd Earl of Huntingdon|Henry Hastings]], the [[Francis Hastings, 2nd Earl of Huntingdon|Earl of Huntingdon]]'s heir.<ref>{{harvnb|de Lisle|2008|pp=93, 304}}; {{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=321}}.</ref>\n\n== Claim to the throne and accession ==\n{{See also|Third Succession Act}}\n[[File:Edward VI's 'devise for the succession'.png|thumb|\"My devise for the Succession\" by Edward VI. The draft will was the basis for the [[letters patent]] which declared Lady Jane Grey successor to the Crown.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=137}}</ref> Edward's [[autograph]] shows his alteration of his text, from \"L Janes heires masles\" to \"L Jane and her heires masles\".<ref name=\"Alford 2002 171\u2013172\">{{harvnb|Alford|2002|pp=171\u2013172}}</ref> [[Inner Temple Library]], London.]]\n\nThe Third Succession Act of 1544 restored Henry VIII's daughters, Mary and Elizabeth, to the line of succession, although they were still regarded as illegitimate. Furthermore, this Act authorised Henry VIII to alter the succession by his will. Henry's will reinforced the succession of his three children, and then declared that, should none of them leave descendants, the throne would pass to heirs of his younger sister, Mary, which included Jane. For unknown reasons, Henry excluded Jane's mother, Frances Grey, from the succession,<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=35}}</ref> and also bypassed the claims of the descendants of his elder sister, [[Margaret Tudor|Margaret]], who had married into the Scottish royal house and nobility.\n\nBoth Mary and Elizabeth had been named illegitimate by statute during the reign of Henry VIII after his marriages to [[Catherine of Aragon]] and [[Anne Boleyn]] had been declared void.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gah0RdbHKmYC&pg=PA38 |page=38|title=A Constitutional History of Secession|isbn=9781455602889}}</ref> When the 15-year-old Edward VI lay dying in the early summer of 1553, his Catholic half-sister Mary was still his heir presumptive. However, Edward, in a draft will (\"My devise for the Succession\") composed earlier in 1553, had first restricted the succession to (non-existent) male descendants of Frances Brandon and her daughters, before he named his Protestant cousin \"Lady Jane and her heirs male\" as his successors, probably in June 1553; the intent was to ensure his Protestant legacy, thereby bypassing Mary, who was a Roman Catholic.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/reformation22lind |page=[https://archive.org/details/reformation22lind/page/149 149] |title=The Reformation |publisher=T. & T. Clark |last1=Lindsay |first1=Thomas Martin |year=1882 }}</ref><ref name=\"Alford 2002 171\u2013172\" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B5P-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT121 |title=Crown of Blood: The Deadly Inheritance of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nicola|last=Tallis|date=6 December 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|via=Google Books|isbn=9781681772875}}</ref> Edward's decision to name Jane Grey herself was possibly instigated by Northumberland.<ref>{{harvnb|Loades|1996|p=240}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Alford|2014|pp=75\u201356}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Loach|2002|pp=163\u2013164}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">Dale Hoak: [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/8522 \"Edward VI (1537\u20131553)\"], ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Oxford University Press, 2004, online edn. January 2008, Retrieved 4 April 2010 (subscription required)</ref>\n\nEdward VI personally supervised the copying of his will which was finally issued as letters patent on 21 June and signed by 102 notables, among them the whole [[Privy Council]], peers, bishops, judges, and [[Court of Aldermen|London aldermen]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=145, 165\u2013166}}</ref> Edward also announced to have his \"declaration\" passed in [[parliament of England|parliament]] in September, and the necessary [[writs]] were prepared.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n[[File:The Crown Offered to Lady Jane Grey after Leslie.jpg|thumb|left|270px|''The Crown Offered to Lady Jane Grey'', as imagined in the 1820s: Guildford and Jane are in the centre]]\nThe King died on 6 July 1553, but his death was not announced until four days later.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39hKrtqiDcIC&pg=PA84 |page=84 |title=Monarchs of the Renaissance: The Lives and Reigns of 42 European Kings and Queens |isbn=9780786491032 |last1=Potter |first1=Philip J. |date=10 January 2014 }}</ref> On 9 July Jane was informed that she was now queen, and according to her own later claims, accepted the crown only with reluctance. On 10 July, she was officially proclaimed Queen of England, France and Ireland after she had taken up secure residence in the [[Tower of London]], where English monarchs customarily resided from the time of accession until coronation. Jane refused to name her husband Dudley as king, because that would require an [[Act of Parliament]].<ref name=\"Ives p. 189\">Ives 2009 p. 189</ref> She would agree only to make him [[Duke of Clarence]].{{cn|date=April 2018}}\n\nNorthumberland faced a number of key tasks to consolidate his [[political power|power]] after Edward's death. Most importantly, he had to isolate and, ideally, capture Mary Tudor to prevent her from gathering support. As soon as Mary was sure of King Edward's demise, she left her residence at [[Hunsdon]] and set out to [[East Anglia]], where she began to rally her supporters. Northumberland set out from London with troops on 14 July to capture Mary. The [[Privy Council of England|Privy Council]] switched their allegiance and proclaimed Mary queen in London, on 19 July. The historical consensus assumes that this was in recognition of overwhelming support of the population for Mary. However, there is no clear evidence for that outside Norfolk and Suffolk, where Northumberland had put down Kett's Rebellion; hence, where princess Mary sought refuge. Rather, it seems that [[Henry FitzAlan, 19th Earl of Arundel]]\u2014whom Northumberland had arrested and detained twice as an ally of Somerset, before rehabilitating\u2014engineered a coup d'\u00e9tat in the Privy Council in Northumberland's absence.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=222\u2013223, 233\u2013236}}</ref>\n\nJane is often called the Nine-Day Queen, although if her reign is dated from the moment of Edward's death on 6 July 1553, her reign could have been a few days longer.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=1}}</ref> On 19 July 1553, Jane was imprisoned in the Tower's Gentleman Gaoler's (Jailer's) apartments, her husband in the Beauchamp Tower. The Duke of Northumberland was executed on 22 August 1553. In September, Parliament declared Mary the rightful successor and denounced and revoked Jane's proclamation as that of a usurper.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39hKrtqiDcIC&pg=PA84 |page=88\u201389 |title=Monarchs of the Renaissance: The Lives and Reigns of 42 European Kings and Queens |isbn=9780786491032 |last1=Potter |first1=Philip J. |date=10 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Trial and execution ==\nReferred to by the court as Jane Dudley, wife of Guildford, Jane was charged with [[high treason]], as were her husband, two of his brothers, and the former [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Thomas Cranmer]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B5P-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT172 |title=Crown of Blood: The Deadly Inheritance of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nicola|last=Tallis|date=6 December 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|via=Google Books|isbn=9781681772875}}</ref> Their trial, by a special commission, took place on 13 November 1553, at [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] in the [[City of London]]. The commission was chaired by [[Thomas White (merchant)|Sir Thomas White]], [[Lord Mayor of London]], and [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk]]. Other members included [[Edward Stanley, 3rd Earl of Derby]] and [[John Bourchier, 2nd Earl of Bath]]. As was to be expected, all defendants were found guilty and sentenced to death. Jane's guilt, of having treacherously assumed the title and the power of the monarch, was evidenced by a number of documents she had signed as \"Jane the Quene\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Her sentence was to \"be burned alive on Tower Hill or beheaded as the Queen pleases\" ([[Execution by burning#Historical usage|burning]] was the [[Burning of women in England|traditional English punishment]] for [[treason]] committed by women).<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=251\u2013252, 334}}; {{harvnb|Bellamy|1979|p=54}}</ref> The [[List of ambassadors of the Kingdom of England to the Holy Roman Emperor|imperial ambassador]] reported to [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]], that her life was to be spared.<ref name=\"odnbJane\">{{cite book| last =Plowden| first =Alison| authorlink =Alison Plowden| title =Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| chapter =Grey, Lady Jane (1534\u20131554), noblewoman and claimant to the English throne| publisher =[[Oxford University Press]]| date =23 September 2004| location =[[Oxford]]| isbn =0-19-861362-8 | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/8154| title-link =Dictionary of National Biography}}</ref> \n[[File:Lady Jane Grey letter as Queen.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Official letter of Lady Jane Grey signing herself as \"Jane the Quene\". [[Inner Temple Library]], London.]]\nThe rebellion of [[Thomas Wyatt the Younger]] in January 1554 against Queen Mary's marriage plans with [[Philip II of Spain|Philip of Spain]] sealed Jane's fate. Her father, Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk, and his two brothers joined the rebellion, and so the government decided to go through with the verdict against Jane and Guildford. Their execution was first scheduled for 9 February 1554, but was then postponed for three days to give Jane a chance to convert to the Catholic faith. Mary sent her chaplain [[John Feckenham]] to Jane, who was initially not pleased about this.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=267, 268}}</ref> Though she would not give in to his efforts \"to save her soul\", she became friends with him and allowed him to accompany her to the scaffold.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=268\u2013270}}</ref>\n\n[[File:PAUL DELAROCHE - Ejecuci\u00f3n de Lady Jane Grey (National Gallery de Londres, 1834).jpg|thumb|300px|''[[The Execution of Lady Jane Grey]]'', by the French painter [[Paul Delaroche]], 1833. [[National Gallery, London]].]]\n\nOn the morning of 12 February 1554, the authorities took Guildford from his rooms at the Tower of London to the public [[execution]] place at [[Tower Hill]], where he was beheaded. A horse and cart brought his remains back to the Tower, past the rooms where Jane was staying. Seeing her husband's corpse return, Jane is reported to have exclaimed: \"Oh, Guildford, Guildford.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=274\u2013275}}</ref> She was then taken out to [[Tower Green]], inside the Tower, to be beheaded.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KZCMGgJzO2IC&pg=PA233 |title=Lady Jane Grey: A Tudor Mystery|first=Eric|last=Ives|date=19 September 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|via=Google Books|isbn=9781444354263}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the account of her execution given in the anonymous ''Chronicle of Queen Jane and of Two Years of Queen Mary'', which formed the basis for [[Raphael Holinshed]]'s depiction, Jane gave a speech upon ascending the scaffold:\n\n<blockquote>Good people, I am come hither to die, and by a law I am condemned to the same. The fact, indeed, against the Queen's highness was unlawful, and the consenting thereunto by me: but touching the procurement and desire thereof by me or on my behalf, I do wash my hands thereof in innocency, before God, and the face of you, good Christian people, this day.<ref name=\"ladyjane\">{{Cite book| contribution=1554, The Execution of Lady Jane Grey and Lord Guildford Dudley|author = Anonymous| editor-last =Nichols|editor-first=John Gough|editor-link=John Gough Nichols| title =Chronicle of Queen Jane and of Two Years of Queen Mary| publisher =[[The Camden Society]]; Marilee Hanson| year=1997|origyear =1850| url =http://englishhistory.net/tudor/executions-of-lady-jane-grey-lord-guildford-dudley/| ref=harv}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile admitting to action considered unlawful, she declared that \"I do wash my hands thereof in innocence\".<ref>{{harvnb|de Lisle|2008|p=138}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KZCMGgJzO2IC&pg=PA22 |title=Lady Jane Grey: A Tudor Mystery|first=Eric|last=Ives|date=19 September 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|via=Google Books|isbn=9781444354263}}</ref> Jane then recited [[Psalm 51]] (''Have mercy upon me, O God'') in English, and handed her gloves and handkerchief to her maid. The executioner asked her forgiveness, which she granted him, pleading: \"I pray you dispatch me quickly.\" Referring to her head, she asked, \"Will you take it off before I lay me down?\", and the axeman answered: \"No, madam.\" She then blindfolded herself. Jane then failed to find the block with her hands, and cried, \"What shall I do? Where is it?\" Probably [[Thomas Brydges|Sir Thomas Brydges]], the Deputy Lieutenant of the Tower, helped her find her way. With her head on the block, Jane spoke the last words of Jesus as recounted by [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]]: \"Lord, into thy hands I commend my spirit!\"<ref name=\"ladyjane\" />\n\nJane and Guildford are buried in the Chapel of [[Church of St Peter ad Vincula|St Peter ad Vincula]] on the north side of Tower Green. No memorial stone was erected at their grave.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B5P-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT214 |title=Crown of Blood: The Deadly Inheritance of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nicola|last=Tallis|date=6 December 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|via=Google Books|isbn=9781681772875}}</ref> Jane's father, the Duke of Suffolk, was executed 11 days after Jane, on 23 February 1554.<ref name=\"CP\">{{cite book | last = Cokayne | first = George | title = The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain, and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant | publisher = A. Sutton | location = Gloucester | year = 1982 | isbn = 0904387828 | volume = 2 | page = 421 }}</ref> Her mother, the Duchess of Suffolk, married her Master of the Horse and [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]], [[Adrian Stokes (Master of Horse)|Adrian Stokes]], in March 1555 (not, as often said, three weeks after the execution of the Duke of Suffolk).<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=38}}</ref> She was fully pardoned by Mary and allowed to live at Court with her two surviving daughters. She died in 1559.\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Miniatureenlarged.jpg|thumb|right|Miniature portrait of a young lady thought by [[David Starkey]] to probably depict Lady Jane Grey.]]\n{{Main|Cultural depictions of Lady Jane Grey}}\n\"The traitor-heroine of the Reformation\", as historian [[Albert Pollard]] called her,<ref>{{cite book| last =Pollard| first =Albert J.| authorlink =Albert Pollard| title =The History of England| publisher =Longmans, Green| year =1911| location =London| page =111| url =https://www.questia.com/read/58544100}}</ref> was only 16 or 17 years old at the time of her execution. During and in the aftermath of the [[List of Protestant martyrs of the English Reformation|Marian persecutions]], Jane became viewed as a Protestant martyr for centuries, featuring prominently in the several editions of the ''[[Book of Martyrs]]'' (''Actes and Monuments of these Latter and Perillous Dayes'') by [[John Foxe]]. The tale of Lady Jane grew to legendary proportions in popular culture, producing romantic biographies, novels, plays, operas, paintings, and films. \n\nJane Grey is the only English monarch in the last 500 years (though whether her short reign was legitimate is disputed) of whom no proven contemporary portrait survives.<ref name=\"guardian\"/><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news | last =Reynolds| first =Nigel| title =The true beauty of Lady Jane Grey| work =[[The Daily Telegraph]]| date =3 June 2007| url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1544576/The-true-beauty-of-Lady-Jane-Grey.html| accessdate =11 May 2008 }}</ref> A painting in London's [[National Portrait Gallery (United Kingdom)|National Portrait Gallery]] was thought to be Jane for many years, but in 1996 it was confirmed to be of Catherine Parr.<ref name=\"yale\">{{cite web| last =Fellman| first =Bruce| title =Looking for Lady Jane| work =Yale Alumni Magazine| publisher =[[Yale University]]| date =May\u2013June 2007| url =http://archives.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/2007_05/ladyjane.html| accessdate =24 November 2014| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20141129201720/http://archives.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/2007_05/ladyjane.html| archive-date =29 November 2014| url-status =dead}}</ref> A portrait believed by some experts to be of Jane was discovered in a private home in 2005. Painted 40 to 50 years after Jane's death, the \"[[Streatham portrait]]\" (so called after the area of London in which it resided for decades) depicts a young woman dressed in a red gown, adorned with jewels and holding a prayer book.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news | last =Higgins| first =Charlotte| title =Is this the true face of Lady Jane?| work =[[The Guardian]]| date =16 January 2006| url =https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/jan/16/arts.research| accessdate =11 May 2008 }}</ref> Historian and Tudor specialist Dr. [[David Starkey]] is sceptical, \"It's an appallingly bad picture and there's absolutely no reason to suppose it's got anything to do with Lady Jane Grey\".<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Higgins \n |first=Charlotte \n |title=A rare portrait of Lady Jane Grey? Or just an 'appallingly bad picture'? \n |work=The Guardian \n |date=11 November 2006 \n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/nov/11/arts.artsnews \n |accessdate=11 February 2014 \n |ref={{sfnRef|Higgins 2006, A rare portrait}} \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NItOvhcr?url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/nov/11/arts.artsnews \n |archivedate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\nAnother portrait, a miniature, was shown to the news media in 2007 by Starkey who stated that he was \"90 per cent certain\" that it is of Lady Jane Grey.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/mar/05/artnews.monarchy|title=Miniature could be second view of Lady Jane Grey|first1=Charlotte|last1=Higgins|first2=arts|last2=correspondent|date=5 March 2007|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> This painting had been discovered at the [[Yale Center for British Art]] in America.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1544576/The-true-beauty-of-Lady-Jane-Grey.html|title=The true beauty of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nigel|last=Reynolds|date=5 March 2007|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Family tree ==\nThe following chart illustrates Jane's relationship to the [[House of Tudor]] and other claimants to the English throne. Italics indicate people who predeceased Edward VI; Arabic numerals indicate the line of succession to Edward VI at the time of his death according to Henry VIII's will; and Roman numerals indicate the line of succession at the time of Edward VI's death according to Edward's will.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|loc=Figures 1-5}}</ref>\n{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | | | | | |Harry|y|Liz| |Liz=''[[Elizabeth of York]]''|Harry=''[[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]]''}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|^|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|.| |}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | |Harry| | | | | | | |Marge| | | |Mary|y|Charlie| |Harry=''[[Henry VIII]]''|Mary=''[[Mary Tudor, Queen of France|Mary Tudor]]''|Charlie=''[[Charles Brandon, 1st Duke of Suffolk|Charles Brandon]]''|Marge=''[[Margaret Tudor]]''}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree|border=0 |Eddy| |Mary| |Bess| |Jim| |Marge| | | |Fran|y|Harry|Mary=[[Mary I]]<br>(1)|Bess=[[Elizabeth I]]<br>(2)|Eddy=[[Edward VI]]|Fran=[[Frances Brandon]]|Jim=''[[James V of Scotland]]''|Marge=[[Margaret Douglas]]|Harry=[[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk|Henry Grey]]}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | | | | | | | | |Marie| |Harry| |Jane| |Kate| |Mary| | |Jane=Jane Grey<br>(3, I)|Marie=[[Mary, Queen of Scots]]|Harry=[[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley|Henry Stuart]]|Kate=[[Lady Katherine Grey|Katherine Grey]]<br>(4, II)|Mary=[[Lady Mary Grey|Mary Grey]]<br>(5, III)}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book | last = Alford| first = Stegdphen| title = Kingship and Politics in the Reign of Edward VI| year = 2002 | publisher = Cambridge University Press| place = Cambridge | isbn = 978-0-521-03971-0 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book|last=Alford|first=Stephen|editor=|title=Edward VI: The Last Boy King|url=|edition=|year=2014|publisher=Penguin|location=London|isbn=978-0141-97691-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ascham|first=Roger|editor=[[John Eyton Bickersteth Mayor|Mayor, John E. B.]]|title=The Scholemaster|url=https://archive.org/details/scholemasterorp00aschgoog|edition=1863|year=1863|publisher=Bell and Daldy|location=London|oclc=251212421|ref=harv}}sfds\n* {{Cite book | last = Bellamy| first = John| title = The Tudor Law of Treason| year =1979 | publisher = Routlegdtre, Kegan & Paufdl| place = Toronto | isbn = 0-7100-8729-2 | ref = harv }}\n* Bindoff,fk|last=de Lisle|first=Leanda|title=The Sisters Who Would Be Queen: Mary, Katherine and Lady Jane Grey. A Tudor Tragedy|year=2008|location=New York|publisher=Ballantine Books|isbn=978-0-345-49135-0|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/sisterswhowouldb00fgdggfcdeli_0}}\n* Hoak, Dale. (2015) \"The succession crisis of 1553 and Mary\u2019s rise to power\", in ''Catholic Renewal and Protestant Resistance in Marian England'' ed. by E. Evenden and V. Westbrook (Aldershot, 2015), pp. 17\u201342.\n* {{cite book|first=Eric|last=Ives|authorgssion crisis reconsidered.\" ''Historical Research'' (2017).  doi:10.1111/1468-2281.12178 \n* {{cite book|dlast=Loach|first=Jennifer|title=Edward VI|year=2002|location=New Haven|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-30009409-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Loaades| first = David|authorrlink=David Loaades| title = John Dudley Duke of huksland 1504\u20131553| year = 1996 | publisher = Clarendon Press| place = Oxford | isbn = 0-19-820193-1 | ref = harv }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource portal|House of Tudor}}\n* {{commonsinline|Lady Jane Grey}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.somegreymatter.com/index.html|title=Somegreymatter.com|first=J. Stephan|last=Edwards}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n79-45478}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou |||1537|12 February|1554}}\n{{S-reg}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edward VI]]}}\n{{S-dis|title=[[List of English monarchs|Queen of England]] and [[King of Ireland|Ireland]]|years=10\u201319 July 1553|by=[[Mary I]]}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Mary I]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{English and British monarchs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grey, Jane}}\n[[Category:Lady Jane Grey| ]]\n[[Category:House of Tudor]]\n[[Category:Women of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:1530s births]]\n[[Category:1554 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:16th-century English women]]\n[[Category:16th-century English monarchs]]\n[[Category:16th-century Irish monarchs]]\n[[Category:Burials at St. Peter ad Vincula (London)]]\n[[Category:Daughters of English dukes]]\n[[Category:Dudley family]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Executed English people]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:English pretenders to the French throne]]\n[[Category:Executed English women]]\n[[Category:Executed royalty]]\n[[Category:Executions at the Tower of London]]\n[[Category:Grey family|Jane Grey]]\n[[Category:People executed by Tudor England by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People executed under Mary I of England]]\n[[Category:People executed under the Tudors for treason against England]]\n[[Category:People from Leicester]]\n[[Category:Prisoners in the Tower of London]]\n[[Category:Protestant monarchs]]\n[[Category:Queens regnant of England]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n[[Category:Dethroned monarchs]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Jane Grey}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Lady Jane Grey\n| image = streathamladyjayne.jpg\n| caption = The [[Streatham portrait]], discovered at the beginning of the 21st century and believed to be a copy of a contemporaneous portrait of Lady Jane Grey<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n| succession = [[List of English monarchs|Queen of England]] and [[List of Irish monarchs|Ireland]]\n| moretext = ([[Style of the British sovereign#Styles of English sovereigns|more&nbsp;...]]) <br> '''Disputed'''\n| reign ={{nowrap|10 July 1553 \u2013 19 July 1553}}<ref>Williamson, David (2010). ''Kings & Queens''. National Portrait Gallery Publications. p. 95. {{ISBN|978-1-85514-432-3}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[Edward VI]]\n| successor = [[Mary I]]\n| birth_date = 1536 or 1537<ref name=birth/>\n| birth_place = Possibly London or [[Bradgate Park]], [[Leicestershire]], England\n| death_date = 12 February 1554 (aged 16-17)\n| death_place = [[Tower of London]], London, England\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Lord Guildford Dudley]]|25 May 1553}}\n| house = [[House of Grey|Grey]]\n| father = [[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk]]\n| mother = [[Lady Frances Brandon]]\n| burial_place = [[Church of St Peter ad Vincula]], Tower of London\n| signature = Janegreysig.jpg\n| religion = [[Protestant]]\n}}\n\n'''Lady Jane Grey''' ({{circa|1537}}<ref name=birth>Her exact date of birth is uncertain; many historians agree on the long-held estimate of 1537, while others set it in the latter half of 1536 based on newer research.[http://www.ladyjanegrey.info/?page_id=17][https://www.britannica.com/biography/Lady-Jane-Grey]</ref> \u2013 12 February 1554), also known as '''Lady Jane Dudley''' (after her marriage)<ref name=\"odnbJane\" /> and as \"the '''Nine Days' Queen'''\",<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=2}}</ref> was an English noblewoman and [[de facto]] Queen of England and Ireland from 10 July until 19 July 1553. \n\nJane was the great-granddaughter of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] through his younger daughter [[Mary Tudor, Queen of France|Mary]], and was a first cousin once removed of [[Edward VI]]. She had an excellent [[Renaissance humanism|humanist]] education and a reputation as one of the most learned young women of her day.<ref name=\"ascham213\">{{harvnb|Ascham|1863|p=213}}</ref> In May 1553, she married [[Lord Guildford Dudley]], a younger son of Edward's chief minister [[John Dudley, Duke of Northumberland]]. In June 1553, Edward VI wrote his will, nominating Jane and her male heirs as successors to the Crown, in part because his half-sister [[Mary I of England|Mary]] was Roman Catholic, while Jane was a committed Protestant and would support the reformed [[Church of England]], whose foundation Edward claimed to have laid. The will removed his half-sisters, Mary and [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]], from the line of succession on account of their illegitimacy, subverting their claims under the [[Third Succession Act]].\n\nAfter Edward's death, Jane was proclaimed queen on 10 July 1553 and awaited coronation in the [[Tower of London]]. Support for Mary grew very quickly, and most of Jane's supporters abandoned her. The [[Privy Council of England]] suddenly changed sides and proclaimed Mary as queen on 19 July 1553, deposing Jane. Her primary supporter, her father-in-law the Duke of Northumberland, was accused of treason and executed less than a month later. Jane was held prisoner in the Tower and was convicted in November 1553 of high treason, which carried a sentence of death\u2014though Mary initially spared her life. However, Jane soon became viewed as a threat to the Crown when her father, [[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk]], got involved with [[Wyatt's rebellion]] against Queen Mary's intention to marry [[Philip II of Spain]]. Both Jane and her husband were executed on 12 February 1554.\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nLady Jane Grey was the eldest daughter of [[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk]], and his wife, [[Frances Grey, Duchess of Suffolk|Frances]]. The traditional view is that she was born at [[Bradgate Park]] in [[Leicestershire]] in October 1537, while more recent research indicates that she was born somewhat earlier, possibly in London, in late 1536 or in the spring of 1537.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=36, 299}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|de Lisle|2008|pp=5\u20138}}</ref> Frances was the elder daughter of [[King Henry VIII]]'s younger sister, [[Mary Tudor, Queen of France|Mary]]. Jane had two younger sisters, [[Lady Catherine Grey|Lady Catherine]] and [[Lady Mary Grey|Lady Mary]]; through their mother, the three sisters were great-granddaughters of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]], grandnieces of Henry VIII, and first cousins once removed of [[Edward VI]], [[Mary I]] and [[Elizabeth I]].\n\nJane received a humanist education, studying [[Latin]], [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] with [[John Aylmer (bishop)|John Aylmer]], and Italian with [[Michelangelo Florio]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=51, 65}}</ref> Through the influence of her father and her tutors, she became a committed Protestant and also corresponded with the [[Z\u00fcrich]] reformer [[Heinrich Bullinger]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=63\u201367}}</ref>\n\nJane preferred book studies to hunting parties<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=51}}</ref> and regarded her strict upbringing, which was typical of the time,<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=53}}</ref> as harsh. To the visiting scholar [[Roger Ascham]], who found her reading [[Plato]], she is said to have complained: <blockquote>\nFor when I am in the presence either of father or mother, whether I speak, keep silence, sit, stand or go, eat, drink, be merry or sad, be sewing, playing, dancing, or doing anything else, I must do it as it were in such weight, measure and number, even so perfectly as God made the world; or else I am so sharply taunted, so cruelly threatened, yea presently sometimes with pinches, nips and bobs and other ways (which I will not name for the honour I bear them) ... that I think myself in hell.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=52}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn early February 1547, Jane was sent to live in the household of Edward VI's uncle, [[Thomas Seymour, 1st Baron Seymour of Sudeley|Thomas Seymour]], who soon married Henry VIII's widow, [[Catherine Parr]]. Jane lived with the couple at [[Sudeley Castle]] in [[Gloucestershire]] until Catherine's [[death in childbirth]] in September 1548.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=42\u201345}}</ref>\n\n== Contracts for marriage ==\nLady Jane acted as chief mourner at Catherine Parr's funeral; Thomas Seymour showed continued interest to keep her in his household, and she returned there for about two months before he was arrested at the end of 1548.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=45\u201347}}</ref> Seymour's brother, the [[Lord Protector]], [[Edward Seymour, 1st Duke of Somerset]], felt threatened by Thomas' popularity with the young King Edward. Among other things, Thomas Seymour was charged with proposing Jane as a bride for the king.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=47\u201349}}</ref>\n\nIn the course of Thomas Seymour's following [[attainder]] and execution, Jane's father was lucky to stay largely out of trouble. After his fourth interrogation by the [[Privy Council of England|King's Council]], he proposed his daughter Jane as a bride for the Protector's eldest son, [[Edward Seymour, 1st Earl of Hertford|Lord Hertford]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=47}}</ref> Nothing came of this, however, and Jane was not engaged until the spring of 1553, her bridegroom being [[Lord Guildford Dudley]], a younger son of [[John Dudley, 1st Duke of Northumberland]].<ref>{{harvnb|Loades|1996|pp=238\u2013239}}</ref> The Duke, [[Lord President of the Council|Lord President]] of the [[privy council|King's Council]] from late 1549, was then the most powerful man in the country.<ref>{{harvnb|Loades|1996|p=179}}</ref> On 25 May 1553, the couple were married at [[Durham House (London)|Durham House]] in a triple wedding, in which Jane's sister [[Lady Catherine Grey|Catherine]] was matched with the heir of the [[William Herbert, 1st Earl of Pembroke (1551 creation)|Earl of Pembroke]], [[Henry Herbert, 2nd Earl of Pembroke|Lord Herbert]], and another [[Katherine Hastings, Countess of Huntingdon|Katherine]], Lord Guildford's sister, with [[Henry Hastings, 3rd Earl of Huntingdon|Henry Hastings]], the [[Francis Hastings, 2nd Earl of Huntingdon|Earl of Huntingdon]]'s heir.<ref>{{harvnb|de Lisle|2008|pp=93, 304}}; {{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=321}}.</ref>\n\n== Claim to the throne and accession ==\n{{See also|Third Succession Act}}\n[[File:Edward VI's 'devise for the succession'.png|thumb|\"My devise for the Succession\" by Edward VI. The draft will was the basis for the [[letters patent]] which declared Lady Jane Grey successor to the Crown.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=137}}</ref> Edward's [[autograph]] shows his alteration of his text, from \"L Janes heires masles\" to \"L Jane and her heires masles\".<ref name=\"Alford 2002 171\u2013172\">{{harvnb|Alford|2002|pp=171\u2013172}}</ref> [[Inner Temple Library]], London.]]\n\nThe Third Succession Act of 1544 restored Henry VIII's daughters, Mary and Elizabeth, to the line of succession, although they were still regarded as illegitimate. Furthermore, this Act authorised Henry VIII to alter the succession by his will. Henry's will reinforced the succession of his three children, and then declared that, should none of them leave descendants, the throne would pass to heirs of his younger sister, Mary, which included Jane. For unknown reasons, Henry excluded Jane's mother, Frances Grey, from the succession,<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=35}}</ref> and also bypassed the claims of the descendants of his elder sister, [[Margaret Tudor|Margaret]], who had married into the Scottish royal house and nobility.\n\nBoth Mary and Elizabeth had been named illegitimate by statute during the reign of Henry VIII after his marriages to [[Catherine of Aragon]] and [[Anne Boleyn]] had been declared void.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gah0RdbHKmYC&pg=PA38 |page=38|title=A Constitutional History of Secession|isbn=9781455602889}}</ref> When the 15-year-old Edward VI lay dying in the early summer of 1553, his Catholic half-sister Mary was still his heir presumptive. However, Edward, in a draft will (\"My devise for the Succession\") composed earlier in 1553, had first restricted the succession to (non-existent) male descendants of Frances Brandon and her daughters, before he named his Protestant cousin \"Lady Jane and her heirs male\" as his successors, probably in June 1553; the intent was to ensure his Protestant legacy, thereby bypassing Mary, who was a Roman Catholic.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/reformation22lind |page=[https://archive.org/details/reformation22lind/page/149 149] |title=The Reformation |publisher=T. & T. Clark |last1=Lindsay |first1=Thomas Martin |year=1882 }}</ref><ref name=\"Alford 2002 171\u2013172\" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B5P-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT121 |title=Crown of Blood: The Deadly Inheritance of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nicola|last=Tallis|date=6 December 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|via=Google Books|isbn=9781681772875}}</ref> Edward's decision to name Jane Grey herself was possibly instigated by Northumberland.<ref>{{harvnb|Loades|1996|p=240}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Alford|2014|pp=75\u201356}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Loach|2002|pp=163\u2013164}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">Dale Hoak: [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/8522 \"Edward VI (1537\u20131553)\"], ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Oxford University Press, 2004, online edn. January 2008, Retrieved 4 April 2010 (subscription required)</ref>\n\nEdward VI personally supervised the copying of his will which was finally issued as letters patent on 21 June and signed by 102 notables, among them the whole [[Privy Council]], peers, bishops, judges, and [[Court of Aldermen|London aldermen]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=145, 165\u2013166}}</ref> Edward also announced to have his \"declaration\" passed in [[parliament of England|parliament]] in September, and the necessary [[writs]] were prepared.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n[[File:The Crown Offered to Lady Jane Grey after Leslie.jpg|thumb|left|270px|''The Crown Offered to Lady Jane Grey'', as imagined in the 1820s: Guildford and Jane are in the centre]]\nThe King died on 6 July 1553, but his death was not announced until four days later.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39hKrtqiDcIC&pg=PA84 |page=84 |title=Monarchs of the Renaissance: The Lives and Reigns of 42 European Kings and Queens |isbn=9780786491032 |last1=Potter |first1=Philip J. |date=10 January 2014 }}</ref> On 9 July Jane was informed that she was now queen, and according to her own later claims, accepted the crown only with reluctance. On 10 July, she was officially proclaimed Queen of England, France and Ireland after she had taken up secure residence in the [[Tower of London]], where English monarchs customarily resided from the time of accession until coronation. Jane refused to name her husband Dudley as king, because that would require an [[Act of Parliament]].<ref name=\"Ives p. 189\">Ives 2009 p. 189</ref> She would agree only to make him [[Duke of Clarence]].{{cn|date=April 2018}}\n\nNorthumberland faced a number of key tasks to consolidate his [[political power|power]] after Edward's death. Most importantly, he had to isolate and, ideally, capture Mary Tudor to prevent her from gathering support. As soon as Mary was sure of King Edward's demise, she left her residence at [[Hunsdon]] and set out to [[East Anglia]], where she began to rally her supporters. Northumberland set out from London with troops on 14 July to capture Mary. The [[Privy Council of England|Privy Council]] switched their allegiance and proclaimed Mary queen in London, on 19 July. The historical consensus assumes that this was in recognition of overwhelming support of the population for Mary. However, there is no clear evidence for that outside Norfolk and Suffolk, where Northumberland had put down Kett's Rebellion; hence, where princess Mary sought refuge. Rather, it seems that [[Henry FitzAlan, 19th Earl of Arundel]]\u2014whom Northumberland had arrested and detained twice as an ally of Somerset, before rehabilitating\u2014engineered a coup d'\u00e9tat in the Privy Council in Northumberland's absence.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=222\u2013223, 233\u2013236}}</ref>\n\nJane is often called the Nine-Day Queen, although if her reign is dated from the moment of Edward's death on 6 July 1553, her reign could have been a few days longer.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=1}}</ref> On 19 July 1553, Jane was imprisoned in the Tower's Gentleman Gaoler's (Jailer's) apartments, her husband in the Beauchamp Tower. The Duke of Northumberland was executed on 22 August 1553. In September, Parliament declared Mary the rightful successor and denounced and revoked Jane's proclamation as that of a usurper.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39hKrtqiDcIC&pg=PA84 |page=88\u201389 |title=Monarchs of the Renaissance: The Lives and Reigns of 42 European Kings and Queens |isbn=9780786491032 |last1=Potter |first1=Philip J. |date=10 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Trial and execution ==\nReferred to by the court as Jane Dudley, wife of Guildford, Jane was charged with [[high treason]], as were her husband, two of his brothers, and the former [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Thomas Cranmer]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B5P-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT172 |title=Crown of Blood: The Deadly Inheritance of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nicola|last=Tallis|date=6 December 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|via=Google Books|isbn=9781681772875}}</ref> Their trial, by a special commission, took place on 13 November 1553, at [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] in the [[City of London]]. The commission was chaired by [[Thomas White (merchant)|Sir Thomas White]], [[Lord Mayor of London]], and [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk]]. Other members included [[Edward Stanley, 3rd Earl of Derby]] and [[John Bourchier, 2nd Earl of Bath]]. As was to be expected, all defendants were found guilty and sentenced to death. Jane's guilt, of having treacherously assumed the title and the power of the monarch, was evidenced by a number of documents she had signed as \"Jane the Quene\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Her sentence was to \"be burned alive on Tower Hill or beheaded as the Queen pleases\" ([[Execution by burning#Historical usage|burning]] was the [[Burning of women in England|traditional English punishment]] for [[treason]] committed by women).<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=251\u2013252, 334}}; {{harvnb|Bellamy|1979|p=54}}</ref> The [[List of ambassadors of the Kingdom of England to the Holy Roman Emperor|imperial ambassador]] reported to [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]], that her life was to be spared.<ref name=\"odnbJane\">{{cite book| last =Plowden| first =Alison| authorlink =Alison Plowden| title =Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| chapter =Grey, Lady Jane (1534\u20131554), noblewoman and claimant to the English throne| publisher =[[Oxford University Press]]| date =23 September 2004| location =[[Oxford]]| isbn =0-19-861362-8 | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/8154| title-link =Dictionary of National Biography}}</ref> \n[[File:Lady Jane Grey letter as Queen.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Official letter of Lady Jane Grey signing herself as \"Jane the Quene\". [[Inner Temple Library]], London.]]\nThe rebellion of [[Thomas Wyatt the Younger]] in January 1554 against Queen Mary's marriage plans with [[Philip II of Spain|Philip of Spain]] sealed Jane's fate. Her father, Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk, and his two brothers joined the rebellion, and so the government decided to go through with the verdict against Jane and Guildford. Their execution was first scheduled for 9 February 1554, but was then postponed for three days to give Jane a chance to convert to the Catholic faith. Mary sent her chaplain [[John Feckenham]] to Jane, who was initially not pleased about this.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=267, 268}}</ref> Though she would not give in to his efforts \"to save her soul\", she became friends with him and allowed him to accompany her to the scaffold.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=268\u2013270}}</ref>\n\n[[File:PAUL DELAROCHE - Ejecuci\u00f3n de Lady Jane Grey (National Gallery de Londres, 1834).jpg|thumb|300px|''[[The Execution of Lady Jane Grey]]'', by the French painter [[Paul Delaroche]], 1833. [[National Gallery, London]].]]\n\nOn the morning of 12 February 1554, the authorities took Guildford from his rooms at the Tower of London to the public [[execution]] place at [[Tower Hill]], where he was beheaded. A horse and cart brought his remains back to the Tower, past the rooms where Jane was staying. Seeing her husband's corpse return, Jane is reported to have exclaimed: \"Oh, Guildford, Guildford.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|pp=274\u2013275}}</ref> She was then taken out to [[Tower Green]], inside the Tower, to be beheaded.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KZCMGgJzO2IC&pg=PA233 |title=Lady Jane Grey: A Tudor Mystery|first=Eric|last=Ives|date=19 September 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|via=Google Books|isbn=9781444354263}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the account of her execution given in the anonymous ''Chronicle of Queen Jane and of Two Years of Queen Mary'', which formed the basis for [[Raphael Holinshed]]'s depiction, Jane gave a speech upon ascending the scaffold:\n\n<blockquote>Good people, I am come hither to die, and by a law I am condemned to the same. The fact, indeed, against the Queen's highness was unlawful, and the consenting thereunto by me: but touching the procurement and desire thereof by me or on my behalf, I do wash my hands thereof in innocency, before God, and the face of you, good Christian people, this day.<ref name=\"ladyjane\">{{Cite book| contribution=1554, The Execution of Lady Jane Grey and Lord Guildford Dudley|author = Anonymous| editor-last =Nichols|editor-first=John Gough|editor-link=John Gough Nichols| title =Chronicle of Queen Jane and of Two Years of Queen Mary| publisher =[[The Camden Society]]; Marilee Hanson| year=1997|origyear =1850| url =http://englishhistory.net/tudor/executions-of-lady-jane-grey-lord-guildford-dudley/| ref=harv}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile admitting to action considered unlawful, she declared that \"I do wash my hands thereof in innocence\".<ref>{{harvnb|de Lisle|2008|p=138}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KZCMGgJzO2IC&pg=PA22 |title=Lady Jane Grey: A Tudor Mystery|first=Eric|last=Ives|date=19 September 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|via=Google Books|isbn=9781444354263}}</ref> Jane then recited [[Psalm 51]] (''Have mercy upon me, O God'') in English, and handed her gloves and handkerchief to her maid. The executioner asked her forgiveness, which she granted him, pleading: \"I pray you dispatch me quickly.\" Referring to her head, she asked, \"Will you take it off before I lay me down?\", and the axeman answered: \"No, madam.\" She then blindfolded herself. Jane then failed to find the block with her hands, and cried, \"What shall I do? Where is it?\" Probably [[Thomas Brydges|Sir Thomas Brydges]], the Deputy Lieutenant of the Tower, helped her find her way. With her head on the block, Jane spoke the last words of Jesus as recounted by [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]]: \"Lord, into thy hands I commend my spirit!\"<ref name=\"ladyjane\" />\n\nJane and Guildford are buried in the Chapel of [[Church of St Peter ad Vincula|St Peter ad Vincula]] on the north side of Tower Green. No memorial stone was erected at their grave.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B5P-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT214 |title=Crown of Blood: The Deadly Inheritance of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nicola|last=Tallis|date=6 December 2016|publisher=Pegasus Books|via=Google Books|isbn=9781681772875}}</ref> Jane's father, the Duke of Suffolk, was executed 11 days after Jane, on 23 February 1554.<ref name=\"CP\">{{cite book | last = Cokayne | first = George | title = The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain, and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant | publisher = A. Sutton | location = Gloucester | year = 1982 | isbn = 0904387828 | volume = 2 | page = 421 }}</ref> Her mother, the Duchess of Suffolk, married her Master of the Horse and [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]], [[Adrian Stokes (Master of Horse)|Adrian Stokes]], in March 1555 (not, as often said, three weeks after the execution of the Duke of Suffolk).<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|p=38}}</ref> She was fully pardoned by Mary and allowed to live at Court with her two surviving daughters. She died in 1559.\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Miniatureenlarged.jpg|thumb|right|Miniature portrait of a young lady thought by [[David Starkey]] to probably depict Lady Jane Grey.]]\n{{Main|Cultural depictions of Lady Jane Grey}}\n\"The traitor-heroine of the Reformation\", as historian [[Albert Pollard]] called her,<ref>{{cite book| last =Pollard| first =Albert J.| authorlink =Albert Pollard| title =The History of England| publisher =Longmans, Green| year =1911| location =London| page =111| url =https://www.questia.com/read/58544100}}</ref> was only 16 or 17 years old at the time of her execution. During and in the aftermath of the [[List of Protestant martyrs of the English Reformation|Marian persecutions]], Jane became viewed as a Protestant martyr for centuries, featuring prominently in the several editions of the ''[[Book of Martyrs]]'' (''Actes and Monuments of these Latter and Perillous Dayes'') by [[John Foxe]]. The tale of Lady Jane grew to legendary proportions in popular culture, producing romantic biographies, novels, plays, operas, paintings, and films. \n\nJane Grey is the only English monarch in the last 500 years (though whether her short reign was legitimate is disputed) of whom no proven contemporary portrait survives.<ref name=\"guardian\"/><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news | last =Reynolds| first =Nigel| title =The true beauty of Lady Jane Grey| work =[[The Daily Telegraph]]| date =3 June 2007| url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1544576/The-true-beauty-of-Lady-Jane-Grey.html| accessdate =11 May 2008 }}</ref> A painting in London's [[National Portrait Gallery (United Kingdom)|National Portrait Gallery]] was thought to be Jane for many years, but in 1996 it was confirmed to be of Catherine Parr.<ref name=\"yale\">{{cite web| last =Fellman| first =Bruce| title =Looking for Lady Jane| work =Yale Alumni Magazine| publisher =[[Yale University]]| date =May\u2013June 2007| url =http://archives.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/2007_05/ladyjane.html| accessdate =24 November 2014| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20141129201720/http://archives.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/2007_05/ladyjane.html| archive-date =29 November 2014| url-status =dead}}</ref> A portrait believed by some experts to be of Jane was discovered in a private home in 2005. Painted 40 to 50 years after Jane's death, the \"[[Streatham portrait]]\" (so called after the area of London in which it resided for decades) depicts a young woman dressed in a red gown, adorned with jewels and holding a prayer book.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news | last =Higgins| first =Charlotte| title =Is this the true face of Lady Jane?| work =[[The Guardian]]| date =16 January 2006| url =https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/jan/16/arts.research| accessdate =11 May 2008 }}</ref> Historian and Tudor specialist Dr. [[David Starkey]] is sceptical, \"It's an appallingly bad picture and there's absolutely no reason to suppose it's got anything to do with Lady Jane Grey\".<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Higgins \n |first=Charlotte \n |title=A rare portrait of Lady Jane Grey? Or just an 'appallingly bad picture'? \n |work=The Guardian \n |date=11 November 2006 \n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/nov/11/arts.artsnews \n |accessdate=11 February 2014 \n |ref={{sfnRef|Higgins 2006, A rare portrait}} \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NItOvhcr?url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/nov/11/arts.artsnews \n |archivedate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\nAnother portrait, a miniature, was shown to the news media in 2007 by Starkey who stated that he was \"90 per cent certain\" that it is of Lady Jane Grey.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/mar/05/artnews.monarchy|title=Miniature could be second view of Lady Jane Grey|first1=Charlotte|last1=Higgins|first2=arts|last2=correspondent|date=5 March 2007|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> This painting had been discovered at the [[Yale Center for British Art]] in America.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1544576/The-true-beauty-of-Lady-Jane-Grey.html|title=The true beauty of Lady Jane Grey|first=Nigel|last=Reynolds|date=5 March 2007|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Family tree ==\nThe following chart illustrates Jane's relationship to the [[House of Tudor]] and other claimants to the English throne. Italics indicate people who predeceased Edward VI; Arabic numerals indicate the line of succession to Edward VI at the time of his death according to Henry VIII's will; and Roman numerals indicate the line of succession at the time of Edward VI's death according to Edward's will.<ref>{{harvnb|Ives|2009|loc=Figures 1-5}}</ref>\n{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | | | | | |Harry|y|Liz| |Liz=''[[Elizabeth of York]]''|Harry=''[[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]]''}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|^|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|.| |}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | |Harry| | | | | | | |Marge| | | |Mary|y|Charlie| |Harry=''[[Henry VIII]]''|Mary=''[[Mary Tudor, Queen of France|Mary Tudor]]''|Charlie=''[[Charles Brandon, 1st Duke of Suffolk|Charles Brandon]]''|Marge=''[[Margaret Tudor]]''}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree|border=0 |Eddy| |Mary| |Bess| |Jim| |Marge| | | |Fran|y|Harry|Mary=[[Mary I]]<br>(1)|Bess=[[Elizabeth I]]<br>(2)|Eddy=[[Edward VI]]|Fran=[[Frances Brandon]]|Jim=''[[James V of Scotland]]''|Marge=[[Margaret Douglas]]|Harry=[[Henry Grey, 1st Duke of Suffolk|Henry Grey]]}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree|border=0 | | | | | | | | | | | | |Marie| |Harry| |Jane| |Kate| |Mary| | |Jane=Jane Grey<br>(3, I)|Marie=[[Mary, Queen of Scots]]|Harry=[[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley|Henry Stuart]]|Kate=[[Lady Katherine Grey|Katherine Grey]]<br>(4, II)|Mary=[[Lady Mary Grey|Mary Grey]]<br>(5, III)}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book | last = Alford| first = Stephen| title = Kingship and Politics in the Reign of Edward VI| year = 2002 | publisher = Cambridge University Press| place = Cambridge | isbn = 978-0-521-03971-0 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book|last=Alford|first=Stephen|editor=|title=Edward VI: The Last Boy King|url=|edition=|year=2014|publisher=Penguin|location=London|isbn=978-0141-97691-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ascham|first=Roger|editor=[[John Eyton Bickersteth Mayor|Mayor, John E. B.]]|title=The Scholemaster|url=https://archive.org/details/scholemasterorp00aschgoog|edition=1863|year=1863|publisher=Bell and Daldy|location=London|oclc=251212421|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Bellamy| first = John| title = The Tudor Law of Treason| year =1979 | publisher = Routlegde, Kegan & Paul| place = Toronto | isbn = 0-7100-8729-2 | ref = harv }}\n* Bindoff, Stanley T. (1953) \"A Kingdom at Stake, 1553.\" ''History Today'' 3.9 (1953): 642-28.\n* {{cite book|last=de Lisle|first=Leanda|title=The Sisters Who Would Be Queen: Mary, Katherine and Lady Jane Grey. A Tudor Tragedy|year=2008|location=New York|publisher=Ballantine Books|isbn=978-0-345-49135-0|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/sisterswhowouldb00deli_0}}\n* Hoak, Dale. (2015) \"The succession crisis of 1553 and Mary\u2019s rise to power\", in ''Catholic Renewal and Protestant Resistance in Marian England'' ed. by E. Evenden and V. Westbrook (Aldershot, 2015), pp. 17\u201342.\n* {{cite book|first=Eric|last=Ives|authorlink=Eric Ives|title=Lady Jane Grey: A Tudor Mystery |year=2009|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|location=Malden MA; Oxford UK|ref=harv|isbn=978-1-4051-9413-6}}\n* Kewes, Paulina. (2017) \"The 1553 succession crisis reconsidered.\" ''Historical Research'' (2017).  doi:10.1111/1468-2281.12178 \n* {{cite book|last=Loach|first=Jennifer|title=Edward VI|year=2002|location=New Haven|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-30009409-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Loades| first = David|authorlink=David Loades| title = John Dudley Duke of Northumberland 1504\u20131553| year = 1996 | publisher = Clarendon Press| place = Oxford | isbn = 0-19-820193-1 | ref = harv }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource portal|House of Tudor}}\n* {{commonsinline|Lady Jane Grey}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.somegreymatter.com/index.html|title=Somegreymatter.com|first=J. Stephan|last=Edwards}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n79-45478}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou |||1537|12 February|1554}}\n{{S-reg}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edward VI]]}}\n{{S-dis|title=[[List of English monarchs|Queen of England]] and [[King of Ireland|Ireland]]|years=10\u201319 July 1553|by=[[Mary I]]}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Mary I]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{English and British monarchs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grey, Jane}}\n[[Category:Lady Jane Grey| ]]\n[[Category:House of Tudor]]\n[[Category:Women of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:1530s births]]\n[[Category:1554 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:16th-century English women]]\n[[Category:16th-century English monarchs]]\n[[Category:16th-century Irish monarchs]]\n[[Category:Burials at St. Peter ad Vincula (London)]]\n[[Category:Daughters of English dukes]]\n[[Category:Dudley family]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Executed English people]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:English pretenders to the French throne]]\n[[Category:Executed English women]]\n[[Category:Executed royalty]]\n[[Category:Executions at the Tower of London]]\n[[Category:Grey family|Jane Grey]]\n[[Category:People executed by Tudor England by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People executed under Mary I of England]]\n[[Category:People executed under the Tudors for treason against England]]\n[[Category:People from Leicester]]\n[[Category:Prisoners in the Tower of London]]\n[[Category:Protestant monarchs]]\n[[Category:Queens regnant of England]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n[[Category:Dethroned monarchs]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:3a08:900:38b1:cffa:c315:9d83", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBibliography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lady_Jane_Grey"}
{"title_page": "Manchester Victoria station", "text_new": "{{redirect|Manchester Victoria}}\n{{short description|Railway station in Manchester, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| symbol2      = metrolink\n| name         = Manchester Victoria\n| image_name   = Manchester Victoria station 19-10-2009 12-11-47kopie.jpg\n| caption      = Station frontage of Manchester Victoria, constructed in 1909\n| code         = MCV\n| dft_category = B\n| pte          = [[Transport for Greater Manchester|Greater Manchester]]\n| zone         = City (D)\n| manager      = [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]\n| locale       = [[Manchester city centre]]\n| borough      = [[City of Manchester]]\n| platforms    = 6\n<!-- | usage0607    = {{pad|1em}}5.060\n| usage0708    = {{decrease}} 4.006\n| usage0809    = {{increase}} 6.174\n| usage0910    = {{decrease}} 6.146\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 6.667\n| usage1112    = {{increase}} 6.782 \n| usage1213    = {{increase}} 6.851\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 7.241 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 7.282\n| usage1516    = {{increase}} 7.630\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 8.226\n| usage1718    = {{decrease}} 8.202\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 8.950\n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.4872|-2.2424|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| years        = 1844\n| events       = Opened\n| years1       = 1902\n| events1      = Extended\n| years2       = 1993\u201396\n| events2      = Northern portion reconstructed\n| years3       = 2014\u201315\n| events3      = Renovated\n| gridref      = SJ839989\n| listing_grade    = [[Grade II listed]]\n| listing_detail   = Victoria Station including concourse to rear with restaurant and booking hall\n| listing_start    = 20 June 1988\n| listing_amended  =\n| listing_entry    = 1254725\n| listing_reference= <ref name=\"Listing\"/>\n}}\n'''Manchester Victoria station''' in [[Manchester]], England is a combined mainline railway station and [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink tram]] stop. Situated to the north of the [[Manchester city centre|city centre]] on Hunts Bank, close to [[Manchester Cathedral]], it adjoins [[Manchester Arena]] which was constructed on part of the former station site in the 1990s. Opened in 1844 and part of the [[Manchester station group]], Victoria is Manchester's busiest railway station after [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Piccadilly]] and [[Manchester Oxford Road railway station|Oxford Road]] and the busiest station managed by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] after Oxford Road.\n\nThe station hosts local and regional services to destinations in [[Northern England]], such as {{rws|Blackburn}}, {{rws|Rochdale}}, [[Bradford Interchange|Bradford]], {{rws|Leeds}}, {{rws|Newcastle}}, {{rws|Huddersfield}}, [[Halifax railway station (West Yorkshire)|Halifax]], [[Wigan Wallgate railway station|Wigan]], {{rws|Southport}}, [[Blackpool North railway station|Blackpool]] (Sundays Only) and [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool]] using the original [[Manchester and Liverpool Railway|Liverpool to Manchester line]]. Most trains calling at Victoria are operated by Northern. [[TransPennine Express]] services call at the station from Liverpool to Newcastle /Scarborough and services towards Manchester Airport (via Ordsall Chord) from Middlesbrough/Newcastle.\n\nManchester Victoria is a [[#Victoria tram stop|major interchange]] for the [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink]] [[light rail]] system. Two former railway lines into the station have been converted to [[tram]] operation: the [[Bury Line|line to Bury]] was converted in the early 1990s in the first phase of Metrolink construction, and the line [[Oldham and Rochdale Line|through Oldham to Rochdale]] was converted during 2009\u20132014. In the other direction, trams switch to on-street running when they emerge from Victoria Station and continue southwards through the city centre to Piccadilly or Deansgate-Castlefield.\n\nIn 2009, Victoria was voted the worst [[United Kingdom railway station categories|category B]] interchange station in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |title= Is Victoria UK's worst station? |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/manchester/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8364000/8364598.stm |work= BBC News |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> The station underwent a two-year \u00a344 million modernisation programme which was completed in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester Victoria station's restoration works start |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-22069010 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2013 |accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"railtechnologymagazine.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/manchester-victoria-upgrades-to-be-finished-this-month|title=Manchester Victoria upgrades to be finished this month|website=www.railtechnologymagazine.com}}</ref> Renovation entailed electrification of lines through the station, renewed Metrolink stop with an additional platform, restoration of listed features, upgraded retail units, and a new roof.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Engineering work at Manchester Victoria stops trains |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-24954232 |work=BBC News |date=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester Victoria Metrolink station closes for upgrade |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-26295791 |work=BBC News |date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=2 May 2014}}</ref> The [[Ordsall Chord]] directly linking Victoria to Oxford Road and Piccadilly was completed in December 2017. In the [[Northern Hub]] proposals, Victoria will become the rail hub for [[TransPennine Express]] and [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern Connect]] services by the end of 2020 with passenger numbers expected to rise to 12 million as a result.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Victoria Station|url= https://www.arcadis.com/en/europe/what-we-do/our-projects/uk/manchester-victoria-station/ |publisher= Arcadis |accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Manchester RJD 47.JPG|thumb|left|[[Railway Clearing House]] map of central Manchester railways in 1910]]\n[[File:Manchester Victoria's original building 1989 - geograph.org.uk - 820318.jpg|thumb|left|Part of the original 1844 station building, photographed in 1989, originally it had a single storey, the second storey was added in the 1860s.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]] (M&LR) was founded in 1836 and the company began building its line between Manchester and [[Leeds]] in 1837. Originally its line terminated at [[Manchester Oldham Road railway station|Manchester Oldham Road]] which opened on 3 July 1839. The company realised it would be advantageous to join its line to the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] (L&MR) creating a through route from Liverpool to Yorkshire with a joint station serving the centre of Manchester.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=1-5}} In 1839 [[Samuel Brooks (railway pioneer)|Samuel Brooks]], vice-chairman of the M&LR, bought land at Hunt's Bank close to the cathedral and presented it to the company for the new station. The site was on the north bank of the [[River Irk]], between the [[workhouse]] to the north which had opened in 1793 and Walker's Croft Cemetery to the south. After several years of negotiations between the companies, work started in 1842. The M&LR built an extension from [[Miles Platting]] to the station which opened on 1 January 1844. On this date, the Oldham Road terminus was closed to passenger services and became a goods station. The new station had a {{convert|852|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} long single platform which handled M&LR trains to Leeds and elsewhere at its eastern end. The L&MR extended its line from [[Ordsall, Greater Manchester|Ordsall]] to Victoria and its trains operated from the western end from 4 May 1844, on which date its [[Manchester Liverpool Road railway station|Liverpool Road station]] terminus became a goods station.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ferneyhough|1980|p=105}}</ref><ref name=\"RailofMan\">{{cite book|last1=Goode|first1=C.T.|title=The Railways of Manchester|date=1986|isbn=0-9508239-8-8|pages=19, 30\u201331}}</ref>\n\nThe station was named Victoria in 1843. Its long, single-storey building designed by [[George Stephenson]] and completed by [[John Brogden (industrialist)|John Brogden]] was approached by a wooden footbridge over the River Irk before the river was [[culvert]]ed.<ref>{{cite book  | first = J.D. | last = Marshall | title = The Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway, volume 1 | publisher = [[David and Charles]] | year = 1970 | page = 56  | isbn = 0-7153-4352-1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book  | first = Jeffrey | last = Wells | title = The Eleven Towns Railway | publisher = [[Railway and Canal Historical Society]] | year = 2000 | page = 74  }}</ref> Most of the original 1844 station buildings are standing including part of the original fa\u00e7ade on Hunt's Bank.<ref name=\"mhisnet\">{{cite web|title=Victoria Station|url=http://manchesterhistory.net/manchester/tours/tour4/area4page17.html|publisher=manchesterhistory.net|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe L&MR became part of the [[Grand Junction Railway]] in 1845, which in turn amalgamated with other railways to create the [[London and North Western Railway]] (LNWR) in 1846, and the M&LR amalgamated with other railways to create the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] (L&YR) the following year. The headquarters of the L&YR were based alongside Victoria.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=21}}\n[[File:Manchester Victoria & Exchange Stations geograph-2169556-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Platforms 11 (left) and 12 (right), looking west towards {{stnlnk|Manchester Exchange}} in 1964]]\n\n===Expansion===\nBy the mid-1840s six railway companies operated from the station connecting Manchester to London, [[Glasgow]], [[Liverpool]], [[Leeds]] and [[Sheffield]]. Victoria Station dominated the Long Millgate area and was one of the biggest passenger stations in Britain.\n\nVictoria underwent several phases of expansion as traffic grew. In 1865, four bay platforms were built on the eastern side on land reclaimed from the cemetery, and another was built on the western side, a second through platform was built at the northern side, and the station's facilities were expanded by the construction of a new east wing of the station building.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=30-33}} Two decades later, the L&YR purchased the workhouse north of the station and its site was used to build another bay and five through platforms which came into use in 1884.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=36-41}} That same year, the LNWR opened its own station, {{rws|Manchester Exchange}} immediately to the west on the opposite side of the [[River Irwell]], and vacated Victoria.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=59-62}}\n[[File:Manchester Victoria, 1968 - geograph.org.uk - 1610488.jpg|thumb|The station's bay platforms 6-10 in 1968, only the two on the right still exist.]]\n[[File:Manchester Victoria station 19-10-2009 12-20-16.JPG|thumb|right|Overlooking the station concourse in 2012 before re-development in 2014.]]\nVictoria reached its maximum extent of 17 platforms in 1904 when the station was enlarged with extra bay platforms to the south. The present station fa\u00e7ade, designed by William Dawes, was built in 1909.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=73-91}} The cast-iron [[train shed]]s behind the fa\u00e7ade were {{convert|700|yd|m|-1}} long.\n\nBecause the station handled large amounts of parcel and newspaper traffic, an overhead parcels carrier system was constructed in 1895. It consisted of an electrically powered trolley suspended from an overhead track operated by an airborne attendant. A large basket could be raised and lowered from the trolley to distribute parcels and newspapers across the station. The system operated until 1940.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=64-72}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Parcel carrier, 1912 |url=https://www.scienceandsociety.co.uk/results.asp?image=10443986 |website=Science and Society |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe L&YR merged with the LNWR on 1 January 1922. A year later, the merged company became the largest constituent of the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]] (LMS). From 16 April 1929, Victoria and Exchange station were linked by the westward extension of platform 11 over the Irwell bridge, known as platform \"11 Middle\", which joined to Exchange's platform 3 to create Europe's longest platform at {{convert|2238|ft|m}}. Crossovers enabled it to accommodate three trains arriving and departing independently.<ref>Joyce, J. (1982), Roads and Rails of Manchester 1900-1950, Ian Allan Ltd, p-23 {{ISBN|0-7110-1174-5}}</ref><ref>Marshall, John (1970), The Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway, volume 2, Newton Abbot: David & Charles, p=67 {{ISBN|0-7153-4906-6}}</ref> Exchange Station closed in 1969 and its services were transferred to Victoria.<ref name=\"LRTArailhistory\">{{cite web|title=A Brief Rail History of Manchester|url=http://www.lrta.org/Manchester/history.html|publisher=Light Rail Transit Association|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> The Exchange Station site opposite the cathedral was for many years used as a car park, until redevelopment of the site began in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manchester Exchange station|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/m/manchester_exchange/index.shtml|publisher=Disused Stations|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe station suffered bomb damage during the [[Manchester Blitz]] in [[World War II]]. On 23 December 1940, several bombs hit the station destroying the parcels office, and a large part of the roof over platforms 12 to 16. The parcels office was rebuilt, but the damaged parts of the roof were taken down and not replaced.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=124-125}} The station came into the ownership of [[British Railways]] in 1948.\n\n===Picc-Vic tunnel and Metrolink===\nProposals to build an underground station, ''Victoria Low Level'' as part of the [[Picc-Vic tunnel]] project emerged in the early-1970s.<ref name=\"piccvic-leaflet\">{{citation |date=October 1971|title=SELNEC Picc-Vic Line |publisher=SELNEC PTE }} publicity brochure</ref> The scheme proposed creating a direct rail link between Victoria and {{stn|Manchester Piccadilly}} via a tunnel and creating several underground stations in [[Manchester city centre]]. Platforms 1\u20134 at Victoria were taken out of use in 1973 in anticipation of the tunnel coming to the surface in that part of the station.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=120}}\n\nThe tunnel project was cancelled in the late 1970s because of high costs, and in the 1980s transport planners turned to [[light rail]] as a lower-cost option. As a result, the stations were linked by the [[Manchester Metrolink]] system which opened in 1992. A street-level [[tram]]way was built across the city centre linking the stations and two converted rail lines to [[Altrincham Line|Altrincham]] and [[Bury Line|Bury]].<ref name=\"RailPR\">{{cite web|title=Winning Station|last1=Coward|first1=Andy|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/rail-uk/20170104/282681866946719|website=PressReader.com|publisher=Rail Magazine|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref> The [[#Victoria tram stop|tram stop]] at Victoria replaced the former Bury Line platforms and the tram line was extended into the streets through a new entrance in the side of the station.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=128}}\n\n===Downsizing===\n[[File:Manchester Victoria - east end 1988 - geograph.org.uk - 820064.jpg|thumb|The station in 1988. Showing the former tracks, platforms and trainshed, which were removed to make way for the Manchester Arena]]\nIn the 1980s and 90s, British Rail adopted a policy of concentrating Manchester services into {{stn|Manchester Piccadilly}}. In 1989, the [[Windsor Link Line, Manchester|Windsor Link]] chord in [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]] opened, enabling many of Victoria's services from the north to be diverted to Piccadilly and in the same year, trans-[[Pennines|Pennine]] services were also transferred.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Brief Rail History of Manchester: 1980s developments|url=http://www.lrta.org/Manchester/history.html#eighties|publisher=Light Rail Transit Association|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HNWR\">{{cite book|last1=Holt|first1=Geoffery|title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain, Volume 10, The North West|date=1986|publisher=David St John Thomas|isbn=0-946537-34-8|page=244}}</ref> Victoria was reduced to six platforms, and part was sold for development. Between 1992 and 1994, the [[Manchester Arena]] was built over the northern part of the station site. Three of the five through tracks between platforms 11 and 12 were removed, along with platforms 12-17. The station was reduced to four through tracks and four through platforms, three of which were built to replace the removed platforms 12-14. They are covered by the Arena which was joined to the station by means of a raft above them. The Arena is accessed via stairs on Hunts Bank and from the station concourse. Following reconstruction, the platforms were renumbered; platforms 1 and 2 are bay platforms facing east (formerly platforms 9 and 10), and the through platforms are 3 to 6 (platform 3 was formerly platform 11). The through platforms are used by mid-distance services.<ref name=\"LRTArailhistory\"/>{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=126-129}}\n\n=== Renovation===\n[[File:Manchester Victoria roof view.JPG|thumb|right|Completed new roof at Victoria in October 2015]]\n[[File:Manchester Victoria station concourse.JPG|thumb|Station concourse following completion of the new roof.]]\n{{See also|Northern Hub}}\nIn 2009, Victoria was identified as the worst [[United Kingdom railway station categories|category B]] interchange station because of its dilapidated fabric and environment. The Transport Secretary, [[Lord Adonis]], announced that, with nine others, it would receive a share of \u00a350 million for a refurbishment programme.<ref name=\"Times-171109\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/nov/17/worst-railway-stations-britain?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Off the rails: Britain's 10 worst stations named and shamed |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |date=17 November 2009 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=7 March 2012| location=London}}</ref> Victoria's \u00a35m share of the 'Better Stations' Network Rail funding for improvements was cancelled in the June 2010 budget cuts,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10154987 |title=Manchester Victoria station's \u00a330m revamp now uncertain |work=BBC News |date=25 May 2010}}</ref> but replacement funding was arranged.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00a350m revamp for 'worst stations' |work=BBC News |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8363621.stm |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=17 November 2009}}</ref> On 16 February 2010, Network Rail announced its intention to refurbish the station as part of the Northern Hub improvement proposals turning it into an interchange for local and regional services throughout north-west England.{{citation needed|date=October 2010}} In August 2010, Network Rail announced the work would go ahead, despite the withdrawal of the \u00a35 million funding.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/victoria-revamp-to-get-go-ahead-despite-cash-895675 |title= Victoria revamp to get go-ahead despite cash blow |newspaper= Manchester Evening News |date=4 August 2010}}</ref> Station improvements included an [[ETFE]] roof, restoration of its walls, exterior canopy and period features, new platforms for additional services, improved access to the [[Manchester Arena]] and improved retail and dining facilities.<ref name=\"networkrail.co.uk\">{{cite web |url= https://www.networkrail.co.uk/running-the-railway/our-routes/lnw/north-west-electrification/ |title=North West electrification |publisher= Network Rail |accessdate=21 February 2015 |date=n.d.}}</ref>\n\nWork to refurbish the station began in April 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title= Manchester Victoria station's restoration works start |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-22069010 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2013 |accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref> The old roof was dismantled in autumn 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title= Manchester Victoria station redevelopment |url= http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/manchester-victoria-station-redevelopment/ |work= Railway Technology |accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref> Installation of the \u00a317 million roof began in May 2014 and final roof beam was lifted into position on 13 October 2014. Installation of the ETFE sheeting was completed in spring 2015, and the station upgrade was completed in August 2015,<ref name=\"railtechnologymagazine.com\"/> with the official reopening that October.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-34445622 |title=Manchester Victoria reopens after \u00a344m upgrade |work=BBC News |date=6 October 2015 |accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ordsall Chord]] was finished in 2017 and links Victoria to Piccadilly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Victoria \u2013 Timeline |url= http://www.networkrail.co.uk/Manchester-Victoria-station-timeline.aspx |publisher=[[Network Rail]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120607072223/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/Manchester-Victoria-station-timeline.aspx |archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref> It is anticipated that, after re-routing services, passenger numbers would increase to 12 million by 2019, compared with 6.6 million in 2011/12.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report for Resolution \u2013 Manchester Victoria Station |url= http://www.manchester.gov.uk/egov_downloads/Item_5__Manchester_Victoria_Station.pdf |publisher= Manchester City Council |date=20 December 2012 |accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref> The chord allows trains to run directly between Piccadilly and Victoria, shortening journey times on [[TransPennine Express]] routes between Manchester Airport and Newcastle, Middlesbrough, Hull and Scarborough. An express service from [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] to [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]] via Victoria is operated by TransPennine Express. Reinstatement of the south and west curve at [[Todmorden]] on the [[Caldervale Line]] facilitated a direct service between Victoria and [[Burnley Manchester Road]] Station for the first time in almost fifty years.\n\n===Electrification===\nIn the 1900s the [[Bury Line]], a busy commuter line which served the suburbs of north Manchester from Victoria, was losing passengers to [[Manchester Corporation Tramways|tramway competition]], in response to this, in 1914 the L&YR decided to [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|electrify]] this line using a unique 1,200 volt side-contact [[third rail]] system, in an effort to win back passengers. Electrification of this route was completed in 1916. As the scheme was a success, in the early 1920s the L&YR drew up plans to extend electrification to the [[Oldham Loop Line]] using the same system. The scheme progressed to an advanced stage, however with the reorganisations of railway companies in the 1920s, the new management had no interest in pursuing the scheme and it was dropped. This meant that the Bury Line remained as the only electrified line into Victoria, and it remained as such until 1991 when it was closed to be converted into part of the Metrolink system.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=103-105}}\n\nNo further electrification came to Victoria until the 21st century, when as part of [[Network Rail]]'s [[Northern Hub]] scheme, overhead electric wires have been erected to Victoria from [[Liverpool-Manchester lines|Manchester to Liverpool]] in 2015,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/News-Releases/Better-rail-services-become-a-reality-between-Liverpool-Lime-Street-and-Manchester-Airport-station-22b0.aspx |title=Better rail services become a reality between Liverpool Lime Street and Manchester Airport station |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=5 March 2015 |website=Network Rail Media Centre |publisher=Network Rail |access-date=5 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150309092746/http://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/News-Releases/Better-rail-services-become-a-reality-between-Liverpool-Lime-Street-and-Manchester-Airport-station-22b0.aspx |archivedate=9 March 2015 }}</ref>  and [[Manchester to Preston Line|Manchester to Preston]] and through to [[Blackpool branch lines|Blackpool]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=First electric passenger trains finally entering service in Bolton |url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/17426252.first-electric-passenger-trains-finally-entering-service-in-bolton/ |publisher=The Bolton News |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Layout==\nManchester Victoria has six railway platforms and the Metrolink stop has four (four platform faces on three tracks). Two railway platforms are bays numbered 1 & 2 for terminating trains arriving from the east, and four are through platforms numbered 3-6 at the northern side of the station. The Metrolink platforms are parallel to, and south of the bay platforms. Only the bay and Metrolink platforms are under the new roof, the through platforms 4, 5 and 6 are mostly covered by [[Manchester Arena]].\n[[File:Manchester Victoria plan.png|thumb|center|500px|Layout map of Manchester Victoria]]\n\n==Architecture and features==\nThe original M&LR single-storey offices facing Hunt's Bank Approach were built in the [[Italianate architecture|Italianate style]] in sandstone [[ashlar]] with slate roofs in 1844. They were later enlarged and given a second storey. William Dawes built the station's larger extension for the L&YR in 1909. It is at right-angles to the north end of the old station giving the enlarged station an L-shaped plan. Facing Victoria Station Approach, its fa\u00e7ade is in the [[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian neo-Baroque style]], four storeys high and 31 [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] to the rounded corner at the south-east end. The ground floor windows have rounded heads and those on the floors above are square. The ornate glass and iron canopy along the fa\u00e7ade displays the names of destinations that the station served in [[Art Nouveau]] lettering.<ref name=\"Listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num= 1254725|desc= Victoria Station including concourse to rear with restaurant and booking hall |access-date=5 April 2013}}</ref> The canopy was damaged by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]]'s [[1996 Manchester bombing|1996 bomb]] placed in a street adjacent to the [[Manchester Arndale|Arndale Centre]] and was restored four years later.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=130}}\n\nHeritage features in the concourse were restored during the 2013-15 renovation, they include the caf\u00e9 with its glass dome and mosaic lettering which was originally the first-class dining room, the adjacent bookstall, and the original 1909 wood-panelled booking hall. In the entrance is a large, white glazed tiled map showing the former network of the Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway.<ref name=\"Listing\"/><ref name=\"RailengManVic\">{{cite web|title=A bright new Victoria station|url=http://www.railengineer.uk/2015/10/07/a-bright-new-victoria-station/|publisher=Rail Engineer|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnderneath the map is a bronze [[World War I]] [[war memorial]] with effigies of [[Saint George]] and [[Saint Michael]] at each end which was installed in 1923.<ref name=\"RailengManVic\"/>{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=111}} At the south end of the concourse is the 'soldier's gate' which opened to the former fish docks from where thousands of soldiers departed for World War I and where a bronze plaque was erected to commemorate them. The gateway was restored in 2015 and a steel screen inserted featuring a map of World War I Commonwealth grave cemeteries in Northern France and Belgium.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester Victoria station officially reopens after \u00a344m overhaul|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-victoria-station-reopens-roof-10201716 |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe station received Grade II [[listed building]] status in 1988.<ref name=\"Listing\"/>\n<gallery widths=\"175px\">\nFile:Manchester Victoria Station frontage, geograph-4748353-by-Stephen-McKay.jpg|Station fa\u00e7ade, and canopy with names of destinations\nFile:Manchester Victoria station, 2015 001.jpg|Restored former first class caf\u00e9 and restaurant in the concourse\nFile:Manchester Victoria station, bar-restaurant, geograph-4695414-by-Stephen-Craven.jpg|The restored interior of the caf\u00e9.\nFile:Manchester Victoria ticket office, 2.18.jpg|Booking office\nFile:Manchester Victoria war memorial.jpg|Bronze war memorial.\nFile:Soldiers' Gate, Manchester Victoria station.jpg|Soldiers' Gate.\n</gallery>\n\n== National Rail services ==\n{{Northern (train operating company) route 9 | collapse=true}}\n[[File:Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway map at Victoria Station.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Tiled Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway map]]\n[[File:185138 at Manchester Victoria (2).jpg|thumb|TransPennine Express train at platform 4.]]\n[[File:158752 at Manchester Victoria.jpg|thumb|Northern {{brc|158}} unit at bay platform 1.]]\nManchester Victoria is served by two [[train operating company|train operating companies]], [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] and [[TransPennine Express]]. It is occasionally used by [[CrossCountry]] services during engineering works. The Chat Moss route to Liverpool is operated by TransPennine Express [[British Rail Class 185|Class 185s]] DMUs and [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] [[British Rail Class 319|Class 319]] EMUs (peak time & early morning only). The [[Ribble Valley Line]] to Blackburn and Clitheroe is operated by [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156]], [[British Rail Class 150|Class 150]] with [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153]] strengthening services at peak times . [[Caldervale Line|Leeds Calder Valley]] services are usually operated by [[British Rail Class 158|Class 158]] Sprinter DMUs, though [[British Rail Class 195|Class 195 Civity]] units are now used on many Chester trains.  New stock is also being introduced on TPE routes in 2019-20, including [[British Rail Class 68|Class 68]] ''Nova 3'' push-pull sets and [[British Rail Class 802|Class 802]] ''Nova 1'' bi-mode multiple units.\n\nSince the May 2018 timetable change, all express services on the North TransPennine route call at the station. These services are run by [[TransPennine Express]]. Westbound, two trains an hour run express to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] (one calling at [[Lea Green railway station|Lea Green]] and the other calling at [[Newton-le-Willows railway station|Newton-le-Willows]]). The other pair of services run westbound to [[Manchester Airport station|Manchester Airport]] via the [[Ordsall Chord]] and [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Manchester Piccadilly]]. Eastbound, there are 4 trains per hour running via [[Huddersfield railway station|Huddersfield]], [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]] and [[York railway station|York]]. After York, one train an hour run to each of {{rws|Edinburgh}}, [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]], [[Middlesbrough railway station|Middlesbrough]] and [[Scarborough railway station|Scarborough.]]\n\nAlso since the May 2018 timetable change, services along the [[Calder Valley line]] have been significantly sped up. Stations between [[Rochdale railway station|Rochdale]] and Manchester are now served by Blackburn services. This means that Calder Valley services now run non-stop between Rochdale and Manchester. As a result, there are now 6 trains an hour to Rochdale.\n\n=== Service summary ===\n\n==== Westbound services ====\n* 1 train per hour (tph) to {{rws|Southport}} (via {{rws|Bolton}})\n* 3tph to [[Wigan Wallgate]] via Atherton; one continues to {{rws|Kirkby}}\n* 1tph to {{rws|Preston}} (not evenings; extended to {{rws|Blackpool North}} on Sundays)\n* 1tph to {{rws|Chester}} via {{rws|Warrington Bank Quay}}\n* 2tph to {{rws|Blackburn}} via Bolton, 1tph continues to {{rws|Clitheroe}}\n* 2tph to {{Stnlnk|Liverpool Lime Street}} (express - limited stopping service also operates)\n* 2tph to {{rws|Manchester Airport}}\n* 2tpd to {{rws|Ellesmere Port}} (except Saturdays)\n* 1tpd to {{rws|Edinburgh Waverley}} (Sundays only)\n\n==== Eastbound services ====\n* 2tph to [[Rochdale railway station|Rochdale]] calling at all stations.\n* 3tph to {{Stnlnk|Leeds}} via Rochdale, then 2 via {{rws|Bradford Interchange}} & 1 via {{rws|Brighouse}}\n* 1tph to {{Stnlnk|Blackburn}} via Rochdale & {{Stnlnk|Todmorden}}\n* 2tph to {{Stnlnk|Stalybridge}} (stopping)\n* 1tph to {{rws|Scarborough}} via Leeds\n* 1tph to [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]] via Leeds\n* 1tph to [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]] via Leeds and Newcastle\n* 1tph to {{rws|Middlesbrough}} via Leeds\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line three to one|previous1={{rws|Manchester Oxford Road}}|previous2=[[Newton-le-Willows railway station|Newton-le-Willows]]|previous3=[[Lea Green railway station|Lea Green]] |next=[[Huddersfield railway station|Huddersfield]] |route=[[TransPennine Express]]<br><small>[[North TransPennine]]</small> |col={{TPX colour}}|next2=[[Stalybridge railway station|Stalybridge]] Limited service}}\n{{rail line one to two|next1=[[Moston railway station|Moston]]|next2=[[Rochdale railway station|Rochdale]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Calder Valley line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line |next=[[Ashton-under-Lyne railway station|Ashton-under-Lyne]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Huddersfield line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line two to two|previous1=[[Salford Central railway station|Salford Central]]|previous2=''Terminus''|next1=''Terminus''|next2=[[Moston railway station|Moston]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Ribble Valley line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line three routes|route1=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Manchester\u2013Preston line|Manchester to Preston Line]]</small> |previous=[[Salford Central railway station|Salford Central]] |route2=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Manchester\u2013Southport line|Manchester to Southport Line]]|route3=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Kirkby branch line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line|previous=[[Eccles railway station|Eccles]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Liverpool\u2013Manchester lines|Liverpool to Manchester Line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{s-note|text=[[:Category:Closed British railway lines|Historical Railways]]}}\n{{s-rail-national|status=Historical|toc=L&YR|route=Caldervale Line|next=Miles Platting|rows1=2|rows2=2}}\n{{s-rail-national|status=Historical|toc=L&YR|route=Huddersfield Line|next=Miles Platting|hide1=true|hide2=true}}\n{{s-rail-national|status=Historical |toc=LNWR |route=Manchester-Liverpool Line|previous=Manchester Exchange}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n== Victoria tram stop ==\n{{Infobox Manchester Metrolink station\n| name = Victoria\n| image_name = Manchester Victoria Metrolink platforms.JPG\n| caption = Victoria tram stop in October 2015\n| Metrolink Zone = 1\n|locale = [[Manchester city centre]]\n| borough = [[City of Manchester]]\n| open =\n| metrolinksince=6 April 1992\n| Metrolink line = 1\n| map_state = collapsed\n| platforms = 4\n| label_position = left\n| coordinates    = {{coord|53.4874|-2.2418|type:railwaystation_region:GB-MAN|display=inline}}<!-- n.b. centred on Metrolink plats, so slightly different from coords of main station -->\n| gridref        = SJ840990\n| status         = 1\n| original       =\n| pregroup       =\n| postgroup      =\n}}\nManchester Victoria is an interchange with the city's [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink]] [[light rail]] system. The stop is at the northern edge of the system's [[Zone 1 (Manchester Metrolink)|Zone 1]] and the start of the [[Bury Line|Bury]] and [[Oldham and Rochdale Line]]s.\n[[File:Tram entering Manchester Victoria.JPG|thumb|upright|left|A tram entering Victoria from the city-centre streets.]]\nThe tram platforms opened on 6 April 1992 for services to Bury which replaced the long-established heavy rail service. The tram platforms were built on the site of the former railway platforms 5 to 8, the terminus of the Bury line. The line was extended into the city-centre streets via a sharp curve south from the platform ends and out through a new entrance in the wall at the side of the station;{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=128}}<ref name=\"thetrams\">{{cite web|title=Victoria Metrolink stop|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/metrolink/stops/Victoria|publisher=TheTrams|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref> The system operates on some [[British Rail]] lines that have been converted to light rail operation and on-street tram tracks. In October 2009 the [[Oldham Loop Line]] was closed for conversion to a Metrolink line. It was completed in March 2014 after reopening in stages to {{tram|Rochdale town centre}}.<ref name=\"LRTABHR\">{{cite web|title=A Brief Rail History of Manchester|url=http://lrta.org/Manchester/history.html#tomlnk|publisher=LRTA|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"LRTAH1\">{{cite web|title=Metrolink History 1|url=http://lrta.org/Manchester/metrolink.html|publisher=LRTA|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 1992 Metrolink platforms consisted of an island platform containing platforms B and C, and a side platform for Bury bound trams lettered A, which was later taken out of use due to leaks in the station roof.<ref name=\"thetrams\"/>\n\nThe Metrolink platforms at Victoria closed on 21 February 2014 and were rebuilt in a different configuration to allow for increased services.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://www.metrolink.co.uk/pages/news.aspx?newsID=75 |publisher= Transport for Greater Manchester |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=7 February 2014 |title= Metrolink: Time to make Victoria posh |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140222011128/http://www.metrolink.co.uk/pages/news.aspx?newsID=75 |archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> The rebuilt stop reopened on 18 February 2015. The new configuration has two island platforms serving three tracks, with platform faces lettered A, B, C and D; the outer platforms A and D are for through trams, south and northbound respectively, and the centre platforms B & C, which both serve the same track, accommodate terminating services.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-31521777 |title= Manchester Victoria Metrolink stop reopens in \u00a344m upgrade |work=BBC News |date=18 February 2015 |accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"MCCLRTA\">{{cite web|title=Metrolink in the City Centre|url=http://lrta.org/Manchester/city_centre.html|publisher=Light Rail Transit Association|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Manchester Victoria Station Metrolink Platforms|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/4763748|publisher=Geograph.org|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref> The stop is one of the most used on the Metrolink network.<ref name=\"TfGM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gmtu.gov.uk/reports/transport2017.htm|title=Transport Statistics Greater Manchester 2017 Public Transport Section|work=TfGM|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Metrolink services ===\nAs of 2017, Metrolink services run through Victoria to [[Altrincham Line|Altrincham]], [[Bury Interchange|Bury]], {{tram|East Didsbury}}, {{tram|Manchester Airport}}, [[Oldham Mumps tram stop|Oldham]] and [[Rochdale Town Centre tram stop|Rochdale]] and [[Piccadilly tram stop|Piccadilly]]. Services mostly run every six to twelve minutes on all routes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metrolink tram times|url=https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/stops/victoria-tram|publisher=[[Transport for Greater Manchester]]|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Metrolink route map (pdf)|url=https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/network-map|publisher=TfGM|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n{{S-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=MML}}\n{{S-line|system=MML|line=Manchester Airport \u2013 Victoria|previous=Shudehill|type=Manchester Airport|type2=Victoria}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=Altrincham \u2013 Bury|previous=Shudehill|next=Queens Road|type=Altrincham|type2=Bury|rows2=2}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=Bury \u2013 Piccadilly|previous=Shudehill|next=Queens Road|type=Piccadilly|type2=Bury|hide2=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=Shaw and Crompton \u2013 East Didsbury|previous=Exchange Square|next=Monsall|type=East Didsbury|type2=Shaw and Crompton}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=East Didsbury \u2013 Rochdale Town Centre|previous=Exchange Square|next=Monsall|type=East Didsbury|type2=Rochdale Town Centre}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n[[File:Manchester Victoria 2017 Arena memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Memorial on the station concourse following the [[Manchester Arena bombing]] in May 2017. A dedicated remembrance space exists to this day.]]\n* On 19 August 1918, an electric train collided with the [[Buffer stop|buffers]], injuring 29 people.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=105}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Accident at Manchester Victoria on 19th August 1918|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=8146|website=railwaysarchive.co.uk|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n* On the early morning of 10 December 1947 a train of 20 tank wagons loaded with [[petrol]] ran out of control while descending the bank towards Victoria. To avoid a collision with another train, it was diverted into the empty bay platform 7, where it crashed through the buffers at 25&nbsp;mph, mounted the concourse, and came to a rest just short of the booking office. Swift action was taken to prevent an outbreak of fire. The train driver was killed in the collision, the fireman was injured and the guard suffered from shock.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=121}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Ministry of Transport report into the accident|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_Manchester1947.pdf|website=railwaysarchive.co.uk|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n* On 25 April 1994, two vehicles of a freight train derailed while passing through new platform six, which had opened that day. The derailed vehicles damaged the platform edging stones along most of its length, putting it out of use until it was repaired.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=129}}\n* On 15 June 1996 a [[1996 Manchester bombing|large truck bomb]] was detonated about 400 metres from the station by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]]. The blast shattered many windows along the station's facade, and glass fell onto the glass canopy causing it serious damage. The station was closed for several days. The blast also damaged the glass and steel roof over the concourse and platforms, which resulted in the removal of much of the glasswork and cladding.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=130}}<ref name=\"railmagvic\">{{cite magazine|title=Victoria: the rebirth of a railway station|url=http://www.railmagazine.com/news/rail-features/victoria-the-rebirth-of-a-railway-station/page/2|magazine=[[Rail Magazine]]|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n* On 18 October 2016, a panel of the roof, which had been built the year before, collapsed under the weight of rain water, causing minor injury to two people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-37694399|title=Injuries after Manchester Victoria Station roof collapse|date=18 October 2016|work=BBC News}}</ref> The damage was blamed on [[seagull]]s weakening the structure by pecking at the roof.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hungry seagulls blamed for Manchester Victoria station roof collapse|url=http://www.itv.com/news/granada/2017-02-22/hungry-seagulls-blamed-for-manchester-victoria-station-roof-damage/|publisher=ITV news|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n* On 22 May 2017, the station was evacuated and closed and services were cancelled following [[Manchester Arena bombing|the bombing]] at [[Manchester Arena]] which is partially above the station.<ref name=\"abc\">{{Cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/police-respond-reports-incident-manchester-arena/story?id=47569092|title=Deaths, injuries after reports of explosion at Ariana Grande concert at Manchester Arena: Police|date=22 May 2017|work=ABC News|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref> The explosion took place in the public area linking the station to the Arena immediately above the station's through platforms,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-arena-bomb-materials-photos.html|title=Found at the Scene in Manchester: Shrapnel, a Backpack and a Battery|last=Chivers|first=C.L.|work=The New York Times|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref> causing structural damage to the station which was closed resulting in significant disruption to train and tram services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Structural damage to Victoria Station after bomb|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-26/structural-damage-to-victoria-station-after-bomb/|publisher=[[itv.com|ITV]] News|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> The station reopened to traffic on 30 May 2017, following the police investigation and repairs to the fabric of the building.<ref>{{cite news|title=Manchester attack: Victoria railway station reopens|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-40089799|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> A memorial space created following the bombing exists adjacent to the 'Soldier's Gate' Memorial.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Manchester Arena bombing: K-Pop band Blackpink pay on-stage tribute |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-48353856 |work=BBC News |date=22 May 2019 |accessdate=2019-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |quote=The story of Manchester Victoria station was changed massively in May 2017 with the Manchester Arena bombing. The memorial stands, not just on the anniversary, but all year around. Perfectly kept and a fitting tribute to the twenty-two killed. |url=https://twitter.com/birdsnestsblog/status/1172848959724904449 |work=Twitter |date=14 September 2019 |accessdate=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n*On 31 December 2018, [[Manchester Victoria stabbing attack|three people, including a police officer were stabbed]] at around 20:50 GMT. A man was held on suspicion of attempted murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-46724322|title=Manchester Victoria station stabbing: Three injured|work=BBC News|date=1 January 2019|accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Greater Manchester}}\n* [[Listed buildings in Manchester-M3]]\n\n== References ==\n;Footnotes\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wray|first=Tom|title=Manchester Victoria Station|year=2004 |publisher=Peter Taylor Publications |isbn= 0-9549451-0-7 |ref= harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Axon|first=William E.|title=The annals of Manchester: a chronological record from the earliest times to the end of 1885|url=https://archive.org/details/annalsofmanchest00axon|publisher=J. Heywood, Deansgate and Ridgefield|location=Manchester and London|year=1886|ref=harv|accessdate=21 October 2013 }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Bairstow|first=Martin|title=The Manchester & Leeds Railway : the Calder Valley Line|year=1987|publisher=M. Bairstow|isbn=0-9510302-6-4|ref=harv }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Ferneyhough|first=Frank|title=Liverpool & Manchester Railway 1830\u20131980|year=1980|publisher=Book Club Associates|ref=harv }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite magazine|title=Manchester Victoria rebuild is approaching completion|magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]]|issue=341|publisher=EMAP Apex Publications|date=7\u201320 October 1998|p=11|issn=0953-4563|oclc=49953699}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Manchester Victoria station}}\n* {{stn art lnk|MCV|M31WY}}\n* [https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/stops/victoria-tram Tram times and station information] for Manchester Victoria station from [[Manchester Metrolink]]\n* [https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/stops/victoria-tram/local-map Victoria area map]\n\n{{Manchester Lines North |collapse=yes}}\n\n{{Major railway stations in Britain}}\n{{Greater Manchester railway stations |state=collapsed }}\n{{Greater Manchester Metrolink stations}}\n{{Manchester B&S}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Former Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1844]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by TransPennine Express]]\n[[Category:Tram stops in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Tram stops on the Altrincham to Bury line]]\n[[Category:Tram stops on the East Didsbury to Rochdale line]]\n[[Category:Tram stops on the Bury to Ashton-under-Lyne line]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Manchester Victoria}}\n{{short description|Railway station in Manchester, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| symbol2      = metrolink\n| name         = Manchester Victoria\n| image_name   = Manchester Victoria station 19-10-2009 12-11-47kopie.jpg\n| caption      = Station frontage of Manchester Victoria, constructed in 1909\n| code         = MCV\n| dft_category = B\n| pte          = [[Transport for Greater Manchester|Greater Manchester]]\n| zone         = City (D)\n| manager      = [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]\n| locale       = [[Manchester city centre]]\n| borough      = [[City of Manchester]]\n| platforms    = 6\n<!-- | usage0607    = {{pad|1em}}5.060\n| usage0708    = {{decrease}} 4.006\n| usage0809    = {{increase}} 6.174\n| usage0910    = {{decrease}} 6.146\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 6.667\n| usage1112    = {{increase}} 6.782 \n| usage1213    = {{increase}} 6.851\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 7.241 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 7.282\n| usage1516    = {{increase}} 7.630\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 8.226\n| usage1718    = {{decrease}} 8.202\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 8.950\n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.4872|-2.2424|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| years        = 1844\n| events       = Opened\n| years1       = 1902\n| events1      = Extended\n| years2       = 1993\u201396\n| events2      = Northern portion reconstructed\n| years3       = 2014\u201315\n| events3      = Renovated\n| gridref      = SJ839989\n| listing_grade    = [[Grade II listed]]\n| listing_detail   = Victoria Station including concourse to rear with restaurant and booking hall\n| listing_start    = 20 June 1988\n| listing_amended  =\n| listing_entry    = 1254725\n| listing_reference= <ref name=\"Listing\"/>\n}}\n'''Manchester Victoria station''' in [[Manchester]], England is a combined mainline railway station and [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink tram]] stop. Situated to the north of the [[Manchester city centre|city centre]] on Hunts Bank, close to [[Manchester Cathedral]], it adjoins [[Manchester Arena]] which was constructed on part of the former station site in the 1990s. Opened in 1844 and part of the [[Manchester station group]], Victoria is Manchester's busiest railway station after [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Piccadilly]] and [[Manchester Oxford Road railway station|Oxford Road]] and the busiest station managed by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] after Oxford Road.\n\nThe station hosts local and regional services to destinations in [[Northern England]], such as {{rws|Blackburn}}, {{rws|Rochdale}}, [[Bradford Interchange|Bradford]], {{rws|Leeds}}, {{rws|Newcastle}}, {{rws|Huddersfield}}, [[Halifax railway station (West Yorkshire)|Halifax]], [[Wigan Wallgate railway station|Wigan]], {{rws|Southport}}, [[Blackpool North railway station|Blackpool]] (Sundays Only) and [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool]] using the original [[Manchester and Liverpool Railway|Liverpool to Manchester line]]. Most trains calling at Victoria are operated by Northern. [[TransPennine Express]] services call at the station from Liverpool to Newcastle /Scarborough and services towards Manchester Airport (via Ordsall Chord) from Middlesbrough/Newcastle.\n\nManchester Victoria is a [[#Victoria tram stop|major interchange]] for the [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink]] [[light rail]] system. Two former railway lines into the station have been converted to [[tram]] operation: the [[Bury Line|line to Bury]] was converted in the early 1990s in the first phase of Metrolink construction, and the line [[Oldham and Rochdale Line|through Oldham to Rochdale]] was converted during 2009\u20132014. In the other direction, trams switch to on-street running when they emerge from Victoria Station and continue southwards through the city centre to Piccadilly or Deansgate-Castlefield.\n\nIn 2009, Victoria was voted the worst [[United Kingdom railway station categories|category B]] interchange station in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |title= Is Victoria UK's worst station? |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/manchester/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8364000/8364598.stm |work= BBC News |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> The station underwent a two-year \u00a344 million modernisation programme which was completed in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester Victoria station's restoration works start |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-22069010 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2013 |accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"railtechnologymagazine.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/manchester-victoria-upgrades-to-be-finished-this-month|title=Manchester Victoria upgrades to be finished this month|website=www.railtechnologymagazine.com}}</ref> Renovation entailed electrification of lines through the station, renewed Metrolink stop with an additional platform, restoration of listed features, upgraded retail units, and a new roof.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Engineering work at Manchester Victoria stops trains |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-24954232 |work=BBC News |date=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester Victoria Metrolink station closes for upgrade |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-26295791 |work=BBC News |date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=2 May 2014}}</ref> The [[Ordsall Chord]] directly linking Victoria to Oxford Road and Piccadilly was completed in December 2017. In the [[Northern Hub]] proposals, Victoria will become the rail hub for [[TransPennine Express]] and [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern Connect]] services by the end of 2020 with passenger numbers expected to rise to 12 million as a result.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Victoria Station|url= https://www.arcadis.com/en/europe/what-we-do/our-projects/uk/manchester-victoria-station/ |publisher= Arcadis |accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Manchester RJD 47.JPG|thumb|left|[[Railway Clearing House]] map of central Manchester railways in 1910]]\n[[File:Manchester Victoria's original building 1989 - geograph.org.uk - 820318.jpg|thumb|left|Part of the original 1844 station building, photographed in 1989, originally it had a single storey, the second storey was added in the 1860s.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]] (M&LR) was founded in 1836 and the company began building its line between Manchester and [[Leeds]] in 1837. Originally its line terminated at [[Manchester Oldham Road railway station|Manchester Oldham Road]] which opened on 3 July 1839. The company realised it would be advantageous to join its line to the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] (L&MR) creating a through route from Liverpool to Yorkshire with a joint station serving the centre of Manchester.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=1-5}} In 1839 [[Samuel Brooks (railway pioneer)|Samuel Brooks]], vice-chairman of the M&LR, bought land at Hunt's Bank close to the cathedral and presented it to the company for the new station. The site was on the north bank of the [[River Irk]], between the [[workhouse]] to the north which had opened in 1793 and Walker's Croft Cemetery to the south. After several years of negotiations between the companies, work started in 1842. The M&LR built an extension from [[Miles Platting]] to the station which opened on 1 January 1844. On this date, the Oldham Road terminus was closed to passenger services and became a goods station. The new station had a {{convert|852|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} long single platform which handled M&LR trains to Leeds and elsewhere at its eastern end. The L&MR extended its line from [[Ordsall, Greater Manchester|Ordsall]] to Victoria and its trains operated from the western end from 4 May 1844, on which date its [[Manchester Liverpool Road railway station|Liverpool Road station]] terminus became a goods station.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ferneyhough|1980|p=105}}</ref><ref name=\"RailofMan\">{{cite book|last1=Goode|first1=C.T.|title=The Railways of Manchester|date=1986|isbn=0-9508239-8-8|pages=19, 30\u201331}}</ref>\n\nThe station was named Victoria in 1843. Its long, single-storey building designed by [[George Stephenson]] and completed by [[John Brogden (industrialist)|John Brogden]] was approached by a wooden footbridge over the River Irk before the river was [[culvert]]ed.<ref>{{cite book  | first = J.D. | last = Marshall | title = The Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway, volume 1 | publisher = [[David and Charles]] | year = 1970 | page = 56  | isbn = 0-7153-4352-1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book  | first = Jeffrey | last = Wells | title = The Eleven Towns Railway | publisher = [[Railway and Canal Historical Society]] | year = 2000 | page = 74  }}</ref> Most of the original 1844 station buildings are standing including part of the original fa\u00e7ade on Hunt's Bank.<ref name=\"mhisnet\">{{cite web|title=Victoria Station|url=http://manchesterhistory.net/manchester/tours/tour4/area4page17.html|publisher=manchesterhistory.net|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe L&MR became part of the [[Grand Junction Railway]] in 1845, which in turn amalgamated with other railways to create the [[London and North Western Railway]] (LNWR) in 1846, and the M&LR amalgamated with other railways to create the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] (L&YR) the following year. The headquarters of the L&YR were based alongside Victoria.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=21}}\n[[File:Manchester Victoria & Exchange Stations geograph-2169556-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Platforms 11 (left) and 12 (right), looking west towards {{stnlnk|Manchester Exchange}} in 1964]]\n\n===Expansion===\nBy the mid-1840s six railway companies operated from the station connecting Manchester to London, [[Glasgow]], [[Liverpool]], [[Leeds]] and [[Sheffield]]. Victoria Station dominated the Long Millgate area and was one of the biggest passenger stations in Britain.\n\nVictoria underwent several phases of expansion as traffic grew. In 1865, four bay platforms were built on the eastern side on land reclaimed from the cemetery, and another was built on the western side, a second through platform was built at the northern side, and the station's facilities were expanded by the construction of a new east wing of the station building.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=30-33}} Two decades later, the L&YR purchased the workhouse north of the station and its site was used to build another bay and five through platforms which came into use in 1884.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=36-41}} That same year, the LNWR opened its own station, {{rws|Manchester Exchange}} immediately to the west on the opposite side of the [[River Irwell]], and vacated Victoria.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=59-62}}\n[[File:Manchester Victoria, 1968 - geograph.org.uk - 1610488.jpg|thumb|The station's bay platforms 6-10 in 1968, only the two on the right still exist.]]\n[[File:Manchester Victoria station 19-10-2009 12-20-16.JPG|thumb|right|Overlooking the station concourse in 2012 before re-development in 2014.]]\nVictoria reached its maximum extent of 17 platforms in 1904 when the station was enlarged with extra bay platforms to the south. The present station fa\u00e7ade, designed by William Dawes, was built in 1909.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=73-91}} The cast-iron [[train shed]]s behind the fa\u00e7ade were {{convert|700|yd|m|-1}} long.\n\nBecause the station handled large amounts of parcel and newspaper traffic, an overhead parcels carrier system was constructed in 1895. It consisted of an electrically powered trolley suspended from an overhead track operated by an airborne attendant. A large basket could be raised and lowered from the trolley to distribute parcels and newspapers across the station. The system operated until 1940.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=64-72}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Parcel carrier, 1912 |url=https://www.scienceandsociety.co.uk/results.asp?image=10443986 |website=Science and Society |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe L&YR merged with the LNWR on 1 January 1922. A year later, the merged company became the largest constituent of the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]] (LMS). From 16 April 1929, Victoria and Exchange station were linked by the westward extension of platform 11 over the Irwell bridge, known as platform \"11 Middle\", which joined to Exchange's platform 3 to create Europe's longest platform at {{convert|2238|ft|m}}. Crossovers enabled it to accommodate three trains arriving and departing independently.<ref>Joyce, J. (1982), Roads and Rails of Manchester 1900-1950, Ian Allan Ltd, p-23 {{ISBN|0-7110-1174-5}}</ref><ref>Marshall, John (1970), The Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway, volume 2, Newton Abbot: David & Charles, p=67 {{ISBN|0-7153-4906-6}}</ref> Exchange Station closed in 1969 and its services were transferred to Victoria.<ref name=\"LRTArailhistory\">{{cite web|title=A Brief Rail History of Manchester|url=http://www.lrta.org/Manchester/history.html|publisher=Light Rail Transit Association|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> The Exchange Station site opposite the cathedral was for many years used as a car park, until redevelopment of the site began in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manchester Exchange station|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/m/manchester_exchange/index.shtml|publisher=Disused Stations|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe station suffered bomb damage during the [[Manchester Blitz]] in [[World War II]]. On 23 December 1940, several bombs hit the station destroying the parcels office, and a large part of the roof over platforms 12 to 16. The parcels office was rebuilt, but the damaged parts of the roof were taken down and not replaced.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=124-125}} The station came into the ownership of [[British Railways]] in 1948.\n\n===Picc-Vic tunnel and Metrolink===\nProposals to build an underground station, ''Victoria Low Level'' as part of the [[Picc-Vic tunnel]] project emerged in the early-1970s.<ref name=\"piccvic-leaflet\">{{citation |date=October 1971|title=SELNEC Picc-Vic Line |publisher=SELNEC PTE }} publicity brochure</ref> The scheme proposed creating a direct rail link between Victoria and {{stn|Manchester Piccadilly}} via a tunnel and creating several underground stations in [[Manchester city centre]]. Platforms 1\u20134 at Victoria were taken out of use in 1973 in anticipation of the tunnel coming to the surface in that part of the station.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=120}}\n\nThe tunnel project was cancelled in the late 1970s because of high costs, and in the 1980s transport planners turned to [[light rail]] as a lower-cost option. As a result, the stations were linked by the [[Manchester Metrolink]] system which opened in 1992. A street-level [[tram]]way was built across the city centre linking the stations and two converted rail lines to [[Altrincham Line|Altrincham]] and [[Bury Line|Bury]].<ref name=\"RailPR\">{{cite web|title=Winning Station|last1=Coward|first1=Andy|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/rail-uk/20170104/282681866946719|website=PressReader.com|publisher=Rail Magazine|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref> The [[#Victoria tram stop|tram stop]] at Victoria replaced the former Bury Line platforms and the tram line was extended into the streets through a new entrance in the side of the station.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=128}}\n\n===Downsizing===\n[[File:Manchester Victoria - east end 1988 - geograph.org.uk - 820064.jpg|thumb|The station in 1988. Showing the former tracks, platforms and trainshed, which were removed to make way for the Manchester Arena]]\nIn the 1980s and 90s, British Rail adopted a policy of concentrating Manchester services into {{stn|Manchester Piccadilly}}. In 1989, the [[Windsor Link Line, Manchester|Windsor Link]] chord in [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]] opened, enabling many of Victoria's services from the north to be diverted to Piccadilly and in the same year, trans-[[Pennines|Pennine]] services were also transferred.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Brief Rail History of Manchester: 1980s developments|url=http://www.lrta.org/Manchester/history.html#eighties|publisher=Light Rail Transit Association|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HNWR\">{{cite book|last1=Holt|first1=Geoffery|title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain, Volume 10, The North West|date=1986|publisher=David St John Thomas|isbn=0-946537-34-8|page=244}}</ref> Victoria was reduced to six platforms, and part was sold for development. Between 1992 and 1994, the [[Manchester Arena]] was built over the northern part of the station site. Three of the five through tracks between platforms 11 and 12 were removed, along with platforms 12-17. The station was reduced to four through tracks and four through platforms, three of which were built to replace the removed platforms 12-14. They are covered by the Arena which was joined to the station by means of a raft above them. The Arena is accessed via stairs on Hunts Bank and from the station concourse. Following reconstruction, the platforms were renumbered; platforms 1 and 2 are bay platforms facing east (formerly platforms 9 and 10), and the through platforms are 3 to 6 (platform 3 was formerly platform 11). The through platforms are used by mid-distance services.<ref name=\"LRTArailhistory\"/>{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=126-129}}\n\n=== Renovation===\n[[File:Manchester Victoria roof view.JPG|thumb|right|Completed new roof at Victoria in October 2015]]\n[[File:Manchester Victoria station concourse.JPG|thumb|Station concourse following completion of the new roof.]]\n{{See also|Northern Hub}}\nIn 2009, Victoria was identified as the worst [[United Kingdom railway station categories|category B]] interchange station because of its dilapidated fabric and environment. The Transport Secretary, [[Lord Adonis]], announced that, with nine others, it would receive a share of \u00a350 million for a refurbishment programme.<ref name=\"Times-171109\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/nov/17/worst-railway-stations-britain?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Off the rails: Britain's 10 worst stations named and shamed |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |date=17 November 2009 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=7 March 2012| location=London}}</ref> Victoria's \u00a35m share of the 'Better Stations' Network Rail funding for improvements was cancelled in the June 2010 budget cuts,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10154987 |title=Manchester Victoria station's \u00a330m revamp now uncertain |work=BBC News |date=25 May 2010}}</ref> but replacement funding was arranged.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00a350m revamp for 'worst stations' |work=BBC News |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8363621.stm |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=17 November 2009}}</ref> On 16 February 2010, Network Rail announced its intention to refurbish the station as part of the Northern Hub improvement proposals turning it into an interchange for local and regional services throughout north-west England.{{citation needed|date=October 2010}} In August 2010, Network Rail announced the work would go ahead, despite the withdrawal of the \u00a35 million funding.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/victoria-revamp-to-get-go-ahead-despite-cash-895675 |title= Victoria revamp to get go-ahead despite cash blow |newspaper= Manchester Evening News |date=4 August 2010}}</ref> Station improvements included an [[ETFE]] roof, restoration of its walls, exterior canopy and period features, new platforms for additional services, improved access to the [[Manchester Arena]] and improved retail and dining facilities.<ref name=\"networkrail.co.uk\">{{cite web |url= https://www.networkrail.co.uk/running-the-railway/our-routes/lnw/north-west-electrification/ |title=North West electrification |publisher= Network Rail |accessdate=21 February 2015 |date=n.d.}}</ref>\n\nWork to refurbish the station began in April 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title= Manchester Victoria station's restoration works start |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-22069010 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2013 |accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref> The old roof was dismantled in autumn 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title= Manchester Victoria station redevelopment |url= http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/manchester-victoria-station-redevelopment/ |work= Railway Technology |accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref> Installation of the \u00a317 million roof began in May 2014 and final roof beam was lifted into position on 13 October 2014. Installation of the ETFE sheeting was completed in spring 2015, and the station upgrade was completed in August 2015,<ref name=\"railtechnologymagazine.com\"/> with the official reopening that October.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-34445622 |title=Manchester Victoria reopens after \u00a344m upgrade |work=BBC News |date=6 October 2015 |accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ordsall Chord]] was finished in 2017 and links Victoria to Piccadilly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Victoria \u2013 Timeline |url= http://www.networkrail.co.uk/Manchester-Victoria-station-timeline.aspx |publisher=[[Network Rail]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120607072223/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/Manchester-Victoria-station-timeline.aspx |archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref> It is anticipated that, after re-routing services, passenger numbers would increase to 12 million by 2019, compared with 6.6 million in 2011/12.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report for Resolution \u2013 Manchester Victoria Station |url= http://www.manchester.gov.uk/egov_downloads/Item_5__Manchester_Victoria_Station.pdf |publisher= Manchester City Council |date=20 December 2012 |accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref> The chord allows trains to run directly between Piccadilly and Victoria, shortening journey times on [[TransPennine Express]] routes between Manchester Airport and Newcastle, Middlesbrough, Hull and Scarborough. An express service from [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] to [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]] via Victoria is operated by TransPennine Express. Reinstatement of the south and west curve at [[Todmorden]] on the [[Caldervale Line]] facilitated a direct service between Victoria and [[Burnley Manchester Road]] Station for the first time in almost fifty years.\n\n===Electrification===\nIn the 1900s the [[Bury Line]], a busy commuter line which served the suburbs of north Manchester from Victoria, was losing passengers to [[Manchester Corporation Tramways|tramway competition]], in response to this, in 1914 the L&YR decided to [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|electrify]] this line using a unique 1,200 volt side-contact [[third rail]] system, in an effort to win back passengers. Electrification of this route was completed in 1916. As the scheme was a success, in the early 1920s the L&YR drew up plans to extend electrification to the [[Oldham Loop Line]] using the same system. The scheme progressed to an advanced stage, however with the reorganisations of railway companies in the 1920s, the new management had no interest in pursuing the scheme and it was dropped. This meant that the Bury Line remained as the only electrified line into Victoria, and it remained as such until 1991 when it was closed to be converted into part of the Metrolink system.{{sfn|Wray|2004|pp=103-105}}\n\nNo further electrification came to Victoria until the 21st century, when as part of [[Network Rail]]'s [[Northern Hub]] scheme, overhead electric wires have been erected to Victoria from [[Liverpool-Manchester lines|Manchester to Liverpool]] in 2015,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/News-Releases/Better-rail-services-become-a-reality-between-Liverpool-Lime-Street-and-Manchester-Airport-station-22b0.aspx |title=Better rail services become a reality between Liverpool Lime Street and Manchester Airport station |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=5 March 2015 |website=Network Rail Media Centre |publisher=Network Rail |access-date=5 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150309092746/http://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/News-Releases/Better-rail-services-become-a-reality-between-Liverpool-Lime-Street-and-Manchester-Airport-station-22b0.aspx |archivedate=9 March 2015 }}</ref>  and [[Manchester to Preston Line|Manchester to Preston]] and through to [[Blackpool branch lines|Blackpool]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=First electric passenger trains finally entering service in Bolton |url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/17426252.first-electric-passenger-trains-finally-entering-service-in-bolton/ |publisher=The Bolton News |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Layout==\nManchester Victoria has six railway platforms and the Metrolink stop has four (four platform faces on three tracks). Two railway platforms are bays numbered 1 & 2 for terminating trains arriving from the east, and four are through platforms numbered 3-6 at the northern side of the station. The Metrolink platforms are parallel to, and south of the bay platforms. Only the bay and Metrolink platforms are under the new roof, the through platforms 4, 5 and 6 are mostly covered by [[Manchester Arena]].\n[[File:Manchester Victoria plan.png|thumb|center|500px|Layout map of Manchester Victoria]]\n\n==Architecture and features==\nThe original M&LR single-storey offices facing Hunt's Bank Approach were built in the [[Italianate architecture|Italianate style]] in sandstone [[ashlar]] with slate roofs in 1844. They were later enlarged and given a second storey. William Dawes built the station's larger extension for the L&YR in 1909. It is at right-angles to the north end of the old station giving the enlarged station an L-shaped plan. Facing Victoria Station Approach, its fa\u00e7ade is in the [[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian neo-Baroque style]], four storeys high and 31 [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] to the rounded corner at the south-east end. The ground floor windows have rounded heads and those on the floors above are square. The ornate glass and iron canopy along the fa\u00e7ade displays the names of destinations that the station served in [[Art Nouveau]] lettering.<ref name=\"Listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num= 1254725|desc= Victoria Station including concourse to rear with restaurant and booking hall |access-date=5 April 2013}}</ref> The canopy was damaged by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]]'s [[1996 Manchester bombing|1996 bomb]] placed in a street adjacent to the [[Manchester Arndale|Arndale Centre]] and was restored four years later.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=130}}\n\nHeritage features in the concourse were restored during the 2013-15 renovation, they include the caf\u00e9 with its glass dome and mosaic lettering which was originally the first-class dining room, the adjacent bookstall, and the original 1909 wood-panelled booking hall. In the entrance is a large, white glazed tiled map showing the former network of the Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway.<ref name=\"Listing\"/><ref name=\"RailengManVic\">{{cite web|title=A bright new Victoria station|url=http://www.railengineer.uk/2015/10/07/a-bright-new-victoria-station/|publisher=Rail Engineer|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnderneath the map is a bronze [[World War I]] [[war memorial]] with effigies of [[Saint George]] and [[Saint Michael]] at each end which was installed in 1923.<ref name=\"RailengManVic\"/>{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=111}} At the south end of the concourse is the 'soldier's gate' which opened to the former fish docks from where thousands of soldiers departed for World War I and where a bronze plaque was erected to commemorate them. The gateway was restored in 2015 and a steel screen inserted featuring a map of World War I Commonwealth grave cemeteries in Northern France and Belgium.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester Victoria station officially reopens after \u00a344m overhaul|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-victoria-station-reopens-roof-10201716 |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe station received Grade II [[listed building]] status in 1988.<ref name=\"Listing\"/>\n<gallery widths=\"175px\">\nFile:Manchester Victoria Station frontage, geograph-4748353-by-Stephen-McKay.jpg|Station fa\u00e7ade, and canopy with names of destinations\nFile:Manchester Victoria station, 2015 001.jpg|Restored former first class caf\u00e9 and restaurant in the concourse\nFile:Manchester Victoria station, bar-restaurant, geograph-4695414-by-Stephen-Craven.jpg|The restored interior of the caf\u00e9.\nFile:Manchester Victoria ticket office, 2.18.jpg|Booking office\nFile:Manchester Victoria war memorial.jpg|Bronze war memorial.\nFile:Soldiers' Gate, Manchester Victoria station.jpg|Soldiers' Gate.\n</gallery>\n\n== National Rail services ==\n{{Northern (train operating company) route 9 | collapse=true}}\n[[File:Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway map at Victoria Station.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Tiled Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway map]]\n[[File:185138 at Manchester Victoria (2).jpg|thumb|TransPennine Express train at platform 4.]]\n[[File:158752 at Manchester Victoria.jpg|thumb|Northern {{brc|158}} unit at bay platform 1.]]\nManchester Victoria is served by two [[train operating company|train operating companies]], [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] and [[TransPennine Express]]. It is occasionally used by [[CrossCountry]] services during engineering works. The Chat Moss route to Liverpool is operated by TransPennine Express [[British Rail Class 185|Class 185s]] DMUs and [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] [[British Rail Class 319|Class 319]] EMUs (peak time & early morning only). The [[Ribble Valley Line]] to Blackburn and Clitheroe is operated by [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156]], [[British Rail Class 150|Class 150]] with [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153]] strengthening services at peak times . [[Caldervale Line|Leeds Calder Valley]] services are usually operated by [[British Rail Class 158|Class 158]] Sprinter DMUs, though [[British Rail Class 195|Class 195 Civity]] units are now used on many Chester trains.  New stock is also being introduced on TPE routes in 2019-20, including [[British Rail Class 68|Class 68]] ''Nova 3'' push-pull sets and [[British Rail Class 802|Class 802]] ''Nova 1'' bi-mode multiple units.\n\nSince the May 2018 timetable change, all express services on the North TransPennine route call at the station. These services are run by [[TransPennine Express]]. Westbound, two trains an hour run express to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] (one calling at [[Lea Green railway station|Lea Green]] and the other calling at [[Newton-le-Willows railway station|Newton-le-Willows]]). The other pair of services run westbound to [[Manchester Airport station|Manchester Airport]] via the [[Ordsall Chord]] and [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Manchester Piccadilly]]. Eastbound, there are 4 trains per hour running via [[Huddersfield railway station|Huddersfield]], [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]] and [[York railway station|York]]. After York, one train an hour run to each of {{rws|Edinburgh}}, [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]], [[Middlesbrough railway station|Middlesbrough]] and [[Scarborough railway station|Scarborough.]]\n\nAlso since the May 2018 timetable change, services along the [[Calder Valley line]] have been significantly sped up. Stations between [[Rochdale railway station|Rochdale]] and Manchester are now served by Blackburn services. This means that Calder Valley services now run non-stop between Rochdale and Manchester. As a result, there are now 6 trains an hour to Rochdale.\n\n=== Service summary ===\n\n==== Westbound services ====\n* 1 train per hour (tph) to {{rws|Southport}} (via {{rws|Bolton}})\n* 3tph to [[Wigan Wallgate]] via Atherton; one continues to {{rws|Kirkby}}\n* 1tph to {{rws|Preston}} (not evenings; extended to {{rws|Blackpool North}} on Sundays)\n* 1tph to {{rws|Chester}} via {{rws|Warrington Bank Quay}}\n* 2tph to {{rws|Blackburn}} via Bolton, 1tph continues to {{rws|Clitheroe}}\n* 2tph to {{Stnlnk|Liverpool Lime Street}} (express - limited stopping service also operates)\n* 2tph to {{rws|Manchester Airport}}\n* 2tpd to {{rws|Ellesmere Port}} (except Saturdays)\n* 1tpd to {{rws|Edinburgh Waverley}} (Sundays only)\n\n==== Eastbound services ====\n* 2tph to [[Rochdale railway station|Rochdale]] calling at all stations.\n* 3tph to {{Stnlnk|Leeds}} via Rochdale, then 2 via {{rws|Bradford Interchange}} & 1 via {{rws|Brighouse}}\n* 1tph to {{Stnlnk|Blackburn}} via Rochdale & {{Stnlnk|Todmorden}}\n* 2tph to {{Stnlnk|Stalybridge}} (stopping)\n* 1tph to {{rws|Scarborough}} via Leeds\n* 1tph to [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]] via Leeds\n* 1tph to [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Edinburgh]] via Leeds and Newcastle\n* 1tph to {{rws|Middlesbrough}} via Leeds\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line three to one|previous1={{rws|Manchester Oxford Road}}|previous2=[[Newton-le-Willows railway station|Newton-le-Willows]]|previous3=[[Lea Green railway station|Lea Green]] |next=[[Huddersfield railway station|Huddersfield]] |route=[[TransPennine Express]]<br><small>[[North TransPennine]]</small> |col={{TPX colour}}|next2=[[Stalybridge railway station|Stalybridge]] Limited service}}\n{{rail line one to two|next1=[[Moston railway station|Moston]]|next2=[[Rochdale railway station|Rochdale]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Calder Valley line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line |next=[[Ashton-under-Lyne railway station|Ashton-under-Lyne]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Huddersfield line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line two to two|previous1=[[Salford Central railway station|Salford Central]]|previous2=''Terminus''|next1=''Terminus''|next2=[[Moston railway station|Moston]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Ribble Valley line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line three routes|route1=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Manchester\u2013Preston line|Manchester to Preston Line]]</small> |previous=[[Salford Central railway station|Salford Central]] |route2=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Manchester\u2013Southport line|Manchester to Southport Line]]|route3=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Kirkby branch line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{rail line|previous=[[Eccles railway station|Eccles]]|route=[[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]<br><small>[[Liverpool\u2013Manchester lines|Liverpool to Manchester Line]]</small> |col={{Northern colour}} }}\n{{s-note|text=[[:Category:Closed British railway lines|Historical Railways]]}}\n{{s-rail-national|status=Historical|toc=L&YR|route=Caldervale Line|next=Miles Platting|rows1=2|rows2=2}}\n{{s-rail-national|status=Historical|toc=L&YR|route=Huddersfield Line|next=Miles Platting|hide1=true|hide2=true}}\n{{s-rail-national|status=Historical |toc=LNWR |route=Manchester-Liverpool Line|previous=Manchester Exchange}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n== Victoria tram stop ==\n{{Infobox Manchester Metrolink station\n| name = Victoria\n| image_name = Manchester Victoria Metrolink platforms.JPG\n| caption = Victoria tram stop in October 2015\n| Metrolink Zone = 1\n|locale = [[Manchester city centre]]\n| borough = [[City of Manchester]]\n| open =\n| metrolinksince=6 April 1992\n| Metrolink line = 1\n| map_state = collapsed\n| platforms = 4\n| label_position = left\n| coordinates    = {{coord|53.4874|-2.2418|type:railwaystation_region:GB-MAN|display=inline}}<!-- n.b. centred on Metrolink plats, so slightly different from coords of main station -->\n| gridref        = SJ840990\n| status         = 1\n| original       =\n| pregroup       =\n| postgroup      =\n}}\nManchester Victoria is an interchange with the city's [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink]] [[light rail]] system. The stop is at the northern edge of the system's [[Zone 1 (Manchester Metrolink)|Zone 1]] and the start of the [[Bury Line|Bury]] and [[Oldham and Rochdale Line]]s.\n[[File:Tram entering Manchester Victoria.JPG|thumb|upright|left|A tram entering Victoria from the city-centre streets.]]\nThe tram platforms opened on 6 April 1992 for services to Bury which replaced the long-established heavy rail service. The tram platforms were built on the site of the former railway platforms 5 to 8, the terminus of the Bury line. The line was extended into the city-centre streets via a sharp curve south from the platform ends and out through a new entrance in the wall at the side of the station;{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=128}}<ref name=\"thetrams\">{{cite web|title=Victoria Metrolink stop|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/metrolink/stops/Victoria|publisher=TheTrams|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref> The system operates on some [[British Rail]] lines that have been converted to light rail operation and on-street tram tracks. In October 2009 the [[Oldham Loop Line]] was closed for conversion to a Metrolink line. It was completed in March 2014 after reopening in stages to {{tram|Rochdale town centre}}.<ref name=\"LRTABHR\">{{cite web|title=A Brief Rail History of Manchester|url=http://lrta.org/Manchester/history.html#tomlnk|publisher=LRTA|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"LRTAH1\">{{cite web|title=Metrolink History 1|url=http://lrta.org/Manchester/metrolink.html|publisher=LRTA|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 1992 Metrolink platforms consisted of an island platform containing platforms B and C, and a side platform for Bury bound trams lettered A, which was later taken out of use due to leaks in the station roof.<ref name=\"thetrams\"/>\n\nThe Metrolink platforms at Victoria closed on 21 February 2014 and were rebuilt in a different configuration to allow for increased services.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://www.metrolink.co.uk/pages/news.aspx?newsID=75 |publisher= Transport for Greater Manchester |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=7 February 2014 |title= Metrolink: Time to make Victoria posh |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140222011128/http://www.metrolink.co.uk/pages/news.aspx?newsID=75 |archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> The rebuilt stop reopened on 18 February 2015. The new configuration has two island platforms serving three tracks, with platform faces lettered A, B, C and D; the outer platforms A and D are for through trams, south and northbound respectively, and the centre platforms B & C, which both serve the same track, accommodate terminating services.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-31521777 |title= Manchester Victoria Metrolink stop reopens in \u00a344m upgrade |work=BBC News |date=18 February 2015 |accessdate=21 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"MCCLRTA\">{{cite web|title=Metrolink in the City Centre|url=http://lrta.org/Manchester/city_centre.html|publisher=Light Rail Transit Association|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Manchester Victoria Station Metrolink Platforms|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/4763748|publisher=Geograph.org|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref> The stop is one of the most used on the Metrolink network.<ref name=\"TfGM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gmtu.gov.uk/reports/transport2017.htm|title=Transport Statistics Greater Manchester 2017 Public Transport Section|work=TfGM|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Metrolink services ===\nAs of 2017, Metrolink services run through Victoria to [[Altrincham Line|Altrincham]], [[Bury Interchange|Bury]], {{tram|East Didsbury}}, {{tram|Manchester Airport}}, [[Oldham Mumps tram stop|Oldham]] and [[Rochdale Town Centre tram stop|Rochdale]] and [[Piccadilly tram stop|Piccadilly]]. Services mostly run every six to twelve minutes on all routes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metrolink tram times|url=https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/stops/victoria-tram|publisher=[[Transport for Greater Manchester]]|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Metrolink route map (pdf)|url=https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/network-map|publisher=TfGM|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n{{S-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=MML}}\n{{S-line|system=MML|line=Manchester Airport \u2013 Victoria|previous=Shudehill|type=Manchester Airport|type2=Victoria}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=Altrincham \u2013 Bury|previous=Shudehill|next=Queens Road|type=Altrincham|type2=Bury|rows2=2}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=Bury \u2013 Piccadilly|previous=Shudehill|next=Queens Road|type=Piccadilly|type2=Bury|hide2=yes}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=Shaw and Crompton \u2013 East Didsbury|previous=Exchange Square|next=Monsall|type=East Didsbury|type2=Shaw and Crompton}}\n{{s-line|system=MML|line=East Didsbury \u2013 Rochdale Town Centre|previous=Exchange Square|next=Monsall|type=East Didsbury|type2=Rochdale Town Centre}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n[[File:Manchester Victoria 2017 Arena memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Memorial on the station concourse following the [[Manchester Arena bombing]] in May 2017. A dedicated remembrance space exists to this day.]]\n* On 19 August 1918, an electric train collided with the [[Buffer stop|buffers]], injuring 29 people.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=105}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Accident at Manchester Victoria on 19th August 1918|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=8146|website=railwaysarchive.co.uk|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n* On the early morning of 10 December 1947 a train of 20 tank wagons loaded with [[petrol]] ran out of control while descending the bank towards Victoria. To avoid a collision with another train, it was diverted into the empty bay platform 7, where it crashed through the buffers at 25&nbsp;mph, mounted the concourse, and came to a rest just short of the booking office. Swift action was taken to prevent an outbreak of fire. The train driver was killed in the collision, the fireman was injured and the guard suffered from shock.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=121}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Ministry of Transport report into the accident|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_Manchester1947.pdf|website=railwaysarchive.co.uk|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n* On 25 April 1994, two vehicles of a freight train derailed while passing through new platform six, which had opened that day. The derailed vehicles damaged the platform edging stones along most of its length, putting it out of use until it was repaired.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=129}}\n* On 15 June 1996 a [[1996 Manchester bombing|large truck bomb]] was detonated about 400 metres from the station by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]]. The blast shattered many windows along the station's facade, and glass fell onto the glass canopy causing it serious damage. The station was closed for several days. The blast also damaged the glass and steel roof over the concourse and platforms, which resulted in the removal of much of the glasswork and cladding.{{sfn|Wray|2004|p=130}}<ref name=\"railmagvic\">{{cite magazine|title=Victoria: the rebirth of a railway station|url=http://www.railmagazine.com/news/rail-features/victoria-the-rebirth-of-a-railway-station/page/2|magazine=[[Rail Magazine]]|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n* On 18 October 2016, a panel of the roof, which had been built the year before, collapsed under the weight of rain water, causing minor injury to two people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-37694399|title=Injuries after Manchester Victoria Station roof collapse|date=18 October 2016|work=BBC News}}</ref> The damage was blamed on [[seagull]]s weakening the structure by pecking at the roof.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hungry seagulls blamed for Manchester Victoria station roof collapse|url=http://www.itv.com/news/granada/2017-02-22/hungry-seagulls-blamed-for-manchester-victoria-station-roof-damage/|publisher=ITV news|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n* On 22 May 2017, the station was evacuated and closed and services were cancelled following [[Manchester Arena bombing|the bombing]] at [[Manchester Arena]] which is partially above the station.<ref name=\"abc\">{{Cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/police-respond-reports-incident-manchester-arena/story?id=47569092|title=Deaths, injuries after reports of explosion at Ariana Grande concert at Manchester Arena: Police|date=22 May 2017|work=ABC News|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref> The explosion took place in the public area linking the station to the Arena immediately above the station's through platforms,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-arena-bomb-materials-photos.html|title=Found at the Scene in Manchester: Shrapnel, a Backpack and a Battery|last=Chivers|first=C.L.|work=The New York Times|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref> causing structural damage to the station which was closed resulting in significant disruption to train and tram services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Structural damage to Victoria Station after bomb|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-26/structural-damage-to-victoria-station-after-bomb/|publisher=[[itv.com|ITV]] News|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> The station reopened to traffic on 30 May 2017, following the police investigation and repairs to the fabric of the building.<ref>{{cite news|title=Manchester attack: Victoria railway station reopens|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-40089799|work=BBC news|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> A memorial space created following the bombing exists adjacent to the 'Soldier's Gate' Memorial.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Manchester Arena bombing: K-Pop band Blackpink pay on-stage tribute |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-48353856 |work=BBC News |date=22 May 2019 |accessdate=2019-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |quote=The story of Manchester Victoria station was changed massively in May 2017 with the Manchester Arena bombing. The memorial stands, not just on the anniversary, but all year around. Perfectly kept and a fitting tribute to the twenty-two killed. |url=https://twitter.com/birdsnestsblog/status/1172848959724904449 |work=Twitter |date=14 September 2019 |accessdate=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n*On 31 December 2018, [[Manchester Victoria stabbing attack|three people, including a police officer were stabbed]] at around 20:50 GMT. A man was held on suspicion of attempted murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-46724322|title=Manchester Victoria station stabbing: Three injured|work=BBC News|date=1 January 2019|accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Greater Manchester}}\n* [[Listed buildings in Manchester-M3]]\n\n== References ==\n;Footnotes\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wray|first=Tom|title=Manchester Victoria Station|year=2004 |publisher=Peter Taylor Publications |isbn= 0-9549451-0-7 |ref= harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Axon|first=William E.|title=The annals of Manchester: a chronological record from the earliest times to the end of 1885|url=https://archive.org/details/annalsofmanchest00axon|publisher=J. Heywood, Deansgate and Ridgefield|location=Manchester and London|year=1886|ref=harv|accessdate=21 October 2013 }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Bairstow|first=Martin|title=The Manchester & Leeds Railway : the Calder Valley Line|year=1987|publisher=M. Bairstow|isbn=0-9510302-6-4|ref=harv }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Ferneyhough|first=Frank|title=Liverpool & Manchester Railway 1830\u20131980|year=1980|publisher=Book Club Associates|ref=harv }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite magazine|title=Manchester Victoria rebuild is approaching completion|magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]]|issue=341|publisher=EMAP Apex Publications|date=7\u201320 October 1998|p=11|issn=0953-4563|oclc=49953699}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Manchester Victoria station}}\n* {{stn art lnk|MCV|M31WY}}\n* [https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/stops/victoria-tram Tram times and station information] for Manchester Victoria station from [[Manchester Metrolink]]\n* [https://tfgm.com/public-transport/tram/stops/victoria-tram/local-map Victoria area map]\n\n{{Manchester Lines North |collapse=yes}}\n\n{{Major railway stations in Britain}}\n{{Greater Manchester railway stations |state=collapsed }}\n{{Greater Manchester Metrolink stations}}\n{{Manchester B&S}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Former Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1844]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by TransPennine Express]]\n[[Category:Tram stops in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Tram stops on the Altrincham to Bury line]]\n[[Category:Tram stops on the East Didsbury to Rochdale line]]\n[[Category:Tram stops on the Bury to Ashton-under-Lyne line]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccidents and incidents:Caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manchester_Victoria_station"}
{"title_page": "Amelia Adams", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Amy Adams}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name                 = Amelia Adams\n|image                = \n|caption              = \n|birth_name           = Amelia Charlton\n|birth_date           = {{birth year and age|1983}}\n|birth_place          = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales|NSW]], Australia \n|residence            = \n|education            = \n|occupation           = {{hlist|[[Journalist]]|[[news presenter]]|producer|reporter}} \n|years_active         = 2003-present    \n|employer             = [[Nine Network]]\n|spouse               = Luke Adams\n|children             = 2 \n|awards               = \n|website              = \n}}\n'''Amelia Adams''' ({{n\u00e9e}} '''Charlton''') is an Australian journalist, news presenter, producer and reporter.\n\n==Early career==\nIn 2003, Adams completed a Bachelor of Communications in Journalism at [[Charles Sturt University]] and whilst she was completing her degree she worked at Sky News Australia. She has also worked as a producer and reporter at the Seven Network on ''[[Seven News]]'' and ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'', and in 2005 moved to Network Ten in Brisbane to be a reporter and presenter on ''[[Ten News]]''.\n\n==Nine Network==\nIn May 2008, Adams moved to the [[Nine Network]] in Sydney to become a general reporter on ''[[Nine News]]''. She has been a regular fill in presenter for a number of ''Nine News'' bulletins and a fill-in news presenter on ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' and ''[[Weekend Today (Australian TV series)|Weekend Today]]''. In 2012, she presented ''Nine Morning News'' and ''Nine Afternoon News'' whilst regular presenter [[Wendy Kingston]] was on maternity leave.\n\nIn January 2013, Adams was appointed presenter for both ''Nine Morning News'' and ''Nine Afternoon News'' with Kingston becoming presenter of ''Nine News Now''. In October 2014, Adams returned from maternity leave to front ''Nine News Now'' from Tuesday to Friday with [[Amber Sherlock]] hosting on Monday. In May 2016, Adams was appointed presenter of ''Nine Morning News'' and ''Nine Afternoon News'' while [[Davina Smith]] went on maternity leave.\n\nIn May 2018, Adams was appointed as ''[[Nine News]]'' Europe correspondent. She relocated to London with her family in July.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Euro correspondent for Nine News|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/05/new-euro-correspondent-for-nine-news.html|accessdate=10 May 2018|publisher=TV Tonight|date=10 May 2018}}</ref>  \n\nAmelia remained as Europe correspondent until January 2020, she later moved to Los Angeles to become ''[[Nine News]]'' United States correspondent.\n\n==Personal life==\nAs the daughter of a pilot, Adams spent time growing up in France where she learnt the language.<ref name=\"Meet the ttn presenters\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mercurynie.com.au/ttnpresenters.htm |title=Meet the ttn presenters|publisher=Hobart Mercury|accessdate=2013-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, she married freelance cameraman and photographer Luke Adams in Byron Bay.<ref name=\"Charlton's Big Splash\">{{cite web |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/amelia-charltons-big-splash/story-e6freq7x-1111115475135 |title=Amelia Charlton's Big Splash |publisher=[[The Courier Mail]] |accessdate=2013-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Adams announced that she was pregnant with her first child. She gave birth to a son in March 2014.<ref name=DT>{{cite news|title=Reading news all in a mum's day's work for Amelia Adams|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/reading-news-all-in-a-mums-days-work-for-amelia-adams/story-fni0cvc9-1227102841030|accessdate=21 May 2015|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=27 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, she announced that she was pregnant with her second child. She gave birth to her second child in November 2016. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121113204545/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/meet-the-team/national/amelia-adams Amelia Adams profile]\n*[http://news.ninemsn.com.au Nine News]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News Now]]''<br />Presenter\n| before = [[Alison Ariotti]]\n| after = Amber Sherlock\n| years = October 2014 - May 2016\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News|Nine Morning News]]''<br />Presenter (Monday - Thursday)\n| before = [[Wendy Kingston]]\n| after = [[Sophie Walsh]]\n| years = May 2016 - July 2018\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News|Nine Afternoon News]]''<br />Presenter (Monday - Thursday)\n| before = [[Wendy Kingston]]\n| after = [[Sophie Walsh]]\n| years = May 2016 - July 2018\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NineNewsAnchors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Amelia}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nine News presenters]]\n[[Category:Charles Sturt University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Amy Adams}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name                 = Amelia Adams\n|image                = \n|caption              = \n|birth_name           = Amelia Charlton\n|birth_date           = {{birth year and age|1983}}\n|birth_place          = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales|NSW]], Australia \n|residence            = \n|education            = \n|occupation           = {{hlist|[[Journalist]]|[[news presenter]]|producer|reporter}} \n|employer             = [[Nine Network]]\n|years_active         = 2003-present         \n|spouse               = Luke Adams\n|children             = 2 \n|awards               = \n|website              = \n}}\n'''Amelia Adams''' ({{n\u00e9e}} '''Charlton''') is an Australian journalist, news presenter, producer and reporter.\n\n==Early career==\nIn 2003, Adams completed a Bachelor of Communications in Journalism at [[Charles Sturt University]] and whilst she was completing her degree she worked at Sky News Australia. She has also worked as a producer and reporter at the Seven Network on ''[[Seven News]]'' and ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'', and in 2005 moved to Network Ten in Brisbane to be a reporter and presenter on ''[[Ten News]]''.\n\n==Nine Network==\nIn May 2008, Adams moved to the [[Nine Network]] in Sydney to become a general reporter on ''[[Nine News]]''. She has been a regular fill in presenter for a number of ''Nine News'' bulletins and a fill-in news presenter on ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' and ''[[Weekend Today (Australian TV series)|Weekend Today]]''. In 2012, she presented ''Nine Morning News'' and ''Nine Afternoon News'' whilst regular presenter [[Wendy Kingston]] was on maternity leave.\n\nIn January 2013, Adams was appointed presenter for both ''Nine Morning News'' and ''Nine Afternoon News'' with Kingston becoming presenter of ''Nine News Now''. In October 2014, Adams returned from maternity leave to front ''Nine News Now'' from Tuesday to Friday with [[Amber Sherlock]] hosting on Monday. In May 2016, Adams was appointed presenter of ''Nine Morning News'' and ''Nine Afternoon News'' while [[Davina Smith]] went on maternity leave.\n\nIn May 2018, Adams was appointed as ''[[Nine News]]'' Europe correspondent. She relocated to London with her family in July.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Euro correspondent for Nine News|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/05/new-euro-correspondent-for-nine-news.html|accessdate=10 May 2018|publisher=TV Tonight|date=10 May 2018}}</ref>  \n\nAmelia remained as Europe correspondent until January 2020, she later moved to Los Angeles to become ''[[Nine News]]'' United States correspondent.\n\n==Personal life==\nAs the daughter of a pilot, Adams spent time growing up in France where she learnt the language.<ref name=\"Meet the ttn presenters\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mercurynie.com.au/ttnpresenters.htm |title=Meet the ttn presenters|publisher=Hobart Mercury|accessdate=2013-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, she married freelance cameraman and photographer Luke Adams in Byron Bay.<ref name=\"Charlton's Big Splash\">{{cite web |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/amelia-charltons-big-splash/story-e6freq7x-1111115475135 |title=Amelia Charlton's Big Splash |publisher=[[The Courier Mail]] |accessdate=2013-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Adams announced that she was pregnant with her first child. She gave birth to a son in March 2014.<ref name=DT>{{cite news|title=Reading news all in a mum's day's work for Amelia Adams|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/reading-news-all-in-a-mums-days-work-for-amelia-adams/story-fni0cvc9-1227102841030|accessdate=21 May 2015|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=27 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, she announced that she was pregnant with her second child. She gave birth to her second child in November 2016. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121113204545/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/meet-the-team/national/amelia-adams Amelia Adams profile]\n*[http://news.ninemsn.com.au Nine News]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News Now]]''<br />Presenter\n| before = [[Alison Ariotti]]\n| after = Amber Sherlock\n| years = October 2014 - May 2016\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News|Nine Morning News]]''<br />Presenter (Monday - Thursday)\n| before = [[Wendy Kingston]]\n| after = [[Sophie Walsh]]\n| years = May 2016 - July 2018\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News|Nine Afternoon News]]''<br />Presenter (Monday - Thursday)\n| before = [[Wendy Kingston]]\n| after = [[Sophie Walsh]]\n| years = May 2016 - July 2018\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NineNewsAnchors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Amelia}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nine News presenters]]\n[[Category:Charles Sturt University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "122.105.86.254", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/