{"title_page": "Bertie Crewe", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Bertie Crewe\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = <!-- if image is smaller than 250px -->\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = {{Birth year|1860}} \n| birth_place           = [[Essex]], England\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|df=y|1937|01|10|1860|01|01}}\n| death_place           = \n| other_names           = \n| nationality           = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| alma_mater            = \n| spouse                = \n| partner               = \n| children              = \n| parents               = \n| awards                = \n| practice              = Associated architectural firm[s]\n| significant_buildings = [[Piccadilly Theatre]], London<br />[[Palace Theatre, Manchester|Palace Theatre]], Manchester<br />[[Shaftesbury Theatre]], London<br />[[Theatre Royal, Bury St Edmunds|Theatre Royal]], Bury St Edmunds\n| significant_projects  = \n| significant_design    = \n| signature             = \n| website               =  <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n{{Portal|Architecture}}\n'''William Robert 'Bertie' Crewe''' (1860, [[Essex]] \u2013 10 January 1937, [[London]]) was one of the leading [[English people|English]] theatre architects in the boom of 1885 to 1915.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Essex and partly trained by [[Frank Matcham]], Crewe and his contemporaries [[W.G.R. Sprague]] and [[Thomas Verity]], were together responsible for the majority \u2013 certainly more than 200 \u2013 of the theatres and variety palaces of the great building boom which took place in Britain between 1885 and 1915, peaking at the turn of the century.<ref>{{cite web | title = New venues and some older ones | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131209124145/http://thelondonseason.com/newvenues.htm | archive-date = 9 December 2013 | url = http://www.thelondonseason.com/newvenues.htm | website = thelondonseason.com | publisher = thelondonseason }}</ref> Crewe became known as one of the most dynamic architects of the 1890s-1900s, specialising entirely in theatres and later cinemas. He also designed the [[Alhambra-Maurice Chevalier|Paris Alhambra]] for [[Thomas Barrasford]], which opened in 1904.\n\nCrewe trained in [[Paris]] and [[London]], where, as a young man, he was a frequent visitor to Frank Matcham's home. Up to the mid-1890s, Crewe collaborated with Sprague, producing the Lincoln Theatre Royal as well as a number of theatres around London. It was after he branched out on his own that he developed what was to become his characteristic Baroque-influenced style. His work around the turn of the century was marked by horizontal balconies tied to ranges of stage boxes and elaborate ornamental features.<ref>{{cite web | title = Theatreland: Architects - Bertie Crewe (d. 1937) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071202131222/http://corpoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/text.asp?ID=334 | archive-date = 2 December 2007 | url = http://www.corpoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/text.asp?ID=334 | website = corpoflondon.gov.uk | publisher = London Metropolitan Archives: Learning Zone }}</ref> [[Cecil Masey]] trained in Crewe's office, working on large theatres and music halls that Crewe designed before the [[First World War]]. Masey's designs include the theatre at [[Stanford Hall, Nottinghamshire]]. In the early 1930s Masey worked for [[Sidney Bernstein, Baron Bernstein|Sidney Bernstein]] on the creation of the Granada cinema circuit, including the Tooting Granada.\n\nCrewe's last project, jointly with Henry G. Kay was the Regal, Kennington Road (opened 17 November 1937) by the Arthur O'Connor circuit. Designed as split theatre-cinema, the Edwardian Kennington Empire would have been in decline by the time of building.<ref>{{cite web | title = GALLERY- October 2004 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081015175359/http://merciacinema.org/gallery1004.htm | archive-date = 15 October 2008 | url = http://www.merciacinema.org.uk/gallery1004.htm | website = merciacinema.org.uk | publisher = Mercia Cinema | date = October 2004 }}</ref>\n\n==After death==\nAfter [[World War II]], many theatres that were not destroyed by bombing were in the way of redevelopment. The building boom of 1885 to 1915 was matched between 1950 and 1975 by theatre demolition. In that 25-year period, 35 theatres were demolished in [[Greater London]] alone.\n\nCrewe's reputation has been re-established over the last 20 years. In 2004, the [[Palace Theatre, Redditch]], (built 1913) completed a \u00a33.7&nbsp;million facelift. A now rare example of Edwardian theatre, it was successful in bidding for a Heritage Lottery Fund grant. Experts believe the Grade II-listed theatre is one of only six examples that can be fully attributed to Bertie Crewe.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Rare theatre revamped to its best |date=23 January 2006 |work=[[BBC News]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/4639830.stm |accessdate= 10 August 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Theatres==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=\"170\" align=center|Theatre\n!width=\"120\" align=center|Location\n!align=center|Build Date\n!align=center|Original Seating Capacity\n!align=center|Screens\n!width=\"110\" align=center|Status\n!align=center|Notes\n|-\n|[[Royal Court Theatre]]\n|[[London]]\n|1888\n|642\n|\n|\n|As sub to [[Walter Emden]]. Next to the Metropolitan railway station (now Sloane Square tube). Reconstructed in 1952 and 1980. An unimpressive auditorium, whose sight-lines could be improved, is the strangely antique setting for modern drama that generally preaches change\n|-\n|[[Theatre Royal, Lincoln|Theatre Royal]]\n|[[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]]\n|1889\n|475\n|\n|Refurbished\n|Reopened after refurbishment 2010<ref>{{cite web | title = Hire venue | url = http://www.lincolntheatreroyal.com/hire.html | website = lincolntheatreroyal.com | publisher = Lincoln Theatre Royal | access-date = 2 August 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160716000215/http://www.lincolntheatreroyal.com/hire.html | archive-date = 16 July 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Olympic Theatre|Olympic]]\n|[[London]]\n|1890\n|\n|\n|Demolished\n|With [[W.G.R. Sprague]]\n|-\n|[[Theatre Royal, Aldershot|Theatre Royal]]\n|[[Aldershot]]\n|16 February 1891\n|700\n|\n|Demolished 1959\n|With [[W. G. R. Sprague]]\n|-\n|Euston Theatre of Varieties\n|[[Euston Road|Euston]]\n|26 December 1900\n|1,310\n|\n|Demolished 1960\n|With Wylson & Long. In use as a Cinema from the mid-1930s to 1950, then renamed the Regent Theatre<ref>{{cite web | title = Cinemas: Cinemas Around the World - Regent Theatre, London UK | url = http://www.cinematour.com/tour/fo/5552.html | website = cinematour.com | publisher = CinemaTour }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Sadler's Wells Theatre|Sadler's Wells]]\n|[[London]]\n|1901\n|\n|\n|Fifth theatre demolished 1996\n|Remodelled\n|-\n|Liverpool Royal Hippodrome\n|[[Liverpool]]\n|1902\n|4,000\n|\n|Demolished 1984\n|The first of the Barrasford halls. The ceiling was painted by Secard, depicting flying cupids upon beds of clouds. From 1931-1967 it was a cinema\n|-\n|Hippodrome\n|[[Brighton]]\n|1902\n|2,000\n|\n|Alterations \n|Frank Matcham converted a skating rink into a circus in 1901. When Thomas Barrasford bought the Hippodrome in October 1902 he called in Crewe to replace the circus ring with raked stalls seating, add boxes where the animal entrances has been and extend the apron with a new orchestra pit in front\n|-\n|[[Lyceum Theatre (London)|Lyceum]]\n|[[London]]\n|1904\n|2,000\n|\n|New Auditorium\n|Built behind Samuel Beazley's original facade and portico\n|-\n|[[Pavilion Theatre (Glasgow)|Pavilion]]\n|[[Glasgow]]\n|1904\n|1.499\n|\n|\n|Now renovated, the theatre is a remarkable original survivor as a commercial theatre. Built for Tom Barrasford.\n|-\n|Palace\n|[[Gorbals]], [[Glasgow]]\n|1904\n|2,000\n|\n|Demolished 1976\n|Cine-variety from 1914, sold to H Maitles. Bingo from 1962\n|-\n|[[Theatre Royal, Bury St Edmunds|Theatre Royal]]\n|[[Bury St Edmunds]]\n|1906\n|\n|\n|Alterations\n|Designed by William Wilkins it opened on 11 October 1819. Redesigned by Crewe in 1906. [[Greene King]] purchased the freehold in 1920, but closed in 1925 and used as a barrel store. Air Vice-Marshal Stanley Vincent raised over \u00a337,000 to restore and re-open the Theatre Royal in 1965, and leased to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] in 1975 on a 999-year lease\n|-\n|Sheffield Hippodrome\n|[[Sheffield]]\n|23 December 1907\n|\n|\n|Demolished 1963<ref>{{cite web | title = Theatres and Halls in Sheffield, South Yorkshire: The Hippodrome Theatre of Varieties, Cambridge Street, Sheffield | url =http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/SheffieldTheatres.htm#hippodrome | website = arthurlloyd.co.uk | publisher = Arthur Lloyd Theatres }}</ref>\n|One of several large Hippodromes opened by Tom Barrasford in direct opposition to [[Oswald Stoll]], then managing director of Moss Theatres\n|-\n|Royal Hippodrome\n|[[Belfast]]\n|1907\n|1,156\n|\n|Demolished, now the site of the modern extension of the [[Grand Opera House, Belfast]] and Fitzwilliam Hotel\n|Became cinema in 1935, Odeon in 1961, and New Victoria Cinema in 1974. Bingo Hall in approx 1987 with occasional theatre use. Closed 1988. Demolished 1997\n|-\n|Nottingham Hippodrome\n|[[Nottingham]]\n|28 September 1908\n|\n|\n|\n|The last Hippodrome to be erected by [[Thomas Barrasford]]\n|-\n|Hippodrome\n|[[Plymouth]]\n|1908\n|\n|\n|Destroyed by bombing and fire in 1941<ref>{{cite web | title = Music halls | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121103083505/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/stephen.pomeroy/local/musichal.pdf | archive-date = 3 November 2012 | url = http://homepag