]]<ref>{{cite web | title = About us: about the theatre | url = http://www.shaftesburytheatre.com/about-us/about-the-theatre/ | website = shaftesburytheatre.com | publisher = Shaftesbury Theatre }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Peacock Theatre#History|London Opera House / Stoll]]\n|[[London]]\n|1911\n|2,660\n|\n|Demolished 1958, became site for an office block. \n|Designed for [[Oscar Hammerstein I|Oscar Hammerstein]] in 1912, sold to London Opera House Ltd (a newly formed company) in 1913, transformed into a cinema by [[Oswald Stoll]] in 1916. A smaller theatre, The Royalty, built nearby opened 1960. Renamed The Peacock Theatre it presented the [[Paul Raymond (publisher)|Paul Raymond]] revues. Today the Peacock is owned by the [[London School of Economics]], it is a lecture theatre by day and home of [[Sadler's Wells]]' West End programme by night.<ref>{{cite web | title = The Peacock Theatre, Kingsway, London: Formerly - The London Opera House / National Theatre of England / Stoll Picture Theatre / Stoll Theatre / Royalty Theatre  | url = http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/Stoll.htm | website = arthurlloyd.co.uk | publisher = Arthur Lloyd Theatres }}</ref>\n|-\n|Empire Burnley\n|[[Burnley]]\n|1911\n|1,200\n|\n|Auditorium reconstructed\n|Built 1894 under G.B. Rawcliffe. Converted to a cinema in 1938, now a [[Gala Bingo]]\n|-\n|[[The Hippodrome, Aldershot|The Hippodrome]]\n|[[Aldershot]]\n|3 February 1913\n|1,000\n|\n|Demolished 1961\n|Partly refurbished, it reopened fitfully until about 1960\n|-\n|-\n|[[Golders Green Hippodrome]]\n|[[Golders Green]]\n|1913\n|3,000\n|\n|Sold, controversially, to [[El Shaddai International Christian Centre]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Anger as church buys hippodrome | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6506043.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | publisher = [[BBC]] |date = 29 March 2007 | access-date = 28 July 2012 }}</ref>\n|Former home of the [[BBC Concert Orchestra]]<ref>{{cite web | title = The BBC's TV studios in London: Golders Green Hippodrome | url = http://www.tvstudiohistory.co.uk/old%20bbc%20studios.htm#golders%20green | website = tvstudiohistory.co.uk | publisher = An incomplete history of London's television studios | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070603161037/http://www.tvstudiohistory.co.uk/old%20bbc%20studios.htm#golders%20green | archivedate = 3 June 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[The Holme]]\n|[[Regent's Park]]\n|1911\n|Private House\n|\n|\n|First villa to be erected in [[Regent's Park]]. Designed in 1816-18 by [[Decimus Burton]] aged 18 for his father, James Burton. Further wings were added in 1911 by Bertie Crewe. More alterations were carried out in 1935<ref>{{cite web | title = The Holme | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090104172357/http://www.members.lycos.co.uk/Catherine_Slater/Holme.htm | archive-date = 4 January 2009 | url = http://members.lycos.co.uk/Catherine_Slater/Holme.htm | website = members.lycos.co.uk/Catherine_Slater | publisher = Catherine Slater }}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Palace Theatre, Manchester|Palace Theatre]]\n|[[Manchester]]\n|1913\n|1,955\n|\n|Auditorium Reconstructed. Now leased to Ambassador Theatre Group\n|Built in 1891 by [[Alfred Darbyshire]] & F B Smith as the ''Manchester Palace of Varietie''. The first computerised box office system in Europe was installed. Owned by the Palace Theatre Trust<ref>{{cite web | title = Manchester: Palace Theatre | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160315160235/http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/carthalia/uk/uk_manchester_palace.htm | archive-date = 15 March 2016 | url = http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/carthalia/uk/uk_Manchester_palace.htm | website = andreas-praefcke.de | publisher = Andreas Praefcke }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Redditch Palace Theatre|Palace]]\n|[[Redditch]]\n|1913\n|399\n|\n|\u00a33.6M refurbishment and extension<ref>{{cite web | title = Grand Theatre & Opera House, Blackpool - A Conservation Statement (Practice Profile) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120204220520/http://www.blackpoolgrand.co.uk/media/4698_Conservation.pdf | archive-date = 4 February 2012 | url = http://www.blackpoolgrand.co.uk/media/4698_Conservation.pdf | website = blackpoolgrand.co.uk | page = 16 | publisher = Blackpool Grand | quote = ''Theatresearch'' was formed in 1985 to undertake the reconstruction of the ''Tyne Theatre & Opera House'' after a devastating fire swept through this Grade I listed theatre... Current work includes a \u00a33.6 million extension of the ''Palace Theatre'', Redditch,... }}</ref>\n|Relatively small, it was used as a Bingo Hall from 1954-1971. Purchased by the council, converted to a theatre<ref>{{cite web | title = The Palace Theatre | url = http://www.sansomehall.co.uk/projects/arts_and_leisure/redditch/redditch_brief.html | website = sansomehall.co.uk | publisher =  Sansome Hall Architects}}</ref>\n|-\n|Coliseum Theatre\n|[[Dublin]]\n|1915\n|3,000\n|\n|Destroyed in the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916\n|With R.F. Bergin\n|-\n|[[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Mogador]]\n|[[Paris]]\n|1919\n|1,800\n|\n|Since the nineties the Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Mogador is also used as a concert hall\n|1913 Sir [[Alfred Butt]] leased an area in Paris. Built after [[World War I]] in the year 1919. The inauguration guests include [[Woodrow Wilson|President Wilson]], in France to negotiate the [[Treaty of Versailles]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Mogador, Paris, France: About the venue | url = https://www.classictic.com/en/paris/th\u00e9\u00e2tre_mogador/54/ | website = classictic.com | publisher = Classictic }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Birmingham Hippodrome]]\n|[[Birmingham]]\n|1899\n|1,817\n|\n|Internal Changes\n|Originally the ''Tower of Varieties and Circus'', it is still a theatre as the ''Birmingham Theatre''<ref>{{cite web | title = Building Stories | url = http://www.birminghamhippodromeheritage.com/ | website = birminghamhippodromeheritage.com | publisher = Birmingham Hippodrome }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Piccadilly Theatre]]\n|[[London]]\n|1928\n|1,400\n|\n|\n|With Edward A. Stone as a private theatre for [[Edward Laurillard]]. Interior decoration by [[Marc-Henri Levy]] and [[Gaston Laverdet]]<ref>{{cite web | title = London: Piccadilly Theatre | url = http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/carthalia/uk/uk_london_piccadilly.htm | website = andreas-praefcke.de | publisher = Andreas Praefcke }}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Phoenix Theatre (London)|Phoenix]]\n|[[London]]\n|1930\n|\n|\n|\n|Designed with [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] and [[Cecil Masey]], with [[Theodore Komisarjevsky]] as Art Director. Hosted the opening production of [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s [[Private Lives]], starring Coward, [[Gertrude Lawrence]], [[Laurence Olivier]] and [[Adrienne Allen]]\n|-\n|[[Saville Theatre|Saville]]\n|[[Covent Garden]]\n|1931\n|1,426\n|\n|Converted to a twin screen cinema in 1970, now a quad screen\n|With Leslie Scott Slaughter. Builders were Messers Gee, Walker and Slater and it was designed by architects T. P. Bennett & Son. Leased by [[Brian Epstein]] in the 60s and is where [[The Beatles]] filmed the videos of \"[[Hello, Goodbye]]\". [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Fats Domino]], [[The Bee Gees]], [[The Who]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Gerry & The Pacemakers]], [[Elton John]], [[Chuck Berry]], [[Harry Secombe]] and [[Leonard Rossiter]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Odeon Covent Garden | url = http://cinematreasures.org/theater/911/ | website = cinematreasures.org | publisher = Cinema Treasures }}</ref>\n|-\n|New Bedford Theatre\n|[[Camden Town|Camden]]\n|1898\n|\n|1\n|Demolished\n|Closed 1950\n|-\n|Capitol Cinema\n|[[Southgate, London]]\n|1935\n|\n|1\n|Demolished September 1982\n|Odeon opened on 16 October 1935 with Edward G. Robinson in \"Passport to Fame\"\n|-\n|Century Cinema\n|[[Kings Cross, London|Kings Cross]]\n|1900\n|\n|1\n|Demolished\n|Closed on 4 April 1968 with [[David McCallum]] in \"The Heroin Gang\" and [[Deborah Kerr]] in \"Eye of the Devil\". Purchased by [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Council]], an extension to the Town Hall was built on the site\n|-\n|Southend Hippodrome / Gaumont Cinema\n|[[Southend-on-Sea]]\n|1909\n|\n|1\n|Demolished 1958\n|Converted into a cinema in 1933, modernised in 1956 and demolished two years later, a supermarket was subsequently built on the site<ref>{{cite web | title = Theatres and Halls in Southend-on-Sea, and Westcliff-on-Sea, Essex: The Hippodrome Theatre, 4 Southchurch Road, Southend-on-Sea  | url =http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/Southend.htm#hipp | website = arthurlloyd.co.uk | publisher = Arthur Lloyd Theatres | access-date = 3 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Gaumont Southend-on-Sea | url = http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/14625/photos | website = cinematreasures.org | publisher = Cinema Treasures | access-date = 3 August 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Olympia Theatre\n|[[Shoreditch]]\n|1889\n|2,170\n|1\n|Demolished 1939\n|Assisted by [[W.G.R. Sprague]]\n|-\n|[[Victoria Theatre, Salford|Victoria Theatre]]\n|[[City of Salford|Salford]]\n|1900\n|3,000\n|1\n|For sale by Palatial Leisure Limited\n|Grade II listed, a bingo hall from 1973, closed 2008<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Victoria Theatre (Salford) | url =http://www.theatrestrust.org.uk/resources/theatres/show/1829-victoria-theatre-salford | website = theatrestrust.org.uk | publisher = [[Theatres Trust]] | date = 2015 |accessdate= 3 April 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Regal Cinema\n|[[Kennington]]\n|1932\n|2,000\n|1\n|Presently boarded up, it is to be converted to flats, 2006\n|With Henry G. Kay, consultant for Duchy of Cornwall estate: Louis de Soissons. Probably Crewe's last project - he died the year it opened. Converted to a cinema in 1961\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Notes ==\n* {{cite book | last = Heathcote | first = Edwin | author-link = Edwin Heathcote | title = Theatre London: an architectural guide | publisher = Ellipsis | location = London | year = 2001 | isbn = 9781841660479 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/theatrelondonarc0000heat }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.corpoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/text.asp?ID=334 Corporation of London page on Bertie Crewe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051218102940/http://www.theatrestrust.org.uk/main/database.html Theatre Trust dBase]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071031065642/http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/timelines20.asp London Theatreland History]\n* [http://www.urban75.org/brixton/history/regal.html Article on conversion of the Regal, Kennington] Crewe's last project\n* [http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/TheatreArchitects.htm Theatre Architects and details of their Theatres]\n*[http://archiveshub.ac.uk/data/gb71-thm/335 Bertie Crewe, architect: architectural drawings of theatres] are held by the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] Theatre and Performance Department.\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crewe, Bertie}}\n[[Category:People from Essex]]\n[[Category:English theatre architects]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Bertie Crewe\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = <!-- if image is smaller than 250px -->\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = {{Birth year|1860}} \n| birth_place           = [[Essex]], England\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|df=y|1937|01|10|1860|01|01}}\n| death_place           = \n| other_names           = \n| nationality           = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| alma_mater            = \n| spouse                = \n| partner               = \n| children              = \n| parents               = \n| awards                = \n| practice              = Associated architectural firm[s]\n| significant_buildings = [[Piccadilly Theatre]], London<br />[[Palace Theatre, Manchester|Palace Theatre]], Manchester<br />[[Shaftesbury Theatre]], London<br />[[Theatre Royal, Bury St Edmunds|Theatre Royal]], Bury St Edmunds\n| significant_projects  = \n| significant_design    = \n| signature             = \n| website               =  <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n{{Portal|Architecture}}\n'''William Robert 'Bertie' Crewe''' (1860, [[Essex]] \u2013 10 January 1937, [[London]]) was one of the leading [[English people|English]] theatre architects in the boom of 1885 to 1915.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Essex and partly trained by [[Frank Matcham]], Crewe and his contemporaries [[W.G.R. Sprague]] and [[Thomas Verity]], were together responsible for the majority \u2013 certainly more than 200 \u2013 of the theatres and variety palaces of the great building boom which took place in Britain between 1885 and 1915, peaking at the turn of the century.<ref>{{cite web | title = New venues and some older ones | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131209124145/http://thelondonseason.com/newvenues.htm | archive-date = 9 December 2013 | url = http://www.thelondonseason.com/newvenues.htm | website = thelondonseason.com | publisher = thelondonseason }}</ref> Crewe became known as one of the most dynamic architects of the 1890s-1900s, specialising entirely in theatres and later cinemas. He also designed the [[Alhambra-Maurice Chevalier|Paris Alhambra]] for [[Thomas Barrasford]], which opened in 1904.\n\nCrewe trained in [[Paris]] and [[London]], where, as a young man, he was a frequent visitor to Frank Matcham's home. Up to the mid-1890s, Crewe collaborated with Sprague, producing the Lincoln Theatre Royal as well as a number of theatres around London. It was after he branched out on his own that he developed what was to become his characteristic Baroque-influenced style. His work around the turn of the century was marked by horizontal balconies tied to ranges of stage boxes and elaborate ornamental features.<ref>{{cite web | title = Theatreland: Architects - Bertie Crewe (d. 1937) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071202131222/http://corpoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/text.asp?ID=334 | archive-date = 2 December 2007 | url = http://www.corpoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/text.asp?ID=334 | website = corpoflondon.gov.uk | publisher = London Metropolitan Archives: Learning Zone }}</ref> [[Cecil Masey]] trained in Crewe's office, working on large theatres and music halls that Crewe designed before the [[First World War]]. Masey's designs include the theatre at [[Stanford Hall, Nottinghamshire]]. In the early 1930s Masey worked for [[Sidney Bernstein, Baron Bernstein|Sidney Bernstein]] on the creation of the Granada cinema circuit, including the Tooting Granada.\n\nCrewe's last project, jointly with Henry G. Kay was the Regal, Kennington Road (opened 17 November 1937) by the Arthur O'Connor circuit. Designed as split theatre-cinema, the Edwardian Kennington Empire would have been in decline by the time of building.<ref>{{cite web | title = GALLERY- October 2004 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081015175359/http://merciacinema.org/gallery1004.htm | archive-date = 15 October 2008 | url = http://www.merciacinema.org.uk/gallery1004.htm | website = merciacinema.org.uk | publisher = Mercia Cinema | date = October 2004 }}</ref>\n\n==After death==\nAfter [[World War II]], many theatres that were not destroyed by bombing were in the way of redevelopment. The building boom of 1885 to 1915 was matched between 1950 and 1975 by theatre demolition. In that 25-year period, 35 theatres were demolished in [[Greater London]] alone.\n\nCrewe's reputation has been re-established over the last 20 years. In 2004, the [[Palace Theatre, Redditch]], (built 1913) completed a \u00a33.7&nbsp;million facelift. A now rare example of Edwardian theatre, it was successful in bidding for a Heritage Lottery Fund grant. Experts believe the Grade II-listed theatre is one of only six examples that can be fully attributed to Bertie Crewe.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Rare theatre revamped to its best |date=23 January 2006 |work=[[BBC News]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/4639830.stm |accessdate= 10 August 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Theatres==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=\"170\" align=center|Theatre\n!width=\"120\" align=center|Location\n!align=center|Build Date\n!align=center|Original Seating Capacity\n!align=center|Screens\n!width=\"110\" align=center|Status\n!align=center|Notes\n|-\n|[[Royal Court Theatre]]\n|[[London]]\n|1888\n|642\n|\n|\n|As sub to [[Walter Emden]]. Next to the Metropolitan railway station (now Sloane Square tube). Reconstructed in 1952 and 1980. An unimpressive auditorium, whose sight-lines could be improved, is the strangely antique setting for modern drama that generally preaches change\n|-\n|[[Theatre Royal, Lincoln|Theatre Royal]]\n|[[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]]\n|1889\n|475\n|\n|Refurbished\n|Reopened after refurbishment 2010<ref>{{cite web | title = Hire venue | url = http://www.lincolntheatreroyal.com/hire.html | website = lincolntheatreroyal.com | publisher = Lincoln Theatre Royal | access-date = 2 August 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160716000215/http://www.lincolntheatreroyal.com/hire.html | archive-date = 16 July 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Olympic Theatre|Olympic]]\n|[[London]]\n|1890\n|\n|\n|Demolished\n|With [[W.G.R. Sprague]]\n|-\n|[[Theatre Royal, Aldershot|Theatre Royal]]\n|[[Aldershot]]\n|16 February 1891\n|700\n|\n|Demolished 1959\n|With [[W. G. R. Sprague]]\n|-\n|Euston Theatre of Varieties\n|[[Euston Road|Euston]]\n|26 December 1900\n|1,310\n|\n|Demolished 1960\n|With Wylson & Long. In use as a Cinema from the mid-1930s to 1950, then renamed the Regent Theatre<ref>{{cite web | title = Cinemas: Cinemas Around the World - Regent Theatre, London UK | url = http://www.cinematour.com/tour/fo/5552.html | website = cinematour.com | publisher = CinemaTour }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Sadler's Wells Theatre|Sadler's Wells]]\n|[[London]]\n|1901\n|\n|\n|Fifth theatre demolished 1996\n|Remodelled\n|-\n|Liverpool Royal Hippodrome\n|[[Liverpool]]\n|1902\n|4,000\n|\n|Demolished 1984\n|The first of the Barrasford halls. The ceiling was painted by Secard, depicting flying cupids upon beds of clouds. From 1931-1967 it was a cinema\n|-\n|Hippodrome\n|[[Brighton]]\n|1902\n|2,000\n|\n|Alterations \n|Frank Matcham converted a skating rink into a circus in 1901. When Thomas Barrasford bought the Hippodrome in October 1902 he called in Crewe to replace the circus ring with raked stalls seating, add boxes where the animal entrances has been and extend the apron with a new orchestra pit in front\n|-\n|[[Lyceum Theatre (London)|Lyceum]]\n|[[London]]\n|1904\n|2,000\n|\n|New Auditorium\n|Built behind Samuel Beazley's original facade and portico\n|-\n|[[Pavilion Theatre (Glasgow)|Pavilion]]\n|[[Glasgow]]\n|1904\n|1.499\n|\n|\n|Now renovated, the theatre is a remarkable original survivor as a commercial theatre. Built for Tom Barrasford.\n|-\n|Palace\n|[[Gorbals]], [[Glasgow]]\n|1904\n|2,000\n|\n|Demolished 1976\n|Cine-variety from 1914, sold to H Maitles. Bingo from 1962\n|-\n|[[Theatre Royal, Bury St Edmunds|Theatre Royal]]\n|[[Bury St Edmunds]]\n|1906\n|\n|\n|Alterations\n|Designed by William Wilkins it opened on 11 October 1819. Redesigned by Crewe in 1906. [[Greene King]] purchased the freehold in 1920, but closed in 1925 and used as a barrel store. Air Vice-Marshal Stanley Vincent raised over \u00a337,000 to restore and re-open the Theatre Royal in 1965, and leased to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] in 1975 on a 999-year lease\n|-\n|Sheffield Hippodrome\n|[[Sheffield]]\n|23 December 1907\n|\n|\n|Demolished 1963<ref>{{cite web | title = Theatres and Halls in Sheffield, South Yorkshire: The Hippodrome Theatre of Varieties, Cambridge Street, Sheffield | url =http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/SheffieldTheatres.htm#hippodrome | website = arthurlloyd.co.uk | publisher = Arthur Lloyd Theatres }}</ref>\n|One of several large Hippodromes opened by Tom Barrasford in direct opposition to [[Oswald Stoll]], then managing director of Moss Theatres\n|-\n|Royal Hippodrome\n|[[Belfast]]\n|1907\n|1,156\n|\n|Demolished, now the site of the modern extension of the [[Grand Opera House, Belfast]] and Fitzwilliam Hotel\n|Became cinema in 1935, Odeon in 1961, and New Victoria Cinema in 1974. Bingo Hall in approx 1987 with occasional theatre use. Closed 1988. Demolished 1997\n|-\n|Nottingham Hippodrome\n|[[Nottingham]]\n|28 September 1908\n|\n|\n|\n|The last Hippodrome to be erected by [[Thomas Barrasford]]\n|-\n|Hippodrome\n|[[Plymouth]]\n|1908\n|\n|\n|Destroyed by bombing and fire in 1941<ref>{{cite web | title = Music halls | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121103083505/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/stephen.pomeroy/local/musichal.pdf | archive-date = 3 November 2012 | url = http://homepage.ntlworld.com/stephen.pomeroy/local/musichal.pdf | format = pdf | website = homepage.ntlworld.com/stephen.pomeroy | publisher = Stephen Pomeroy }}</ref>\n|Remains purchased in May 1958 by Plymouth Council for \u00a34,000, building demolished<ref>{{cite web | title = The Encyclopaedia of Plymouth History: Hippodrome Theatre, Devonport | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060928033833/http://www.plymouthdata.info/TH-Hippodrome.htm | archive-date = 28 September 2006 | url = http://www.plymouthdata.info/TH-Hippodrome.htm | website = plymouthdata.info | publisher = Plymouth Data }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Oldham Palace]]\n|[[Oldham]], [[Greater Manchester]]\n|1908\n|2,380\n|\n|Demolished\n|Built for [[Walter de Frece]], his wife [[Vesta Tilley]] performed on the opening night, and in 1915 it played host to the only pantomime undertaken by [[Gracie Fields]]. Converted to the Odeon Cinema in 1936, it became a three screen in 1974. Unsuccessful in this format, it closed the same year, and remained closed until demolition in 1983. Now the site of a council social services building<ref>{{cite web | title = Theatres and Halls in Oldham, Greater Manchester: The Palace Theatre of Varieties, 140 Union Street, Oldham | url =http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/OldhamTheatres.htm#palace | website = arthurlloyd.co.uk | publisher = Arthur Lloyd Theatres }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hoxton Hall]]\n|[[London]]\n|1909\n|\n|\n|Internal Alterations\n|Built 1863 by James Mortimer, now an Arts Centre\n|-\n|Kingston Empire\n|[[Kingston upon Thames]]\n|1910\n|\n|\n|Converted to a pub and offices in 1956\n|With C J Bourne. Converted to a cinema in 1930, with [[Neon lighting]] was introduced to light the dome, the second theatre in the country to do this (the first being the London Coliseum) Sister theatre to Aldershot Hippodrome.\n|-\n|[[Shaftesbury Theatre|Shaftesbury]]\n|[[London]]\n|26 December 1911\n|\n|\n|changed to the Shaftesbury in 1963\n|Originally Prince's, it opened with the play [[The Three Musketeers]]<ref>{{cite web | title = About us: about the theatre | url = http://www.shaftesburytheatre.com/about-us/about-the-theatre/ | website = shaftesburytheatre.com | publisher = Shaftesbury Theatre }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Peacock Theatre#History|London Opera House / Stoll]]\n|[[London]]\n|1911\n|2,660\n|\n|Demolished 1958, became site for an office block. \n|Designed for [[Oscar Hammerstein I|Oscar Hammerstein]] in 1912, sold to London Opera House Ltd (a newly formed company) in 1913, transformed into a cinema by [[Oswald Stoll]] in 1916. A smaller theatre, The Royalty, built nearby opened 1960. Renamed The Peacock Theatre it presented the [[Paul Raymond (publisher)|Paul Raymond]] revues. Today the Peacock is owned by the [[London School of Economics]], it is a lecture theatre by day and home of [[Sadler's Wells]]' West End programme by night.<ref>{{cite web | title = The Peacock Theatre, Kingsway, London: Formerly - The London Opera House / National Theatre of England / Stoll Picture Theatre / Stoll Theatre / Royalty Theatre  | url = http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/Stoll.htm | website = arthurlloyd.co.uk | publisher = Arthur Lloyd Theatres }}</ref>\n|-\n|Empire Burnley\n|[[Burnley]]\n|1911\n|1,200\n|\n|Auditorium reconstructed\n|Built 1894 under G.B. Rawcliffe. Converted to a cinema in 1938, now a [[Gala Bingo]]\n|-\n|[[The Hippodrome, Aldershot|The Hippodrome]]\n|[[Aldershot]]\n|3 February 1913\n|1,000\n|\n|Demolished 1961\n|Partly refurbished, it reopened fitfully until about 1960\n|-\n|-\n|[[Golders Green Hippodrome]]\n|[[Golders Green]]\n|1913\n|3,000\n|\n|Sold, controversially, to [[El Shaddai International Christian Centre]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Anger as church buys hippodrome | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6506043.stm | work = [[BBC news]] | publisher = [[BBC]] |date = 29 March 2007 | access-date = 28 July 2012 }}</ref>\n|Former home of the [[BBC Concert Orchestra]]<ref>{{cite web | title = The BBC's TV studios in London: Golders Green Hippodrome | url = http://www.tvstudiohistory.co.uk/old%20bbc%20studios.htm#golders%20green | website = tvstudiohistory.co.uk | publisher = An incomplete history of London's television studios | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070603161037/http://www.tvstudiohistory.co.uk/old%20bbc%20studios.htm#golders%20green | archivedate = 3 June 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[The Holme]]\n|[[Regent's Park]]\n|1911\n|Private House\n|\n|\n|First villa to be erected in [[Regent's Park]]. Designed in 1816-18 by [[Decimus Burton]] aged 18 for his father, James Burton. Further wings were added in 1911 by Bertie Crewe. More alterations were carried out in 1935<ref>{{cite web | title = The Holme | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090104172357/http://www.members.lycos.co.uk/Catherine_Slater/Holme.htm | archive-date = 4 January 2009 | url = http://members.lycos.co.uk/Catherine_Slater/Holme.htm | website = members.lycos.co.uk/Catherine_Slater | publisher = Catherine Slater }}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Palace Theatre, Manchester|Palace Theatre]]\n|[[Manchester]]\n|1913\n|1,955\n|\n|Auditorium Reconstructed. Now leased to Ambassador Theatre Group\n|Built in 1891 by [[Alfred Darbyshire]] & F B Smith as the ''Manchester Palace of Varietie''. The first computerised box office system in Europe was installed. Owned by the Palace Theatre Trust<ref>{{cite web | title = Manchester: Palace Theatre | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160315160235/http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/carthalia/uk/uk_manchester_palace.htm | archive-date = 15 March 2016 | url = http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/carthalia/uk/uk_Manchester_palace.htm | website = andreas-praefcke.de | publisher = Andreas Praefcke }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Redditch Palace Theatre|Palace]]\n|[[Redditch]]\n|1913\n|399\n|\n|\u00a33.6M refurbishment and extension<ref>{{cite web | title = Grand Theatre & Opera House, Blackpool - A Conservation Statement (Practice Profile) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120204220520/http://www.blackpoolgrand.co.uk/media/4698_Conservation.pdf | archive-date = 4 February 2012 | url = http://www.blackpoolgrand.co.uk/media/4698_Conservation.pdf | website = blackpoolgrand.co.uk | page = 16 | publisher = Blackpool Grand | quote = ''Theatresearch'' was formed in 1985 to undertake the reconstruction of the ''Tyne Theatre & Opera House'' after a devastating fire swept through this Grade I listed theatre... Current work includes a \u00a33.6 million extension of the ''Palace Theatre'', Redditch,... }}</ref>\n|Relatively small, it was used as a Bingo Hall from 1954-1971. Purchased by the council, converted to a theatre<ref>{{cite web | title = The Palace Theatre | url = http://www.sansomehall.co.uk/projects/arts_and_leisure/redditch/redditch_brief.html | website = sansomehall.co.uk | publisher =  Sansome Hall Architects}}</ref>\n|-\n|Coliseum Theatre\n|[[Dublin]]\n|1915\n|3,000\n|\n|Destroyed in the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916\n|With R.F. Bergin\n|-\n|[[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Mogador]]\n|[[Paris]]\n|1919\n|1,800\n|\n|Since the nineties the Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Mogador is also used as a concert hall\n|1913 Sir [[Alfred Butt]] leased an area in Paris. Built after [[World War I]] in the year 1919. The inauguration guests include [[Woodrow Wilson|President Wilson]], in France to negotiate the [[Treaty of Versailles]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Mogador, Paris, France: About the venue | url = https://www.classictic.com/en/paris/th\u00e9\u00e2tre_mogador/54/ | website = classictic.com | publisher = Classictic }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Birmingham Hippodrome]]\n|[[Birmingham]]\n|1899\n|1,817\n|\n|Internal Changes\n|Originally the ''Tower of Varieties and Circus'', it is still a theatre as the ''Birmingham Theatre''<ref>{{cite web | title = Building Stories | url = http://www.birminghamhippodromeheritage.com/ | website = birminghamhippodromeheritage.com | publisher = Birmingham Hippodrome }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Piccadilly Theatre]]\n|[[London]]\n|1928\n|1,400\n|\n|\n|With Edward A. Stone as a private theatre for [[Edward Laurillard]]. Interior decoration by [[Marc-Henri Levy]] and [[Gaston Laverdet]]<ref>{{cite web | title = London: Piccadilly Theatre | url = http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/carthalia/uk/uk_london_piccadilly.htm | website = andreas-praefcke.de | publisher = Andreas Praefcke }}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Phoenix Theatre (London)|Phoenix]]\n|[[London]]\n|1930\n|\n|\n|\n|Designed with [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] and [[Cecil Masey]], with [[Theodore Komisarjevsky]] as Art Director. Hosted the opening production of [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s [[Private Lives]], starring Coward, [[Gertrude Lawrence]], [[Laurence Olivier]] and [[Adrienne Allen]]\n|-\n|[[Saville Theatre|Saville]]\n|[[Covent Garden]]\n|1931\n|1,426\n|\n|Converted to a twin screen cinema in 1970, now a quad screen\n|With Leslie Scott Slaughter. Builders were Messers Gee, Walker and Slater and it was designed by architects T. P. Bennett & Son. Leased by [[Brian Epstein]] in the 60s and is where [[The Beatles]] filmed the videos of \"[[Hello, Goodbye]]\". [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Fats Domino]], [[The Bee Gees]], [[The Who]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Gerry & The Pacemakers]], [[Elton John]], [[Chuck Berry]], [[Harry Secombe]] and [[Leonard Rossiter]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Odeon Covent Garden | url = http://cinematreasures.org/theater/911/ | website = cinematreasures.org | publisher = Cinema Treasures }}</ref>\n|-\n|New Bedford Theatre\n|[[Camden Town|Camden]]\n|1898\n|\n|1\n|Demolished\n|Closed 1950\n|-\n|Capitol Cinema\n|[[Southgate, London]]\n|1935\n|\n|1\n|Demolished September 1982\n|Odeon opened on 16 October 1935 with Edward G. Robinson in \"Passport to Fame\"\n|-\n|Century Cinema\n|[[Kings Cross, London|Kings Cross]]\n|1900\n|\n|1\n|Demolished\n|Closed on 4 April 1968 with [[David McCallum]] in \"The Heroin Gang\" and [[Deborah Kerr]] in \"Eye of the Devil\". Purchased by [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Council]], an extension to the Town Hall was built on the site\n|-\n|Southend Hippodrome / Gaumont Cinema\n|[[Southend-on-Sea]]\n|1909\n|\n|1\n|Demolished 1958\n|Converted into a cinema in 1933, modernised in 1956 and demolished two years later, a supermarket was subsequently built on the site<ref>{{cite web | title = Theatres and Halls in Southend-on-Sea, and Westcliff-on-Sea, Essex: The Hippodrome Theatre, 4 Southchurch Road, Southend-on-Sea  | url =http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/Southend.htm#hipp | website = arthurlloyd.co.uk | publisher = Arthur Lloyd Theatres | access-date = 3 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Gaumont Southend-on-Sea | url = http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/14625/photos | website = cinematreasures.org | publisher = Cinema Treasures | access-date = 3 August 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Olympia Theatre\n|[[Shoreditch]]\n|1889\n|2,170\n|1\n|Demolished 1939\n|Assisted by [[W.G.R. Sprague]]\n|-\n|[[Victoria Theatre, Salford|Victoria Theatre]]\n|[[City of Salford|Salford]]\n|1900\n|3,000\n|1\n|For sale by Palatial Leisure Limited\n|Grade II listed, a bingo hall from 1973, closed 2008<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Victoria Theatre (Salford) | url =http://www.theatrestrust.org.uk/resources/theatres/show/1829-victoria-theatre-salford | website = theatrestrust.org.uk | publisher = [[Theatres Trust]] | date = 2015 |accessdate= 3 April 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Regal Cinema\n|[[Kennington]]\n|1932\n|2,000\n|1\n|Presently boarded up, it is to be converted to flats, 2006\n|With Henry G. Kay, consultant for Duchy of Cornwall estate: Louis de Soissons. Probably Crewe's last project - he died the year it opened. Converted to a cinema in 1961\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Notes ==\n* {{cite book | last = Heathcote | first = Edwin | author-link = Edwin Heathcote | title = Theatre London: an architectural guide | publisher = Ellipsis | location = London | year = 2001 | isbn = 9781841660479 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/theatrelondonarc0000heat }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.corpoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/text.asp?ID=334 Corporation of London page on Bertie Crewe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051218102940/http://www.theatrestrust.org.uk/main/database.html Theatre Trust dBase]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071031065642/http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/lma_learning/theatreland/timelines20.asp London Theatreland History]\n* [http://www.urban75.org/brixton/history/regal.html Article on conversion of the Regal, Kennington] Crewe's last project\n* [http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/TheatreArchitects.htm Theatre Architects and details of their Theatres]\n*[http://archiveshub.ac.uk/data/gb71-thm/335 Bertie Crewe, architect: architectural drawings of theatres] are held by the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] Theatre and Performance Department.\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crewe, Bertie}}\n[[Category:People from Essex]]\n[[Category:English theatre architects]]\